hree lazy wannabe pirates go back in time to the 17th century, to fight real pirates and become heroes in a battle, to rescue a royal family from an evil tyrant. The three slackers learn that a hero doesn't have to be tall, strong, and handsome to be useful.<ref name=\"RottenTomatoesPWDDA\">{{cite web |title=The Pirates Who Don't Do Anything: A VeggieTales Movie |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/pirates_who_dont_do_anything_a_veggietales_movie |website=Rotten Tomatoes |publisher=Fandango |accessdate=18 August 2019}}</ref>\n* ''The Bob and Larry Movie'' (TBD): The origin story of VeggieTales hosts Bob the Tomato and Larry the Cucumber reveals how they met, how they got their own show, and answers the question how vegetables and fruit talk. This will be the first film in the series to feature humans. According to Phil Vischer, \"Since ''[[Jonah: A VeggieTales Movie]]'' was our [[The Ten Commandments (1956 film)|''The'' ''Ten Commandments,'']] ''The Bob and Larry Movie'' would be our ''[[Toy Story (franchise)|Toy Story]].''<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://philvischer.com/news/what-happened-to-big-idea-part-1/|title=What Happened to Big Idea? (Part 1) - Phil Vischer - Official Blog of VeggieTales Creator|date=2004-11-15|website=Phil Vischer|access-date=2019-03-17}}</ref>''\"'' The Bob and Larry Movie was originally planned to be the second VeggieTales movie with a released date in late 2005. It was placed into production in early 2002, toward the end of production of ''Jonah: A VeggieTales Movie'' (2002).<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2008/januaryweb-only/philvischer.html|title=The More You Preach, the Fewer You Reach|last=Hertz|first=by Todd|website=ChristianityToday.com|access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref> However, Big Idea Productions fell into bankruptcy in late 2002 and the film was placed on hiatus because it was deemed too expensive. As a result, [[Phil Vischer]] wrote ''[[The Pirates Who Don't Do Anything: A VeggieTales Movie]]'' to replace this movie. In 2008, it was considered to be the sequel to ''The Pirates who Don't Do Anything: A VeggieTales Movie'', but talks had stalled after the 2008 recession had led to the bankruptcy of VeggieTales owner ''Entertainment Rights'' and ''Classic Media.'' According to Phil Vischer in 2018, \"I have a copy of ''The Bob and Larry'' script on my laptop, but probably won't release it because it is technically owned by Universal and DreamWorks.\" \"It will hopefully be produced in the near future.\"<ref name=\"auto1\" />\n*''Untitled VeggieTales Movie'' (TBD): On March 28, 2019, Vischer and Nawrocki announced at the National Religious Broadcast Convention that they were developing a screenplay with Universal Studios for a new Veggietales movie. Universal Studios wants the film to be a bible story similar to ''Jonah: A Veggietales Movie'', so the film will not be ''The Bob and Larry Movie''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/philvischer/status/1241348735386427393|title=Twitter|website=mobile.twitter.com|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> The release date has not been announced.<ref name=\":14\">{{cite web |title=Phil Vischer on Twitter: \"New TV series in production with TBN. New movie in development at Universal. I'm involved in both!\" |url=https://twitter.com/philvischer/status/1111372778039476230 |website=Twitter}}{{Primary source inline|date=April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Stage production===\n''VeggieTales Live'' is a series of stage shows based on the ''VeggieTales'' videos. The first stage series was part of a two-year agreement with [[iHeartMedia|Clear Channel]] in 2002.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hettrick|first1=Scott|title='VeggieTales' hit the stage|url=https://variety.com/2001/digital/features/veggietales-hit-the-stage-1117802949/|accessdate=October 16, 2017|work=Variety|date=July 18, 2001}}</ref> Six versions of the shows have been staged. The shows have toured across the U.S. and at theme parks including [[Dollywood]] and [[Silver Dollar City]].<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/veggietales-live-happy-birthday-bob--larry-tour-returns-this-fall-with-first-time-show-dates-for-west-coast-221632901.html |title=VeggieTales Live! Happy Birthday Bob & Larry Tour Returns This Fall With First-Time Show Dates For West Coast |author=Big Idea Entertainment|date=August 29, 2013 |agency=PR Newswire |accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Video games===\nBig Idea, and its successors, have released ''VeggieTales'' themed games on various platforms including PC, Macintosh, iOS, and Android. Applications include games revolving around specific ''VeggieTales'' episodes (such as the PlayStation 2 release of ''LarryBoy and the Bad Apple'') to new content revolving around various ''VeggieTales'' characters.\n\n{{Infobox VG series\n| title              = VeggieTales\n| image              = VeggieTales 2014 logo.png\n| caption            = Logo (as of August 2014)\n| developer          = {{Collapsible list\n  |framestyle=border:none; padding:0;\n  |title=Various, including\n  |1=[[Papaya Studio]] |2=DC Studios |3=Fingerprint Network |4=[[Digital Praise]]}}\n| genre              = [[Christian video game|Christian]]<br/>[[Adventure game|Adventure]]<br/>[[Educational video game|Edutainment]]\n| platforms          = [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]], [[Game Boy Advance]], [[PlayStation 2]], [[Mac OS X]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[VideoNow]]\n| creator            = [[Big Idea Entertainment]]\n| first release version  = ''The Mystery of Veggie Island''\n| first release date     = September 3, 2002\n| latest release version = ''Step-by-Story presents: Larry's Missing Music''\n| latest release date    = March 19, 2012\n}}\n\n====Macintosh/PC====\n#''The Mystery of Veggie Island'' (September 15, 2002)<ref name=\"VG\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hive4media.com/news/html/Product_article.cfm?article_id=2625|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020305134828/http://www.hive4media.com:80/news/html/Product_article.cfm?article_id=2625|title=Veggie Tales Headed for CD-ROM|website=[[hive4media.com]]|archivedate=March 5, 2002|date=February 19, 2002|accessdate=September 21, 2019}}</ref>\n#''Veggie Carnival'' (October 15, 2002)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/VeggieTales-Veggie-Carnival-Jewel-Case-Pc/dp/B00006JK51/ref=sr_1_8?s=videogames&ie=UTF8&qid=1326816810&sr=1-8 |title=VeggieTales: Veggie Carnival (Jewel Case) \u2013 PC: Video Games |accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n#''Jonah: A VeggieTales Game'' (November 2002)<ref name=\"VG\"/>\n#''VeggieTales Creativity City'' (February 4, 2003)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Veggie-Tales-Creativity-City-PC-Game/dp/B000098XNE/ref=sr_1_2?s=videogames&ie=UTF8&qid=1326816810&sr=1-2 |title=Veggie Tales Creativity City (PC Game): Video Games |accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n#''Minnesota Cuke and the Coconut Apes'' (September 30, 2003)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Veggie-Tales-Minnesota-Coconut-Jewel-Pc/dp/B0002BJSLE/ref=pd_sim_sbs_vg_3 |title=Veggie Tales: Minnesota Cuke and the Coconut Apes (Jewel Case): Video Games |accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n#''VeggieTales Super Silly Fun!'' (December 15, 2005)<ref>{{cite web|author=ValuSoft |url=https://www.amazon.com/Veggie-Tales-Super-Silly-Cd-rom-PC/dp/B001E91ELA/ref=sr_1_12?s=videogames&ie=UTF8&qid=1326816810&sr=1-12 |title=Veggie Tales Super Silly Fun! Cd-rom: Video Games |date=August 13, 2008 |accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n#''VeggieTales Dance Dance Dance'' (December 2006)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Bigideass-Veggietales-Dance-Pad-Game/dp/B001D6K2B2|title=Bigideas's Veggietales Dance Dance Dance Dance Pad Game: Video Games|access-date=April 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====PlayStation 2 and Game Boy Advance games====\n#''[[LarryBoy and the Bad Apple]]'' (August 1, 2006)<ref name=\":11\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Veggietales-Larry-Boy-Apple-Playstation-2/dp/B000F7CECU/ref=sr_1_1?s=videogames&ie=UTF8&qid=1326816810&sr=1-1 |title=Veggietales: Larry Boy and the Bad Apple \u2013 PlayStation 2: Big Idea: Video Games |accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====iOS====\n#\"Step-by-Story presents: The Goofy Gift\" (December 28, 2011)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/step-by-story-veggietales/id492022025?ls=1&mt=8 |title=iTunes Store |publisher=iTunes Store |accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n#\"VeggieTales Spotisodes Collection\" (February 7, 2012)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/veggietales-spotisode-collection/id499459063?mt=8 |title=Watch and Find \u2013 VeggieTales Games and Video Clips \u2013 A Fingerprint Network App on the App Store on iTunes |publisher=iTunes Store |date=December 7, 2013 |accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n#\"Step-by-Story presents: Larry's Missing Music\" (March 19, 2012)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/step-by-story-veggietales/id509109422?mt=8 |title=iTunes Store |publisher=iTunes Store |accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Android====\n#\"Step-by-Story presents: The Goofy Gift\" (December 28, 2011)\n#\"VeggieTales Spotisodes Collection\" (February 7, 2012)\n#\"Step-by-Story presents: Larry's Missing Music\" (March 19, 2012)\n\n====Other systems====\n''VeggieTales'' games shipped pre-bundled in the  [[Game Wave Family Entertainment System]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pearson|first1=Jordan|title=Christians Loved Canada's Failed Video Game Console|url=https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/3k5d58/christians-loved-canadas-failed-video-game-console-game-wave|accessdate=December 26, 2017|work=Motherboard|date=December 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Music and audio CDs===\n{{main|List of VeggieTales albums}}\n\nThere have been over 45 musical albums released that tie into either ''VeggieTales'' characters or videos. While some of the albums are merely compilations of songs from the various videos (including albums entitled ''Larry-Boy Soundtrack'', ''[[A Very Veggie Easter]]'', and ''25 Favorite Very VeggieTunes''), others contain completely original content such as stories or songs performed by Phil Vischer, Mike Nawrocki, and the other ''VeggieTales'' voice talent (such as ''Bob and Larry's Campfire Songs'', ''Christian Hit Music'', and ''Bob and Larry Sing the 80's'').\n\n===Merchandise===\nOn February 10, 2011, Big Idea Entertainment announced several new product promotions, including partnerships with [[Chick-fil-A]] (kids meal promotions), American Puzzle Company (wooden puzzles and trains), CTI Industries (mylar and latex balloons), Tabbies (index tabs, stickers, temporary tattoos and wall clings), Victory Designs (children's guitars), and Zoobies (plush pillows and blankets).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.licensemag.com/license-global/big-idea-grows-veggietales-brand |title=Big Idea Grows VeggieTales Brand |publisher=License! Global |date=February 10, 2011 |accessdate=October 9, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==== Books and Comics ====\n{{Main|List of VeggieTales books}}\nIn June 2014, B&H Kids announced plans to produce a ''VeggieTales'' comic with [[Big Idea Productions]] and [[DreamWorks Animation]].<ref>{{cite press release|author1=B&H Kids|title=B&H Kids and Veggitales Team to Create New Line of Comic Books|url=http://www.bhpublishinggroup.com/press-release/bh-kids-and-veggietales-team-to-create-a-new-line-of-comic-books|publisher=B&H Publishing Group|accessdate=January 22, 2017|date=June 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{official website|http://www.veggietales.com/ }}\n*[http://www.ceganmo.com/2008/11/veggietales.html VeggieTales] at CEGAnMo.com\n*{{IMDb title|id=0865856|title=VeggieTales}}\n{{VeggieTales}}\n{{DreamWorks Animation}}{{Netflix original ended series}}{{TBN}}{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Veggietales}}\n[[Category:VeggieTales| ]]\n[[Category:1990s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:1993 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2000s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American children's television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American children's television series]]\n[[Category:2015 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:American animated television programs featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated musical television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:American computer-animated television series]]\n[[Category:Animated film series]]\n[[Category:American preschool education television series]]\n[[Category:Big Idea Entertainment television series]]\n[[Category:Christian animation]]\n[[Category:Christian children's television series]]\n[[Category:DreamWorks Classics]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:Qubo]]\n[[Category:Fruit and vegetable characters]]\n[[Category:Internet memes]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American Christian animated series}}\n{{pp-move|small=yes}}\n{{split|1=VeggieTales (franchise)|2=VeggieTales (1993 video series)|date=May 2019|discuss=Talk:VeggieTales#Title change (long overdue) and making the original video series a separate article}}\n{{tone|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox media franchise\n| website = https://www.veggietales.com\n| title = VeggieTales\n| image = VeggieTales 2014 logo.png\n| caption = ''VeggieTales'' Logo (2014\u2013present)\n| creator = {{Unbulleted list|[[Phil Vischer]]|[[Mike Nawrocki]]}}\n| origin = VeggieTales (1993 video series)\n| owner = {{Unbulleted list|[[Big Idea Entertainment]]|([[DreamWorks Classics]])|([[DreamWorks Animation]])|([[NBCUniversal]])|([[Comcast]])}}\n| italic_title = force\n| books = {{Main|List of VeggieTales books}}\n| comics = {{Unbulleted list|''VeggieTales SuperComics''}}\n| films = {{Unbulleted list|''[[Jonah: A VeggieTales Movie]]'' (2002)|''[[The Pirates Who Don't Do Anything: A VeggieTales Movie]]'' (2008)}}\n| atv = {{Unbulleted list|''VeggieTales'' (1993\u2013present)|''[[Larryboy: The Cartoon Adventures]]'' (2002\u201303)| ''VeggieTales on TV!'' (2006\u20132009)|''[[VeggieTales in the House]]'' (2014\u201316)|''[[VeggieTales in the City]]'' (2017)|''[[The VeggieTales Show]]'' (2019\u2013present)}}\n| tv_specials = {{Unbulleted list|''VeggieTales Christmas Spectacular'' (1998\u20132000)|''The Star of Christmas'' (2002)}}\n| dtv = {{Main|List of VeggieTales videos}}\n| games = {{Unbulleted list|3D Trading Cards - 4 PK|Veggie Checkers|Game Wave DVD Game: Letter Zap|Game Wave DVD Game: Sudoku Challenge|Tic Tac Twice Board Game|Toss Across Game|Water Wow}}\n| vgs = {{Unbulleted list|The Mystery of Veggie Island (September 3, 2002)|Veggie Carnival (October 15, 2002)|Jonah: A VeggieTales Game (October 15, 2002)|VeggieTales Creativity City (February 4, 2003)|Minnesota Cuke and the Coconut Apes (September 30, 2003)|VeggieTales Super Silly Fun! (December 15, 2005)|VeggieTales Dance Dance Dance (December 2006)|LarryBoy and the Bad Apple (August 1, 2006)|\"Step-by-Story presents: The Goofy Gift\" (December 28, 2011)|\"VeggieTales Spotisodes Collection\" (February 7, 2012)|\"Step-by-Story presents: Larry's Missing Music\" (March 19, 2012)}}\n| soundtracks = {{Main|List of VeggieTales albums}}\n| music = {{Main|List of VeggieTales albums}}\n| toys = {{Unbulleted list|Bob Bath Toy|God's Creation: Leopard|God's Creation: Panda|God's Creation: Tiger|Princess Petunia Magnetic Dress Up Doll|Slushie Bath Toy}}\n}}\n'''''VeggieTales''''' is an American Christian franchise of children's [[computer animation|computer animated]] [[Television|home entertainment]] series (videos, DVDs, and Blu-rays), television shows, feature films, web series, books, games and albums. Sarcastic, limbless, talking fruit and vegetable characters feature in videos that retell [[Bible stories]] and parody mainstream [[Popular culture|pop culture]].<ref name=\":8\" /> Each episode presents a life lesson through a biblical worldview, Christian history and concepts. The lessons include dealing with bullies, handling peer pressure, forgiving others, fighting temptation, handling fear, listening to parents, having self-esteem and being compassionate. It was created by [[Phil Vischer]] and [[Mike Nawrocki]], who both perform many of the characters\u2019 voices.<ref name=\"Wrap Emmys\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/daytime-emmy-awards-2015-complete-winners-list/|title=Daytime Emmy Awards 2015: Complete Winners List|last=Staff|first=Wrap|date=April 27, 2015|website=TheWrap|access-date=March 17, 2019}}</ref> it was one of the earliest computer animated franchises, predating both [[ReBoot]] and [[Toy Story (franchise)|Toy Story]].\n\nThe series is hosted by Bob the Tomato and Larry the Cucumber. Other main cast members include Junior Asparagus, Archibald Asparagus, Petunia Rhubarb, Mr. Lunt, Mr. Nezzer, Pa Grape, Laura Carrot, Madame Blueberry, the French Peas, and Jimmy and Jerry Gourd. The majority of the shows feature ''[[Silly Songs with Larry]]'', \"the part of the show where Larry comes out to sing a silly song\".<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nVeggieTales has been nominated for several [[Emmy Award]]s, [[Annie Award]]s, [[Movieguide Awards]], [[Golden Reel Award (Motion Picture Sound Editors)|Golden Reel Award]]s, [[Chicago International Film Festival|Chicago Film Festival Awards]], [[Parents' Choice Award]]s, World Animation Celebration Awards, and [[GMA Dove Award]]s.<ref name=\"Wrap Emmys\" /> It is distinguished as the most successful faith-based Christian children's franchise of all time.<ref name=\"tbn.org\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tbn.org/press-releases/tbn-and-big-idea-content-group-partner-produce-all-new-%E2%80%9Cveggietales%E2%80%9D-episodes|title=TBN and Big Idea Content Group Partner to Produce All-New \"VeggieTales\" Episodes|date=2019-04-04|website=TBN|language=en|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> In 1999 and 2000, near the height of the series' popularity, the videos outsold every other kids property in the world to date, including [[Pok\u00e9mon]], [[Scooby-Doo]], and [[Barney & Friends|Barney the Dinosaur]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://faithasawayoflife.typepad.com/blog/2005/03/veggie_tales_fa.html|title=Veggie Tales Faith as a Way of Life|website=faithasawayoflife|access-date=2019-08-09}}</ref> ''VeggieTales'' has also sold over 16&nbsp;million books, 7&nbsp;million [[Compact disc|music CDs]], and 235&nbsp;million [[Streaming media|music streams]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tbn.org/press-releases/tbn-and-big-idea-content-group-partner-produce-all-new-%E2%80%9Cveggietales%E2%80%9D-episodes|title=TBN and Big Idea Content Group Partner to Produce All-New \"VeggieTales\" Episodes|date=2019-04-04|website=TBN|access-date=2019-08-08}}</ref> \n\nOriginally released in [[direct-to-video]] format, Veggietales debuted on December 21, 1993 and released 58 original episodes on video, DVD, and Blu-ray until March 3, 2015. Big Idea Entertainment has released two theatrical feature films, ''[[Jonah: A VeggieTales Movie]]'' (2002) in association with [[Lionsgate]] and ''[[The Pirates Who Don't Do Anything: A VeggieTales Movie]]'' (2008) in association with [[Universal Pictures|Universal Studios]],<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gospelmusic.org/industry-update-big-ideas-leslie-ferrell-talks-women-in-leadership/|title=INDUSTRY UPDATE: Big Idea's Leslie Ferrell Talks Women in Leadership|last=GMA|date=July 9, 2015|website=The Gospel Music Association|access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> that both rank in the top ten best [[box office]] performing [[Christian film industry|faith based films]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factsandtrends.net/2018/03/14/top-20-christian-movies-time/|title=Top 20 Christian Movies of All Time|date=2018-03-14|website=Facts & Trends|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> From 2002 to 2003, Big Idea created a short running spin-off called ''[[Larryboy: The Cartoon Adventures]]''.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite news|last1=Daley|first1=Ashley|title=Duo creative at Big Idea|url=https://variety.com/2002/scene/markets-festivals/duo-creative-at-big-idea-1117868594/|accessdate=May 20, 2016|work=Variety|date=June 17, 2002}}</ref>\n\nFor four seasons from September 9, 2006 to September 7, 2009, a series known as ''VeggieTales on TV!'' appeared on [[NBC]], [[Telemundo]], and [[Ion Television|ION TV]] as part of the [[Qubo]] [[children's programming]] block.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.veggietales.com/about_bigidea_entertainment/|title=About Big Idea Entertainment|website=veggietales.com|access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> ''Veggietales on TV!'' was the most watched Saturday morning program on television from 2006 to 2008.<ref name=\"today\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.today.com/popculture/veggietales-stirs-religious-controversy-wbna14960737|title='VeggieTales' stirs up a religious controversy|website=TODAY.com|access-date=2019-08-09}}</ref> With an average of 430,000 children watching each weekend from 2006 to 2007, the first two seasons of ''VeggieTales on TV!'' allowed NBC to see a 16% ratings jump, its biggest in Saturday morning children's programming since 2003.<ref name=\"today\"/> The first and last segments on ''Veggietales on TV!'' episodes featured entirely new animated segments that took place at Bob the Tomato's house, while the middle segments showcased shorts from the original video series that related in subject to the newly animated segments. On November 3, 2012, the show began running on the [[Trinity Broadcasting Network]] (TBN) as well as its children's network [[Smile (TV network)|Smile]], where it currently continues to air the original videos (in a repackaged and edited format).\n\nIn 2009, [[Netflix]] made numerous VeggieTales videos (in their uncut, original formats) and the two feature films available via their [[video streaming]] service. In November 2014, the original VeggieTales video series spun off into the Netflix series ''[[VeggieTales in the House]]'', produced by [[DreamWorks Animation Television]].<ref name=\"tbn.org\"/> VeggieTales in the House featured the characters venturing off the kitchen countertop from the original series and exploring new areas of the vegetable and fruit inhabited house.<ref>{{Citation|title=VeggieTales in the House (TV Series 2014\u20132016) - IMDb|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3692064/|access-date=2019-08-09}}</ref> The series ran for four seasons from 2014 to 2016 and included 52 episodes. In February 2017, Veggietales in the House spun off into ''[[VeggieTales in the City]]'' in which the characters ventured off to live in the city area of the house. VeggieTales in the City ran on Netflix<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christiantoday.com/article/brand-new-veggietales-brings-godly-vegetables-back-to-netflix-exclusive-clips/104975.htm|title=Brand New VeggieTales Brings Godly Vegetables Back To Netflix: Exclusive Clips|first=Joseph Hartropp Thu 23 February 2017 16:00|last=GMT|website=christiantoday.com|accessdate=March 17, 2019}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted ([[Special:Diff/909993545]]) by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite at [[Special:Permalink/909989613]] cite No. 11 - please verify the cite's accuracy and remove this {verify source} template. [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref> for two seasons and consisted of 26 episodes.\n\nFrom 1993 to 2004, VeggieTales videos were produced in [[Chicago|Chicago, Illinois]]. After Big Idea Production fell into bankruptcy in 2003, VeggieTales was purchased by [[DreamWorks Classics|Classic Media]] in 2004 and production moved to [[Nashville, Tennessee]]. In 2012, [[DreamWorks Animation]] purchased Classic Media.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\"CTDWBuysOwner\">{{cite web|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/gleanings/2012/august/dreamworks-buys-veggietaless-owner.html|title=DreamWorks Buys VeggieTales's Owner &#124; Gleanings|date=August 5, 2012|publisher=ChristianityToday.com|accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref> When DreamWorks launched production on the [[Netflix]] series [[VeggieTales in the House]] in 2013, production was split between studios in Nashville, Chicago, and [[Glendale, California]].<ref name=\":13\" /> In 2016, [[Comcast]]'s [[NBCUniversal]] bought DreamWorks Animation and since then, Universal Studios currently owns the rights to VeggieTales.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/biz/news/dreamworks-animation-3-8-billion-nbcuniversal-comcast-1201762634/|title=NBCUniversal to Acquire DreamWorks Animation for $3.8 Billion|last=Littleton|first=Brent Lang,Cynthia|last2=Lang|first2=Brent|date=2016-04-28|website=Variety|access-date=2019-08-08|last3=Littleton|first3=Cynthia}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, [[NBCUniversal|Universal Studios]] greenlit a new series, ''[[The VeggieTales Show]]'', which aired on the [[Trinity Broadcasting Network]] and [[Smile (TV network)|Smile]] on October 22, 2019 .<ref>{{Citation|title=VeggieTales is Back: Brand New VeggieTales Show Trailer|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v6RF9XIGyhg|access-date=2019-08-08}}</ref> On March 28, 2019, Vischer announced that he, Nawrocki, and Universal Studios were developing a screenplay for a new VeggieTales theatrical movie.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/philvischer/status/1111372778039476230|title=Twitter|publisher=Twitter|access-date=2019-08-09}}</ref>\n\nBig Idea has also published several ''VeggieTales'' books and music CDs, as well as branded items such as toys, clothing, and garden seeds for vegetables, fruits and flowers.<ref name=\"tbn.org\"/>\n\n==Background==\n===History===\n''VeggieTales'' was created by Phil Vischer and Mike Nawrocki through their company Big Idea Productions. Their aim was to produce children's videos which conveyed Christian moral themes and taught Biblical values and lessons. The animated feature involved stories told by a group of recurring fruit and vegetable characters who lived on a kitchen countertop. The program was offered in the direct-to-video market, with the first 30-minute program, ''[[Where's God When I'm S-Scared?]],'' released in December 1993.<ref name=\"MeMyselfBob\">{{cite book|last1=Vischer|first1=Phil|title=Me, Myself, & Bob: A True Story About God, Dreams, and Talking Vegetables|date=2008|publisher=T. Nelson|location=Nashville, Tenn.|isbn=978-1595551221}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=VeggieTales award-winning musical composer Kurt Heinecke to visit Wallace State on April 21 as part of Arts in April festivities|url=http://news.wallacestate.edu/2014/04/15/veggietales-award-winning-musical-composer-kurt-heinecke-to-visit-wallace-state-on-april-21-as-part-of-arts-in-april-festivities/|publisher=Wallace State News|date=April 15, 2014|accessdate=June 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe idea for ''VeggieTales'' was conceived in the early 1990s when Vischer was testing animation software to use as a medium for children's videos.<ref name=\"MeMyselfBob\" /> Due to the limitations of [[Softimage 3D|Softimage Creative Environment]] at the time, he decided to avoid the technical production hurdle of designing characters with arms, legs, hair, and clothes. His first animation model was an [[anthropomorphic]] candy bar. When his wife suggested that parents might prefer a hero who promoted [[healthy diet|healthier eating habit]]s, he began designing the characters based on fruits and vegetables. The cast of voice actors of the early VeggieTales videos predominantly came from friends of Phil Vischer such as Dan Anderson ([[List of VeggieTales characters#Dad and Mom Asparagus|Dad Asparagus]]) and Jim Poole ([[List of VeggieTales characters#Scooter|Scooter the Carrot]]) who collaborated with Vischer on dramas at their local church.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Vischer|first1=Phil|title=Episode 200: THE BIG 2-0-0!|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zzD_J03KcuY|via=YouTube|accessdate=January 22, 2017|date=May 10, 2016}}</ref> Softimage 3D was used for further episodes until 1999 when it was replaced with [[Autodesk Maya|Maya]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Evans|first1=Noell Wolfgram|title=VeggieTales: What's the Big Idea?|url=http://www.digitalmediafx.com/Features/bigideap.html|accessdate=January 6, 2018|work=Digital Media FX|year=2003}}</ref>\n\n[[Lyrick Studios]] sued Big Idea in January 2002 claiming Big Idea \"abruptly walked away\" from a 1997 deal to manufacture and distribute VeggieTales merchandise.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/dallas/stories/2002/01/21/story1.html|title=Lawsuit over verbal pact pits Lyrick Studios, VeggieTales|last=Patrick|first=Stephanie|work=[[Dallas Business Journal]]|date=January 20, 2002|accessdate=October 24, 2019}}</ref> Big Idea, which had no written contract, made a new deal with [[Warner Home Video]]. In April 2003, a jury in Texas ruled Big Idea must pay $11 million to Lyrick (which was overturned in 2005 on appeal).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2003/julyweb-only/10.18.html|title=Big Idea Loses Suit|last=Hertz|first=Todd|work=[[Christianity Today]]|date=July 1, 2003|accessdate=October 24, 2019}}</ref> Vischer lost control over VeggieTales in 2004<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/veggie-tales-christian-children-show-bible-stories|title='VeggieTales' creator Phil Vischer says show's comeback has 'classic' feel with new Bible stories|last=Parke|first=Caleb|work=[[Fox News]]|date=October 22, 2019|accessdate=October 24, 2019}}</ref> and various owners de-emphasized Christian messages.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/10/20/771314561/tis-in-season-a-harvest-of-new-veggietales-in-time-for-christmas|title='Tis In Season: A Harvest Of New VeggieTales, In Time For Christmas|last=Hale|first=Lee|work=[[NPR]]|via=[[KUER-FM]]|date=October 20, 2019|accessdate=October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Show format===\nThe videos generally follow a standard format where a moral issue is posited in the opening countertop sequence, either through a viewer question or an issue brought up by Bob or Larry, followed by one or more \"films\" that address the issue, with a ''Silly Song'' in the middle. The ''Silly Songs'' are generally introduced with a [[title card]] and a [[voice-over]] saying, \"And now it's time for Silly Songs with Larry, the part of the show where Larry comes out and sings a silly song.\" Some ''Silly Songs'' have alternate titles, such as \"Love Songs with Mr. Lunt,\" or \"Ukulele Karaoke with Bob,\" where another character sings the song instead.<ref>{{Citation|last=VeggieTales Official|title=VeggieTales {{!}} Monkey Silly Song {{!}} Silly Songs With Larry {{!}} Kids Cartoon {{!}} Kids Videos {{!}} Kids Movies|date=April 30, 2019|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Pv9YwNGUSSU|access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> The ''Silly Song'', if one appears, is usually in the middle of the program, often at a [[cliffhanger]] moment or in between two stories (although the LarryBoy videos, in particular, often lack this segment, with the exception of ''League of Incredible Vegetables''). Each video ends with this program's signature sign-off: \"Remember kids, God made you special and He loves you very much.\"<ref>{{Citation|last=Ultrocraze|title=From Veggietales- God made you special!|date=December 17, 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U7mJkmDfuj0|access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===VeggieTales premieres on TV===\n\"The Toy that Saved Christmas\" was broadcast on [[Pax TV]] on December 19, 1998.<ref name=\":8\">{{cite news|last1=Reber|first1=Deborah|title=All in the Family: Rated \"G\" Animated Programming|url=https://www.awn.com/animationworld/all-family-rated-g-animated-programming|accessdate=January 7, 2018|work=Animation World Network|date=December 1, 1998}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{cite news|last1=Mattingly|first1=Terry|title=Bible animators dish out a helping of VeggieTales|work=[[The Washington Times]]|date=November 21, 1998|page=D8|quote=Meanwhile, Mr. Vischer is taking calls from movie studios and cable bosses. The Veggies make their TV debut Dec. 19 in a prime-time Pax TV special built around the company's \"The Toy that Saved Christmas\" video.}}</ref> Another Christmas video, \"The Star of Christmas\", aired on over 260 public television stations in December 2002.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Godfrey|first1=Leigh|title=VeggieTales Star in Their Public Television Debut|url=https://www.awn.com/news/veggietales-star-their-public-television-debut|accessdate=January 7, 2018|work=Animation World Network|date=December 10, 2002}}</ref>\n\n===NBC version (2006)===\nFor four seasons, ''VeggieTales on TV!'' ran on [[NBC]], [[Telemundo]], and [[Ion Television|ION TV]] as part of the [[Qubo]] [[children's programming]] block from 2006 to 2009.<ref name=\"off-and-running\">{{Cite web|url=https://philvischer.com/news/bob-and-larry-are-off-and-running/|title=Bob and Larry Are Off and Running! - Phil Vischer - Official Blog of VeggieTales Creator|date=2006-09-15|website=Phil Vischer|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> The television show altered the general format by opening at the front gate of [[Bob the Tomato]]'s house. Bob, [[Larry the Cucumber]], and other Veggie characters then sing the show's theme song as they hop to Bob's front door. The theme song ends with a character making a random comment, such as Pa Grape commenting on Archibald's new sweater. Bob and Larry then wait for the mailman, Jimmy Gourd, to deliver a letter. When Jimmy comes, he happily sings his Mail Song, which Bob and Larry both find tedious. Similar to the opening counter top sequence of the ''VeggieTales'' videos, Bob and Larry read the letter and the cast tries to decide how to solve the viewer's problem through one of three regular segments: Archibald reads a story from his Big Book of Oddities, Pa Grape shows an old film, or Mr. Lunt appears with his stick puppet, Paco the Storytelling Mule, and tells a story. The result always proves disastrous, as the story or film makes no sense. Bob and Larry then intervene with a story from a VeggieTales video. The show ends with Bob and Larry wrapping things up by reiterating the story's lesson and thanking the kids for coming to his house. NBC episodes end with characters bidding the audience a simple \"Good-bye\".\n\nAccording to the [[Los Angeles Times]], \"Veggietales has been very successful for NBC in a Saturday morning time slot that has traditionally been difficult for the networks. Thanks to Bob the Tomato and Larry the Cucumber, NBC saw its biggest ratings jump in Saturday morning children's programming since 2003.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2006-sep-23-fi-veggies23-story.html|title=NBC Issues New Explanation for 'VeggieTales' Cuts|date=2006-09-23|website=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> Ratings on NBC's Saturday morning program had grown from an average [[Nielsen ratings|Nielsen Rating]] of 0.5 between 2003 and 2005 to an average [[Nielsen ratings|Nielsen Rating]] of 0.95 between 2006 and 2008 thanks to ''Veggietales on TV!''.<ref name=\"off-and-running\" /> ''Veggietales on TV!'' was the most watched Saturday morning program on television from 2006 to 2008, with an average of 430,000 children watching each weekend.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.today.com/popculture/veggietales-stirs-religious-controversy-wbna14960737|title=\u2018VeggieTales\u2019 stirs up a religious controversy|website=TODAY.com|language=en|access-date=2019-08-09}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted ([[Special:Diff/910168749]]) by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite at [[Special:Permalink/910155484]] cite No. 10 - please verify the cite's accuracy and remove this {verify source} template. [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref>\n\nWhen [[NBC]] aired the first few episodes of the first season in September 2006,<ref>{{cite web|last1=DeMott|first1=Rick|title=Qubo To Launch on NBC, Telemundo & The i Network This September|url=http://www.awn.com/news/qubo-launch-nbc-telemundo-i-network-september|accessdate=May 20, 2016|publisher=Animation World Network|date=August 24, 2006}}</ref> it edited the shows to remove religious messages, including references to [[God]]. The original sign-off message--\"Remember kids, God made you special and He loves you very much!\"\u2014became \"Thanks for coming to my house today, kids. See you next week! Good-bye!\" The changes were made at the request of the network's [[standards and practices]] department to enforce compliance with network policies regarding religious neutrality. The original dialogue remained viewable by users of the network's closed-caption feature.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wesbury|first1=Joe|title=NBC chooses family values over spiritual values in VeggieTales Saturday morning line-up|url=http://www.tciarchive.org/2596.article|publisher=The Muslim Index|accessdate=January 22, 2017|date=September 28, 2006}}</ref>\n\nThe conservative watch group [[Parents Television Council]] complained to NBC about the changes.<ref name=FOXStirControversy>{{cite web|title=Talking Veggies Stir Controversy at NBC|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,215266,00.html|agency=Associated Press|publisher=Fox News Channel|accessdate=January 22, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629071019/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,215266,00.html|archivedate=June 29, 2011|date=September 22, 2006|url-status=live}}</ref> [[L. Brent Bozell III|L. Brent Bozell]], president of the group, complained of the network \"ripping the heart and soul out of a successful product\", saying that if NBC was concerned about references to God, they should not have taken the series. Bozell added \"This just documents the disconnect between [[Hollywood]] and the real world.\"<ref name=FOXStirControversy />\n\nNBC replied that the editing conformed to the network's broadcast standards, which direct producers \"not to advocate any one religious point of view.\" NBC spokeswoman Rebecca Marks said \"Our goal is to reach as broad an audience as possible with these positive messages while being careful not to advocate any one religious point of view.\"<ref name=\"FOXStirControversy\" /> Vischer said he was not informed that the religious content would be removed and said he would have declined to sign the contract had he known. \"I would have declined partly because I knew a lot of fans would feel like it was a [[sellout]] or it was done for money,\" he said.<ref name=\"FOXStirControversy\" /> Vischer added that he still understood NBC's wish to remain religiously neutral. \"VeggieTales is religious, NBC is not. I want to focus people more on 'Isn't it cool that Bob and Larry are on television.'\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Parker|first1=Jenni|title=PTC Applauds NBC's Airing of VeggieTales, Religious Content Intact|url=http://headlines.agapepress.org/archive/12/62006g.asp|publisher=Agape Press|accessdate=January 22, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061207214625/http://headlines.agapepress.org/archive/12/62006g.asp|archivedate=December 7, 2006|date=December 6, 2006}}</ref>\n\n=== VeggieTales Netflix Original Series: ''In The House'' and ''In the City'' (2014\u20132017) ===\n{{Main|VeggieTales in the House|VeggieTales in the City}}\nA new series,<ref>Hearn, Samantha. Nolensville - Home for the Holidays, September 15, 2016, \"[https://nolensvillehomepage.com/women-in-business-to-hear-from-veggietales-president/ Women in Business to hear from VeggieTales president]\". Retrieved December 29, 2017.</ref> ''VeggieTales in the House'', premiered on [[Netflix]] as an original series in Thanksgiving 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dickson|first1=Jeremy|title=VeggieTales Q&A: Off the counter and onto Netflix|url=http://kidscreen.com/2014/11/20/veggietales-qa-off-the-counter-and-onto-netflix/|publisher=Kidscreen|accessdate=December 5, 2014|date=November 20, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205190834/http://kidscreen.com/2014/11/20/veggietales-qa-off-the-counter-and-onto-netflix/|archivedate=December 5, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> The series lead is [[Doug TenNapel]] and features a theme song by independent studio musician and frequent TenNapel collaborator [[Terry Scott Taylor]]. The deal between current ''VeggieTales'' owner DreamWorks and Netflix calls for the release of 75 episodes over a three-year period with each episode featuring two 11-minute stories.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christianexaminer.com/article/veggie-tales-hops-to-netflix-is-god-in-it/47666.htm|title=Veggie Tales hops to Netflix, is God in it?|website=christianexaminer.com|accessdate=March 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMike Nawrocki and Phil Vischer continue to voice their characters,<ref>{{cite news|last1=K. Martin|first1=Sami|title='VeggieTales in the House' Co-Creator Tells History of Popular Series|url=http://www.muslimpost.com/news/veggietales-in-the-house-co-creator-tells-history-of-popular-series-130695/|accessdate=January 22, 2017|work=The Muslim Post|date=December 4, 2014}}</ref> but the rest of the original video cast has been replaced by veteran voice actors [[Tress MacNeille]] and [[Rob Paulsen]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Veggietales in the House (Season 3, Episode 1)|url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/veggietales-house-vod|publisher=British Board of Film Classification|accessdate=January 22, 2017}}</ref> The series is an expansion of the kitchen counter top segments of the original videos to include a full city which the characters live in. Bob and Larry live as roommates in an apartment west of the kitchen counter. Several stories revolve around a general store built into the bottom-right corner of a kitchen counter which is run by Pa Grape. The cast from the original videos remains the same aside from the absence of Mr. Nezzer, who has been replaced by a similar looking character named Ichabeezer. Themes in each episode relate to Biblical principles such as forgiveness, compassion and generosity.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Leah Marieann|first1=Klett|title=Exclusive: 'VeggieTales in the House' Season 2 on Netflix Sneak Preview|url=http://www.gospelherald.com/articles/58093/20150924/exclusive-sneak-preview-veggietales-in-the-house-season-2-on-netflix.htm|work=The Gospel Herald|accessdate=January 22, 2017|date=September 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, ''VeggieTales in the House'' ended, and a new series was made, to continue VeggieTales on Netflix. The series was called ''VeggieTales in the City''.<ref name=CTBrandNewVegatables>{{cite web|url=https://www.christiantoday.com/article/brand-new-veggietales-brings-godly-vegetables-back-to-netflix-exclusive-clips/104975.htm|title=Brand New VeggieTales Brings Godly Vegetables Back To Netflix: Exclusive Clips|first=Joseph Hartropp Thu 23 February 2017 16:00|last=GMT|website=christiantoday.com|accessdate=March 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.netflix.com/title/80119145|title=VeggieTales in the City - Netflix Official Site|website=netflix.com}}</ref>\n\n=== The VeggieTales Show (2019) ===\n{{Main|The VeggieTales Show}}\nIn March 2019, it was announced that the Trinity Broadcasting Network was picking up the broadcasting rights to a new ''VeggieTales'' series to air on their networks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tbn.org/press-releases/tbn-and-big-idea-content-group-partner-produce-all-new-%E2%80%9Cveggietales%E2%80%9D-episodes|title=TBN And Big Idea Content Group Partner To Produce All-New \"VeggieTales\" Episodes|website=TBN.com}}</ref> Vischer confirmed on Twitter that he and Nawrocki were both returning to Big Idea as full-time staff to work on the series, tentatively titled ''The VeggieTales Show''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/philvischer/status/1111372363805802496|title=Phil Vischer on Twitter: \"Correction - TBN is licensing VT from Universal... they didn't buy it. Bob and Larry still live with Shrek and Donkey and Minions. BUT... TBN is producing new eps and Mike and I are writing!\"|website=Twitter}}{{Primary source inline|date=March 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn April 24, 2019, the VeggieTales Official YouTube channel published a video called \"VeggieTales is Back: Brand New VeggieTales Show Trailer<ref name=\":16\">{{Citation|last=VeggieTales Official|title=VeggieTales is Back: Brand New VeggieTales Show Trailer|date=2019-04-24|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v6RF9XIGyhg|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref>\" which gives more information about The VeggieTales Show. It started airing on TBN in 2019. The show focuses on the VeggieTales characters putting on shows of Bible stories in a theater. The series also brings back Mr. Nezzer, as the owner of the theater in which the show takes place. The first episode was a Christmas special called The Best Christmas Gift that was distributed on DVD and Digital by [[Universal Pictures Home Entertainment]]. It premiered on TBN Christmas Day 2019.\n\n[[Phil Vischer]] and [[Mike Nawrocki]] reprised their respective roles as the voices of Bob the Tomato and Larry the Cucumber. Vischer and Nawrocki joined the creative team, led by show-runner Todd Waterman (who also worked on ''[[Mulan (1998 film)|Mulan]]'' and ''[[Transformers: Prime|Transformers Prime]]'').\n{{Quote|text=TBN is excited to partner with Big Idea Content Group to bring new life to a much-loved children's brand. These all new episodes will re-introduce VeggieTales to existing fans and remind new ones about the importance of presenting biblical values through high-quality children's entertainment.|sign=Tom Newman, head of Development and Production at TBN|{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}}}\n\nMost of the new episodes act out stories and lessons from the [[Bible]]. The show includes a nine-episode series about the [[Fruit of the Holy Spirit|fruits of the Spirit]]. There are also new adventures with LarryBoy and the League of Incredible Vegetables. The series will provide ''VeggieTales'' content through 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tbn.org/press-releases/tbn-and-big-idea-content-group-partner-produce-all-new-%E2%80%9Cveggietales%E2%80%9D-episodes|title=TBN and Big Idea Content Group Partner to Produce All-New \"VeggieTales\" Episodes|date=April 4, 2019|website=TBN|access-date=April 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Untitled VeggieTales movie ===\nAt the National Religious Broadcast 2019 Convention in California, Phil Vischer and Mike Nawrocki announced that [[Universal Pictures]] are developing a VeggieTales movie that will see a theatrical release in the future. What was also stated is that [[DreamWorks Animation]] will have no involvement in the movie. <ref name=\":14\" /> It does not have a script or [[Green-light|greenlight]] yet, and it is confirmed not to be the Bob and Larry Movie.<ref name=\":19\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/philvischer/status/1120797257392173056|title=There's a film in development, but no green light yet. Need a script first. (And it won't be the Bob & Larry Movie.)|last1=Phil|first1=Vischer|website=Twitter}}{{Primary source inline|date=April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Characters==\n{{Main|List of VeggieTales characters}}\n''VeggieTales'' has a continuous back story that all of the cartoons are actually teleplays, performed by various vegetables and fruit that live together on the same kitchen countertop. Some of these characters have \"real names,\" and take on various roles in the teleplays, although in the earlier adventures they appeared as themselves, showing some of their real-life situations. Most of these \"regulars\", such as Larry, Bob, Junior Asparagus, and Pa Grape, were established in the earliest videos.{{Citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n==Videos==\n{{main|List of VeggieTales videos}}\n\n===Re-issues and re-releases===\nBig Idea has released a few \"special edition\" DVDs which consist of remastered videos and additional features not on the original DVD.\n\n#''[[Lyle the Kindly Viking]] Special Edition (also includes 3\u20132\u20131 Penguins! Trouble on Planet Wait-Your-Turn)''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/VeggieTales-Kindly-Viking-Penguins-Feature/dp/B002SOP8O4// |title=VeggieTales: Lyle the Kindly Viking / 3\u20132\u20131 Penguins Double Feature (DVD) |accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref>\n#''[[King George and the Ducky]] Special Edition (also includes 3\u20132\u20131 Penguins! Runaway Pride at Lightstation Kilowatt)''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/VeggieTales-George-Ducky-Penguins-Episode/dp/B006LC3ZGM/ |title=VeggieTales: King George & The Ducky + Bonus 3\u20132\u20131 Penguins Episode |accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref>\n#''[[Where's God When I'm S-Scared?]] 15th Anniversary Collector's Edition (also includes 3\u20132\u20131 Penguins! Trouble on Planet Wait-Your-Turn)''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Wheres-When-S-Scared-15th-Anniversary/dp/B002NMV5TS/ |title=Where's God When I'm S-Scared (15th Anniversary) \u2013 DVD |accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Compilation videos===\nVarious ''VeggieTales'' videos were bundled into collections ranging in size from double features all the way up to a boxed collection of the first 30 ''VeggieTales'' videos. In addition, compilation videos of only the ''Silly Songs'' were also released. These song collections included the songs in \"Sing Along\" format as well as countdowns of the most popular Silly Songs as voted on by fans.{{Citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n== Reception and awards ==\n{{more citations needed section|date=March 2019|reason=The prize section is unsourced.}}\nVeggieTales has been nominated for three [[Emmy Award]]s,<ref name=\"Wrap Emmys\" /> four [[Annie Award]]s,<ref name=\"Annie\" />{{citation needed|date=August 2019}} thirteen [[GMA Dove Award]]s,<ref name=\"CBN\">{{Cite web|url=https://www1.cbn.com/cbnnews/us/2014/October/Blockbuster-Veggie-Tales-Series-Wins-Dove-Award|title=Blockbuster 'Veggie Tales' Series Wins Dove Award|date=October 9, 2014|website=CBN News|access-date=March 17, 2019}}</ref> six [[Parents' Choice Award]]s,<ref name=\"digitalmediafx\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.digitalmediafx.com/Features/bigidea.html|title=What's the Big Idea?|website=digitalmediafx.com|access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref> two [[Chicago Film Festival]] Awards,<ref name=\"digitalmediafx\" /> one [[Movieguide Awards|Movieguide Award]],<ref name=\"digitalmediafx\" /> one [[Golden Reel Award (Motion Picture Sound Editors)|Golden Reel Award]],<ref name=\"Variety\">{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2003/film/awards/gangs-perdition-top-golden-reel-nods-1117880217/|title='Gangs,' 'Perdition' top Golden Reel nods|last=Martin|first=Denise|last2=Martin|first2=Denise|date=2003-02-08|website=Variety|access-date=2019-08-08}}</ref> and one International World Animation Celebration Festival Award.<ref>{{Citation|title=VeggieTales (TV Series 1993\u2013 ) - IMDb|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0865856/trivia|access-date=2019-08-09}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2019, ''VeggieTales'' has sold 175&nbsp;million [[home video|videos]] (VHS, DVD, and Blu-Ray), making it the best selling [[Television|home entertainment]] series of all time, 16&nbsp;million books, 7&nbsp;million [[Album|music albums]], and 235&nbsp;million [[Streaming media|music streams]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tbn.org/press-releases/tbn-and-big-idea-content-group-partner-produce-all-new-%E2%80%9Cveggietales%E2%80%9D-episodes|title=TBN and Big Idea Content Group Partner to Produce All-New \"VeggieTales\" Episodes|date=2019-04-04|website=TBN|access-date=2019-08-08}}</ref> The revenue for Big Idea grew between 1996 and 1999 by 3300% from $1.3&nbsp;million to over $44&nbsp;million as the moral tales and off-beat humor proved popular with parents.<ref name=\"MeMyselfBob\" />{{rp|54}} According to Phil Vischer's book, ''Me, Myself, and Bob'', \"one third of American homes owned a Veggietales video by the year 2000\".<ref name=\"Me, myself, & Bob\">{{Cite book|title=Me, myself, & Bob : a true story about God, dreams, and talking vegetables|last=Vischer, Phil.|year=2008|publisher=T. Nelson|isbn=9781595551221|oclc=799058621}}</ref> ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' commented on the franchise's success that \"VeggieTales is the [[Barney & Friends|Barney]] of the group. It's simple characters, bright colors and catchy tunes sweeten the Christian message...The real appeal of the veggies is their wackiness. Like [[Bugs Bunny]], the cartoons contain a multitude of adult jokes, and like a sanitized version of \"[[South Park]],\" [[Comedy Central Stand-Up Presents|Comedy Central's]] raunchy cartoon, they rely on gross-out humor. Among [[Evangelicalism|evangelical Christian]] young adults, the veggies have a cult following, analogous to the adult audience of \"South Park.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB904601596159110500|title=They Look Ripe for Stardom: Christian Videos of Cartoon Cukes|last=Miller|first=Lisa|date=1998-09-01|work=The Wall Street Journal|access-date=2019-08-08|issn=0099-9660|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021024722/https://www.wsj.com/amp/articles/SB904601596159110500|archivedate=October 21, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe franchise's two theatrical releases, [[Jonah: A VeggieTales Movie|Jonah-A VeggieTales Movie]] (2002), and [[The Pirates Who Don't Do Anything: A VeggieTales Movie|The Pirates Who Don't Do Anything-A VeggieTales Movie]] (2008), rank as the top 10 best box office performing [[Christian film industry|faith based films]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?id=christian.htm|title=Christian Movies at the Box Office - Box Office Mojo|website=boxofficemojo.com|access-date=2019-08-08}}</ref> ''Jonah \u2013 A VeggieTales Movie'' currently holds a 65% approval rating on Rotten Tomatoes based on 55 reviews from critics, with an average score of 5.8 out of 10.<ref name=JonahRotten>{{cite web|title=Jonah \u2013 A VeggieTales Movie (2002)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/jonah_a_veggietales_movie/#contentReviews|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=December 27, 2013}}</ref> ''The Pirates Who Don't Do Anything '' received a 39% approval rating on Rotten Tomatoes based on 33 reviews, with an average rating of 4.7/10.<ref name=RottenTomatoesPirates>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/pirates_who_dont_do_anything_a_veggietales_movie/ |title=The Pirates Who Don't Do Anything: A VeggieTales Movie |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref> Their summary of critical consensus was, \"This Veggietale should please the youngest crowds, but the silly script will tire the more discerning viewer.\"\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Award\n!Nominated work\n!Result\n! Ref\n|-\n|1997\n| [[Chicago International Film Festival]]: Children's Jury Award for Best Animated Short Film\n|[[Very Silly Songs!|VeggieTales: Very Silly Songs!]]\n| {{won}}\n|<ref name=\"Doves\">{{Cite web|url=https://doveawards.com/awards/past-winners/|title=Past Winners {{!}} The 49th Annual GMA Dove Awards|access-date=March 17, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1998\n|[[GMA Dove Award]]: Children's Music Album of the Year<br />\n|A Very Veggie Christmas\n| {{won}}\n|<ref name=\"Doves\" />\n|-\n|[[GMA Dove Award]]: Long Form Music Video of the Year\n|[[Very Silly Songs!|VeggieTales: Very Silly Songs!]]\n| {{won}}\n|<ref name=\"Doves\" />\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1999\n|[[GMA Dove Award]]: Long Form Music Video of the Year\n|[[The End of Silliness?|VeggieTales: The End of Silliness?]]\n| {{nom}} \n|\n|-\n|AdQ Design Award: Outstanding Advertising Print Ad \n|VeggieTales: What's The Big Idea Magazine\n| {{won}}\n|<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.parents-choice.org/searchresult.cfm?cx=014227988025412781383:pafmblnckig&cof=FORID:11&q=VeggieTales+&sa=Search&siteurl=www.parents-choice.org/allawards.cfm|title=Parents' Choice Advanced Search|website=parents-choice.org|access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|2000\n|[[GMA Dove Award]]: Children's Music Album of the Year\n|[[Larry the 