om - The Christian Broadcasting Network|access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|2010\n|[[GMA Dove Award]]: Children's Music Album of the Year\n|Veggietales: Here I Am to Worship\n| {{won}}\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2011\n|[[GMA Dove Award]]: Children's Music Album of the Year\n|Sweetpea's Songs for Girls\n|{{nom}}\n|\n|-\n|[[Parents' Choice Award]]: Seasons Best Family Game\n|VeggieTales: Find It!\n| {{won}}\n|<ref name=\":6\" />\n|-\n|2012\n|[[GMA Dove Award]]: Children's Music Album of the Year\n|Hosanna! Today Top Worship Songs for Kids\n|{{nom}}\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|[[GMA Dove Award]]: Children's Music Album of the Year\n|VeggieTales 25 Favorite Bible Songs\n| {{won}}\n|<ref name=\"CBN\" />\n|-\n|2015\n|[[Emmy Award]]: Outstanding Animated Program\n|[[VeggieTales in the House]] Season One\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref name=\"Wrap Emmys\" />\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2017\n|[[Emmy Award]]: Outstanding Sound Editing\n|[[VeggieTales in the House]] Season Four\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Citation|title=VeggieTales in the House - IMDb|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt3692064/awards|access-date=March 17, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Tennessee House of Representatives|The Tennessee State House]] Resolution 68 Award: Life Time Achievement in Children's Entertainment \n|[[Mike Nawrocki]] for his 25 years of work on VeggieTales \n| {{won}}\n|<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web |url= https://www.linkedin.com/in/mike-nawrocki-450b465/|title=Mike Nawrocki \u2013 Chief Creative \u2013 Mike Nawrocki Creative, LLC {{!}} LinkedIn |accessdate= July 1, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|2018\n|[[Emmy Award]]: Best Performer in an Animated Program\n|[[Tress MacNeille]] in [[VeggieTales in the City]]\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goldderby.com/article/2018/2018-daytime-emmy-winners-full-list-creative-arts-awards-news-264817359/|title=2018 Daytime Emmy winners: Full list of Creative Arts Awards winners and nominees|last=Montgomery|first=Daniel|last2=Montgomery|first2=Daniel|date=April 28, 2018|website=GoldDerby|access-date=March 17, 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Related media==\n===Feature-length films===\n*''[[Jonah: A VeggieTales Movie]]'' (2002): Archibald Asparagus stars as [[Jonah]] in this version of the Biblical story. The Veggies learn that God is a God of second chances, and that we need to give second chances too and be compassionate and merciful.<ref name=\"NYTJonah\">{{cite news |last1=Kehr |first1=David |title=FILM IN REVIEW; 'Jonah' -- 'A Veggie Tales Movie' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/18/movies/film-in-review-jonah-a-veggie-tales-movie.html |accessdate=18 August 2019 |work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Veggie Tales - Conyers.jpg|thumb|Mr. Lunt, Pa Grape, and Larry the Cucumber at the Celebrate Freedom 2007 concert.]]\n*''[[The Pirates Who Don't Do Anything: A VeggieTales Movie]]'' (2008): In this second VeggieTales feature film, three lazy wannabe pirates go back in time to the 17th century, to fight real pirates and become heroes in a battle, to rescue a royal family from an evil tyrant. The three slackers learn that a hero doesn't have to be tall, strong, and handsome to be useful.<ref name=\"RottenTomatoesPWDDA\">{{cite web |title=The Pirates Who Don't Do Anything: A VeggieTales Movie |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/pirates_who_dont_do_anything_a_veggietales_movie |website=Rotten Tomatoes |publisher=Fandango |accessdate=18 August 2019}}</ref>\n* ''The Bob and Larry Movie'' (TBD): The origin story of VeggieTales hosts Bob the Tomato and Larry the Cucumber reveals how they met, how they got their own show, and answers the question how vegetables and fruit talk. This will be the first film in the series to feature humans. According to Phil Vischer, \"Since ''[[Jonah: A VeggieTales Movie]]'' was our [[The Ten Commandments (1956 film)|''The'' ''Ten Commandments,'']] ''The Bob and Larry Movie'' would be our ''[[Toy Story (franchise)|Toy Story]].''<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://philvischer.com/news/what-happened-to-big-idea-part-1/|title=What Happened to Big Idea? (Part 1) - Phil Vischer - Official Blog of VeggieTales Creator|date=2004-11-15|website=Phil Vischer|access-date=2019-03-17}}</ref>''\"'' The Bob and Larry Movie was originally planned to be the second VeggieTales movie with a released date in late 2005. It was placed into production in early 2002, toward the end of production of ''Jonah: A VeggieTales Movie'' (2002).<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2008/januaryweb-only/philvischer.html|title=The More You Preach, the Fewer You Reach|last=Hertz|first=by Todd|website=ChristianityToday.com|access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref> However, Big Idea Productions fell into bankruptcy in late 2002 and the film was placed on hiatus because it was deemed too expensive. As a result, [[Phil Vischer]] wrote ''[[The Pirates Who Don't Do Anything: A VeggieTales Movie]]'' to replace this movie. In 2008, it was considered to be the sequel to ''The Pirates who Don't Do Anything: A VeggieTales Movie'', but talks had stalled after the 2008 recession had led to the bankruptcy of VeggieTales owner ''Entertainment Rights'' and ''Classic Media.'' According to Phil Vischer in 2018, \"I have a copy of ''The Bob and Larry'' script on my laptop, but probably won't release it because it is technically owned by Universal and DreamWorks.\" \"It will hopefully be produced in the near future.\"<ref name=\"auto1\" />\n*''Untitled VeggieTales Movie'' (TBD): On March 28, 2019, Vischer and Nawrocki announced at the National Religious Broadcast Convention that they were developing a screenplay with Universal Studios for a new Veggietales movie. Universal Studios wants the film to be a bible story similar to ''Jonah: A Veggietales Movie'', so the film will not be ''The Bob and Larry Movie''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/philvischer/status/1241348735386427393|title=Twitter|website=mobile.twitter.com|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> The release date has not been announced.<ref name=\":14\">{{cite web |title=Phil Vischer on Twitter: \"New TV series in production with TBN. New movie in development at Universal. I'm involved in both!\" |url=https://twitter.com/philvischer/status/1111372778039476230 |website=Twitter}}{{Primary source inline|date=April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Stage production===\n''VeggieTales Live'' is a series of stage shows based on the ''VeggieTales'' videos. The first stage series was part of a two-year agreement with [[iHeartMedia|Clear Channel]] in 2002.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hettrick|first1=Scott|title='VeggieTales' hit the stage|url=https://variety.com/2001/digital/features/veggietales-hit-the-stage-1117802949/|accessdate=October 16, 2017|work=Variety|date=July 18, 2001}}</ref> Six versions of the shows have been staged. The shows have toured across the U.S. and at theme parks including [[Dollywood]] and [[Silver Dollar City]].<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/veggietales-live-happy-birthday-bob--larry-tour-returns-this-fall-with-first-time-show-dates-for-west-coast-221632901.html |title=VeggieTales Live! Happy Birthday Bob & Larry Tour Returns This Fall With First-Time Show Dates For West Coast |author=Big Idea Entertainment|date=August 29, 2013 |agency=PR Newswire |accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Video games===\nBig Idea, and its successors, have released ''VeggieTales'' themed games on various platforms including PC, Macintosh, iOS, and Android. Applications include games revolving around specific ''VeggieTales'' episodes (such as the PlayStation 2 release of ''LarryBoy and the Bad Apple'') to new content revolving around various ''VeggieTales'' characters.\n\n{{Infobox VG series\n| title              = VeggieTales\n| image              = VeggieTales 2014 logo.png\n| caption            = Logo (as of August 2014)\n| developer          = {{Collapsible list\n  |framestyle=border:none; padding:0;\n  |title=Various, including\n  |1=[[Papaya Studio]] |2=DC Studios |3=Fingerprint Network |4=[[Digital Praise]]}}\n| genre              = [[Christian video game|Christian]]<br/>[[Adventure game|Adventure]]<br/>[[Educational video game|Edutainment]]\n| platforms          = [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]], [[Game Boy Advance]], [[PlayStation 2]], [[Mac OS X]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[VideoNow]]\n| creator            = [[Big Idea Entertainment]]\n| first release version  = ''The Mystery of Veggie Island''\n| first release date     = September 3, 2002\n| latest release version = ''Step-by-Story presents: Larry's Missing Music''\n| latest release date    = March 19, 2012\n}}\n\n====Macintosh/PC====\n#''The Mystery of Veggie Island'' (September 15, 2002)<ref name=\"VG\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hive4media.com/news/html/Product_article.cfm?article_id=2625|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020305134828/http://www.hive4media.com:80/news/html/Product_article.cfm?article_id=2625|title=Veggie Tales Headed for CD-ROM|website=[[hive4media.com]]|archivedate=March 5, 2002|date=February 19, 2002|accessdate=September 21, 2019}}</ref>\n#''Veggie Carnival'' (October 15, 2002)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/VeggieTales-Veggie-Carnival-Jewel-Case-Pc/dp/B00006JK51/ref=sr_1_8?s=videogames&ie=UTF8&qid=1326816810&sr=1-8 |title=VeggieTales: Veggie Carnival (Jewel Case) \u2013 PC: Video Games |accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n#''Jonah: A VeggieTales Game'' (November 2002)<ref name=\"VG\"/>\n#''VeggieTales Creativity City'' (February 4, 2003)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Veggie-Tales-Creativity-City-PC-Game/dp/B000098XNE/ref=sr_1_2?s=videogames&ie=UTF8&qid=1326816810&sr=1-2 |title=Veggie Tales Creativity City (PC Game): Video Games |accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n#''Minnesota Cuke and the Coconut Apes'' (September 30, 2003)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Veggie-Tales-Minnesota-Coconut-Jewel-Pc/dp/B0002BJSLE/ref=pd_sim_sbs_vg_3 |title=Veggie Tales: Minnesota Cuke and the Coconut Apes (Jewel Case): Video Games |accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n#''VeggieTales Super Silly Fun!'' (December 15, 2005)<ref>{{cite web|author=ValuSoft |url=https://www.amazon.com/Veggie-Tales-Super-Silly-Cd-rom-PC/dp/B001E91ELA/ref=sr_1_12?s=videogames&ie=UTF8&qid=1326816810&sr=1-12 |title=Veggie Tales Super Silly Fun! Cd-rom: Video Games |date=August 13, 2008 |accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n#''VeggieTales Dance Dance Dance'' (December 2006)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Bigideass-Veggietales-Dance-Pad-Game/dp/B001D6K2B2|title=Bigideas's Veggietales Dance Dance Dance Dance Pad Game: Video Games|access-date=April 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====PlayStation 2 and Game Boy Advance games====\n#''[[LarryBoy and the Bad Apple]]'' (August 1, 2006)<ref name=\":11\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Veggietales-Larry-Boy-Apple-Playstation-2/dp/B000F7CECU/ref=sr_1_1?s=videogames&ie=UTF8&qid=1326816810&sr=1-1 |title=Veggietales: Larry Boy and the Bad Apple \u2013 PlayStation 2: Big Idea: Video Games |accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====iOS====\n#\"Step-by-Story presents: The Goofy Gift\" (December 28, 2011)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/step-by-story-veggietales/id492022025?ls=1&mt=8 |title=iTunes Store |publisher=iTunes Store |accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n#\"VeggieTales Spotisodes Collection\" (February 7, 2012)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/veggietales-spotisode-collection/id499459063?mt=8 |title=Watch and Find \u2013 VeggieTales Games and Video Clips \u2013 A Fingerprint Network App on the App Store on iTunes |publisher=iTunes Store |date=December 7, 2013 |accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n#\"Step-by-Story presents: Larry's Missing Music\" (March 19, 2012)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/step-by-story-veggietales/id509109422?mt=8 |title=iTunes Store |publisher=iTunes Store |accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Android====\n#\"Step-by-Story presents: The Goofy Gift\" (December 28, 2011)\n#\"VeggieTales Spotisodes Collection\" (February 7, 2012)\n#\"Step-by-Story presents: Larry's Missing Music\" (March 19, 2012)\n\n====Other systems====\n''VeggieTales'' games shipped pre-bundled in the  [[Game Wave Family Entertainment System]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pearson|first1=Jordan|title=Christians Loved Canada's Failed Video Game Console|url=https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/3k5d58/christians-loved-canadas-failed-video-game-console-game-wave|accessdate=December 26, 2017|work=Motherboard|date=December 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Music and audio CDs===\n{{main|List of VeggieTales albums}}\n\nThere have been over 45 musical albums released that tie into either ''VeggieTales'' characters or videos. While some of the albums are merely compilations of songs from the various videos (including albums entitled ''Larry-Boy Soundtrack'', ''[[A Very Veggie Easter]]'', and ''25 Favorite Very VeggieTunes''), others contain completely original content such as stories or songs performed by Phil Vischer, Mike Nawrocki, and the other ''VeggieTales'' voice talent (such as ''Bob and Larry's Campfire Songs'', ''Christian Hit Music'', and ''Bob and Larry Sing the 80's'').\n\n===Merchandise===\nOn February 10, 2011, Big Idea Entertainment announced several new product promotions, including partnerships with [[Chick-fil-A]] (kids meal promotions), American Puzzle Company (wooden puzzles and trains), CTI Industries (mylar and latex balloons), Tabbies (index tabs, stickers, temporary tattoos and wall clings), Victory Designs (children's guitars), and Zoobies (plush pillows and blankets).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.licensemag.com/license-global/big-idea-grows-veggietales-brand |title=Big Idea Grows VeggieTales Brand |publisher=License! Global |date=February 10, 2011 |accessdate=October 9, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==== Books and Comics ====\n{{Main|List of VeggieTales books}}\nIn June 2014, B&H Kids announced plans to produce a ''VeggieTales'' comic with [[Big Idea Productions]] and [[DreamWorks Animation]].<ref>{{cite press release|author1=B&H Kids|title=B&H Kids and Veggitales Team to Create New Line of Comic Books|url=http://www.bhpublishinggroup.com/press-release/bh-kids-and-veggietales-team-to-create-a-new-line-of-comic-books|publisher=B&H Publishing Group|accessdate=January 22, 2017|date=June 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{official website|http://www.veggietales.com/ }}\n*[http://www.ceganmo.com/2008/11/veggietales.html VeggieTales] at CEGAnMo.com\n*{{IMDb title|id=0865856|title=VeggieTales}}\n{{VeggieTales}}\n{{DreamWorks Animation}}{{Netflix original ended series}}{{TBN}}{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Veggietales}}\n[[Category:VeggieTales| ]]\n[[Category:1990s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:1993 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2000s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American children's television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American children's television series]]\n[[Category:2015 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:American animated television programs featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated musical television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:American computer-animated television series]]\n[[Category:Animated film series]]\n[[Category:American preschool education television series]]\n[[Category:Big Idea Entertainment television series]]\n[[Category:Christian animation]]\n[[Category:Christian children's television series]]\n[[Category:DreamWorks Classics]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:Qubo]]\n[[Category:Fruit and vegetable characters]]\n[[Category:Internet memes]]\n", "name_user": "92.13.207.106", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Extra)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/VeggieTales"}
{"title_page": "July 1959", "text_new": "{{short description|Month of 1959}}\n{{Events by month|1959}}\n{{calendar|year=1959|month=July}}\n[[File:Oldupai gorge.jpg|350px|thumb|left|July 17, 1959: ''Homo habilis'' remains unearthed after 1,750,000 years in Olduvai Gorge]]\n[[File:Homo habilis.JPG|200px|right|thumb|Homo habilis]]\n[[File:Kitchen debate.jpg|350px|thumb|left|July 24, 1959: Nixon and Khrushchev debate in kitchen exhibit]]\n[[File:1959 Decree 1.jpg|200px|thumb|right|July 5, 1959: Sukarno decrees \"Guided Democracy\", creates totalitarian state in Indonesia]]\n\nThe following events occurred in '''July 1959''':\n\n==July 1, 1959 (Wednesday)==\n* A new standard for the [[yard]] and for the inch was adopted by the United States and Britain. The yard was formally defined as 0.9144 meters, and, as 1/36 of a yard, the inch was {{Nowrap|0.0254 m}} or 2.54 centimeters.<ref>Brian Lasater, ''The Dream of the West, Pt II'' (Lulu.com, 2008), p 256</ref>\n* \"World Refugee Year\" began for the United Nations, running until June 30, 1960. At that time, the UN estimated that 15,000,000 people were [[refugees]], and campaigned for private contributions and increased government spending.<ref>Merle Curti, ''American Philanthropy Abroad'' (Transaction Publishers, 1988), pp 571\u201372</ref>\n* At 12:01&nbsp;a.m., the consumption of opium in [[Thailand]] became illegal, and all approved opium dens were closed. When 12:01 arrived, [[Field Marshal]] [[Sarit Thanarat]] sent the military on a nationwide crackdown on the opium trade.<ref>Thak Chaloemtiarana, ''Thailand: The Politics of Despotic Paternalism'' (SEAP Publications, 2007), p 126</ref>\n* [[Heinrich L\u00fcbke]] was elected the second [[President of Germany|President of West Germany]], succeeding [[Theodor Heuss]]. L\u00fcbke had 517 of the 1038 electoral votes, 3 shy of a majority, while Carlo Schmid had 385 and Max Becker 104 on the first ballot in the electoral college. L\u00fcbke won on the second round.<ref>\"Germans Elect Adenauer's Man President\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 1, 1959, p 1</ref>\n\n==July 2, 1959 (Thursday)==\n*The [[Lushan Conference]] opened, with members of the [[Politburo of the Communist Party of China|Politburo]] and the [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of China]] discussing the failure of the [[Great Leap Forward]], the economic program instituted by [[Mao Zedong]]. When members of the committee drafted a letter to the Chairman, a [[purge]] followed against so-called \"right-wing deviation.\"<ref>Zhengyuan Fu, ''Autocratic Tradition and Chinese Politics'' (Cambridge University Press, 1993), pp300\u2013303</ref>\n*[[Crown Prince]] Albert (later [[Albert&nbsp;II of Belgium]]) married Princess [[Paola Ruffo di Calabria]]. Albert succeeded his brother [[Baudouin of Belgium]] as [[Monarchy of Belgium|King of Belgium]] in 1993.<ref>Paul F. State, ''Historical Dictionary of Brussels'' (Scarecrow Press, 2004), p7</ref>\n*A fire at [[the Pentagon]] destroyed {{Nowrap|$30&nbsp;million}} worth of computers in the Air  Force Statistical Center, forced the evacuation of 30,000 employees, and sent 25 firemen for medical treatment.<ref>\"Secrets Burn, Fire Empties Pentagon\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 2, 1959, p1</ref>\n\n==July 3, 1959 (Friday)==\n*For the first time, a [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] champion came from South America, as [[Alex Olmedo]] of [[Peru]] won the men's singles title, beating Australia's [[Rod Laver]] 6\u20131, 6\u20133 and 6\u20134.<ref>\"Olmedo Blasts Aussie Laver For Wimbledon Title\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 3, 1959, p31</ref> The next day, [[Maria Bueno]] of [[Brazil]] completed the South American sweep and ended a 21-year streak of U.S. titles, defeating American [[Darlene Hard]], 6\u20134, 6\u20133, to win the women's singles.<ref>\"U.S. Net Reign At Wimbledon Ends\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 4, 1959, p11</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Julie Burchill]], British journalist and novelist; in [[Frenchay]]\n\n==July 4, 1959 (Saturday)==\n*The [[Cayman Islands]] became a [[Crown colony]] of the [[British Empire]].<ref>\"Cayman Islands\", ''Encyclopedia of the United Nations and International Agreements'' (Taylor & Francis, 2003) pp284\u20135</ref>\n*The [[Cumberland Gap National Historical Park]] was dedicated.<ref>\"Yesterday's Trails\", ''Popular Science'' (April 1988), p44F</ref>\n*The 49th star was added to the American flag on the first [[Independence Day (United States)|Fourth of July]] following Alaska's admission to the Union. [[United States Secretary of the Interior|Secretary of the Interior]] [[Fred Seaton]] raised the banner (seven stars in seven staggered rows) at 12:01 a.m over [[Fort McHenry]] in Baltimore, where [[Francis Scott Key]] wrote about the Star Spangled Banner.<ref>\"49th Star-By Dawn's Early Light\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 4, 1959, p1</ref>\n\n==July 5, 1959 (Sunday)==\n*[[President Sukarno's 1959 Decree|President Sukarno]] of [[Indonesia]] dissolved the [[Konstituante]] parliament and introduced a totalitarian system, which he called \"[[Guided Democracy]]\" (Demokrasi Terpimpin), with the assistance of General [[Abdul Haris Nasution]].<ref>Bob S. Hadiwinata, ''The Politics of NGOs in Indonesia: Developing Democracy and Managing a Movement'' (Routledge, 2003), p51</ref>\n*[[David Ben-Gurion]] resigned as [[Prime Minister of Israel]] and new elections were called for the [[Knesset]]. Ben-Gurion's Israel Workers' Party won a majority of seats in the November election.<ref>Avraham Avi-ha\u00ef, ''Ben-Gurion: State-Builder'' (Transaction Publishers, 1974), p207</ref>\n*German jurisdiction over [[Saarland]], and its one&nbsp;million residents, became effective at {{Nowrap|12:01 am}} after a period of transition that had begun on January 1, 1957. France had administered the region since the end of World War&nbsp;II, and Saarlanders were given five days to exchange 117 francs for each deutschmark.<ref>\"Saarland Returns To Germany Today \", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 5, 1959, p2</ref>\n\n==July 6, 1959 (Monday)==\n*A [[C-124 Globemaster]] cargo plane, carrying nuclear weapons, crashed on takeoff from [[Barksdale Air Force Base]] in Louisiana. The crew of seven survived, and safety devices functioned properly, but one weapon was destroyed in the fire that followed.<ref>Michael H. Maggelet and James C. Oskins, ''Broken Arrow \u2013 The Declassified History of U.S. Nuclear Weapons Accidents'' (Lulu.com, 2008), pp123\u2013127</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Richard Dacoury]], French National Team basketball player\n\n==July 7, 1959 (Tuesday)==\n*[[Venus]] passed between Earth and the star [[Regulus]] at 1428 GMT, providing astronomers an opportunity to learn more about the second planet. Because the starlight dimmed measurably as it passed through the Venusian atmosphere during the [[occultation]], the density of that atmosphere could be calculated more precisely. The next conjunction of Venus and Regulus will take place on October 1, 2044.<ref>Patrick Moore, ''The Data Book of Astronomy'' (CRC Press, 2000), pp88\u201389</ref>\n*[[Bulgaria]], [[Romania]] and the [[Soviet Union]] signed the \"Convention Concerning Fishing in the Black Sea\" at [[Varna]], Bulgaria's [[Black Sea]] resort.<ref>P. C. Sinha K'Cherry, ''International Encyclopaedia of Environmental Laws'' (Anmol Publications, 1996) pp2357\u201361</ref>\n*The [[National League]] All-Stars defeated the [[American League]] All-Stars 5-4 at [[Pittsburgh]]'s [[Forbes Field]] in the [[1959 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (first game)|first of two Major League Baseball All-Star games]].  Because of an offseason vote by the MLB owners, an unprecedented second All-Star game would be played on [[August 1959|August 3]].<ref>[http://www.baseball-almanac.com/asgbox/yr1959as.shtml|Baseball-Almanac.com]</ref>\n\n==July 8, 1959 (Wednesday)==\n*[[United States Army]] [[Major (United States)|Major]] [[Dale R. Buis]] and [[Master Sergeant]] [[Chester M. Ovnand]] formerly listed as the first two of 57,939 Americans to die in the [[Vietnam War]], killed by a [[Viet Cong]] attack on the divisional headquarters at [[Bi\u00ean H\u00f2a]]. They were two of the 700 American [[Military Assistance Advisory Group|military advisors]] sent to [[South Vietnam]], and had been watching a movie with six other advisors when the attack began. Four were wounded.<ref>James E. Westheider, ''The Vietnam War'' (Greenwood Publishing Group, 2007), pp9\u201310; \"Red Terrorists Kill 2 Yanks In Viet Nam\", ''San Mateo Times'', July 9, 1959, p1</ref> Buis's name is the first on the [[Vietnam Veterans Memorial]]. Richard Vandegeer, one of 18 Americans killed on May 15, 1975, in the [[Mayaguez incident|''Mayaguez'' incident]], is the last.<ref>Rick Atkinson, ''The Long Gray Line: The American Journey of West Point's Class of 1966'' (Macmillan, 1999), p477</ref>\n*An explosion on a [[tour boat]] in [[Haderslev]], [[Denmark]], killed 44 people.<ref>\"Excursion Boat Blast And Fire Fatal to 44\", ''The Post-Standard'' (Syracuse), July 9, 1959, p1</ref>\n\n==July 9, 1959 (Thursday)==\n*After a 16-month break, the United States secretly resumed U-2 spy plane flights over the Soviet Union. Pilot Marty Knutson flew into Soviet airspace to photograph the missile site at [[Tyuratam]].<ref>Curtis Peebles, ''Twilight Warriors: Covert Air Operations Against the USSR'' (Naval Institute Press, 2005), pp150\u2013151</ref> Ironically, the same day marked the signing of an exchange agreement between the [[United States National Academy of Sciences]] and the [[Academy of Sciences of the U.S.S.R.]]<ref>''Annual Report, National Academy of Sciences'' (G.P.O. 1959), pp82\u201383</ref>\n*[[Al Sharpton]] preached his first sermon, at the age of four, at the Washington Temple Church of God in Christ in the Bedford-Stuyvesant section of Brooklyn.<ref>Michael Klein, ''The Man Behind the Sound Bite'' (Castillo International, 1991)</ref>\n*'''Born:''' \n**[[Jim Kerr]], Scottish rock singer ([[Simple Minds]]), in [[Toryglen]] \n**[[Kevin Nash]], American professional wrestler, WCW and WWF, in [[Trenton, Michigan]] \n**[[Clive Stafford Smith]], British civil liberties attorney, in [[Cambridge]]\n\n==July 10, 1959 (Friday)==\n*''[[The Hate That Hate Produced]]'', a TV documentary by [[Mike Wallace]] and [[Louis Lomax]], was first broadcast. Intended as an [[expos\u00e9 (journalism)|expos\u00e9]] of the [[African American Muslims|Black Muslim]] movement, the show instead gave national celebrity to [[Malcolm X]] and [[Warith Deen Mohammed|Wallace Muhammad]]. Prior to the program, the Black Muslim sect had 30,000 members, and within a few weeks the number had doubled.<ref>By Douglas T. Miller and Marion Nowak,\n''The Fifties: The Way We Really Were'' (Doubleday, 1977), p. 209.</ref>\n*A memorial for [[Frank Foley]] (1884\u20131958) was dedicated in [[Harel, Israel]], in the form of a forest planted in the desert. As a [[passport control officer]] at Britain's embassy in Nazi Germany, Foley flouted strict rules in order to help as many as 10,000 German Jews to leave the country.<ref>Mordecai Paldiel, ''Diplomat Heroes of the Holocaust'' (KTAV Publishing House, Inc., 2007), p. 16.</ref>\n\n==July 11, 1959 (Saturday)==\n*The Japanese government implemented a policy of publishing documents with a combination of 881 approved [[kanji]] symbols and the [[katakana]] syllabary.<ref>John Young and Kimiko Nakajima-Okano, ''Learn Japanese: New College Text'' Volume&nbsp;II (University of Hawaii Press, 1984), p320</ref>\n*The crew of a Pan American flight from Honolulu to San Francisco encountered a UFO at 21,000 feet over the Pacific, and the sighting was confirmed by pilots on two other airlines. Captain George Wilson told reporters \"There was an extremely bright light surrounded by small lights\" and that the object traveled at \"inconceivable\" speed, and added \"I'm a believer now.\"<ref>\"5 Pilots Sight Mysterious Flying Object\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 11, 1959, p1; \"Believer Now In Saucers, Says Witness\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 12, 1959, p1</ref>\n*'''Born:'''  \n**[[Richie Sambora]], guitarist in [[Bon Jovi]], in [[Perth Amboy, New Jersey]] \n**[[Suzanne Vega]], American singer-songwriter, in [[Santa Monica, California]]\n*'''Died:''' [[Charlie Parker (cricketer)|Charlie Parker]], 76, English cricketer\n\n==July 12, 1959 (Sunday)==\n*More than 100 people were killed during a 15-hour-long rebellion in the [[Honduras|Honduran]] capital of [[Tegucigalpa]]. Members of the National Police seized the town of [[Comayagua]] and captured several locations in the capital, but failed to get control of the residence of [[President of Honduras]] [[Ramon Villeda Morales]].<ref>\"100 Killed, Rebellion Put Down in Honduras Capital\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 13, 1959, p1</ref>\n\n==July 13, 1959 (Monday)==\n*The worst nuclear accident in American history happened at the [[Santa Susana Field Laboratory]] in southern [[California]]. The [[Sodium Reactor Experiment]], which used liquid sodium to cool the uranium fuel rods and the nuclear reactor, experienced a sudden rise in temperature and radiation. Technicians managed to shut down the reactor, and after a two-hour inspection, the reactor was restarted. On July 26, a second inspection determined that 13 of the 43 fuel rods had melted. For two weeks, radioactive by-products had been released into the surrounding area.<ref>Teresa Patterson, \"Overcooking With Atoms\", from ''It Looked Good On Paper'' (HarperCollins, 2009), pp46\u201350</ref>\n*The planet [[Neptune]] reached its [[aphelion]], the point in its 165-year orbit furthest from the Sun. The planet was at its closest on August 28, 1876, and will be again on September 5, 2042.<ref>Patrick Moore, ''The Data Book of Astronomy'' (CRC Press, 2000), p204</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Richard Leman]], British field hockey player and Olympic medalist, in [[East Grinstead]]\n\n==July 14, 1959 (Tuesday)==\n[[File:General Peng Dehuai.jpg|100px|left|thumb|Ex-Defense Minister Peng]]\n*Marshal [[Peng Dehuai]], China's Minister of Defense, handed Chairman Mao Zedong a letter summarizing problems with the Great Leap Forward. Mao was furious, and two days later printed copies of the letter to distribute to the Luzhang Conference participants. Peng was fired and soon became the focus of the \"Anti-Right Deviation Movement\".<ref>Zhengyuan Fu, Autocratic Tradition and Chinese Politics, p391</ref>\n*In [[Kirkuk]], [[Iraq]], a rally to celebrate the first anniversary of the 1958 revolution degenerated into a three-day-long massacre of ethnic Turks by the Kurds. At least 30 people were killed, and over 100 injured. The event was last referred to as the [[Iraqi Turkmens#Kirkuk massacre of 1959|Kirkuk Massacre]].<ref>Phebe Marr, ''The Modern History of Iraq'' (Westview Press, 2004), p34</ref> On the same day, Iraq became the first Arab nation to appoint a woman to a ministerial post, with Dr. Naziha ad-Dulaimi becoming Minister of Rural Affairs.<ref>[[Gabriel Baer]], ''Population and Society in the Arab East'' (Routledge, 2003), p57</ref>\n*The first nuclear warship, the [[USS Long Beach (CGN-9)|USS ''Long Beach'']], was launched from [[Quincy, Massachusetts]].<ref>Andrew D. Lambert, ''Warship'' (Naval Institute Press, 2004), p25</ref>\n*The [[French Community]], France's version of the British Commonwealth of Nations, was organized in Paris.<ref>Robert Aldrich, ''Greater France: A History of French Overseas Expansion'' (Macmillan, 1996), p303</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Susana Mart\u00ednez]], American politician and Governor of New Mexico since 2011; in [[El Paso, Texas]]\n\n==July 15, 1959 (Wednesday)==\n*More than 500,000 steelworkers walked off the job as the [[United Steelworkers of America]] called the [[Steel strike of 1959|largest strike in American history]]. Only after intervention by the President and the Supreme Court did the strike end, 116 days later, on November 6.<ref>Jack Metzgar, ''Striking Steel: Solidarity Remembered'' (Temple University Press, 2000), p58</ref>\n*'''Died:''' [[Ernest Bloch]], 78, classical music composer\n\n==July 16, 1959 (Thursday)==\n*Seconds after liftoff, a [[Juno II]] rocket, and the satellite it was carrying, were destroyed by ground control when the rocket veered off course toward central Florida.<ref>\"Juno Rocket Blown Up As It Veers on Takeoff\", ''The Post-Standard'' (Syracuse), July 17, 1959, p1</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Gary Anderson (placekicker)|Gary Anderson]], NFL kicker, in [[Parys]], [[South Africa]]\n\n==July 17, 1959 (Friday)==\n[[File:Mary Leakey.jpg|100px|right|thumb|Mary Leakey]]\n[[File:Billie Holiday 0001 original.jpg|100px|left|thumb|Billie Holiday]]\n*Anthropologist [[Mary Leakey]] unearthed a skull fragment, commonly referred to as ''[[Zinjanthropus]]'', that would lead to a rethinking of the origins of human beings. Discovered at the [[Olduvai Gorge]] in [[Tanzania]], where [[Louis Leakey]] had found prehistoric tools 28 years earlier. Zinjanthropus (now Australopithecus boisei) is not considered a direct human ancestor, but another Olduvai discovery from 1960, the mandible with teeth of \"OH 5\" (Olduvai Hominid 5), the toolmaking ''Homo habilis'', some {{Nowrap|1.75&nbsp;million}} years old, is believed to be.<ref>Matt Cartmill and Fred H. Smith, ''The Human Lineage'' (John Wiley and Sons, 2009), pp162\u201364; Ute Gacs, et al., ''Women Anthropologists: Selected Biographies'' (University of Illinois Press, 1989), p226; \"600,000 Year Old Human Skull Discovered\", ''Oakland Tribune'', August 28, 1960, p1</ref>\n*An early experiment was done by New York TV station [[WPIX]], after a hit by Jim McAnany of the White Sox ended a no-hitter by the Yankees' Ralph Terry. Since the game was being videotaped, broadcaster [[Mel Allen]] asked director Terry Murphy to play a tape of McAnany's hit over the air for a soon-thereafter replay, if not an instant replay.<ref>Stephen Borelli, ''How about That!: The Life of Mel Allen'' (Sports Publishing LLC, 2005), p185</ref>\n*Alfred Hitchcock's ''[[North by Northwest]]'', with Cary Grant, premiered.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0053125/releaseinfo imdb.com]</ref>\n*'''Died:''' Singer [[Billie Holiday]] died at {{Nowrap|3:20 a.m.}} at New York's Metropolitan Hospital, where she had been admitted on May 31 for heart failure. Thousands of mourners turned out for her wake and her funeral.<ref>Bud Kliment, ''Billie Holiday'' (Holloway House Publishing, 1990), pp148\u2013151</ref>\n\n==July 18, 1959 (Saturday)==\n[[File:Manuel Urrutia Lle\u00f3.JPG|100px|right|thumb|Ex-President Urrutia]]\n*[[Osvaldo Dorticos Torrado]] was sworn in as [[President of Cuba]] shortly after midnight, hours after [[Fidel Castro]] went on television to denounce President [[Manuel Urrutia]]. On July 17, Castro had announced his resignation as Prime Minister and his plans to address the nation at {{Nowrap|7:00 p.m.}} Urrutia, who had disagreed with Castro's confiscation of private farmland, resigned three hours into Castro's speech and made plans to flee the country.<ref>\"Castro Changes Presidents in Coup\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 18, 1959, p1</ref>\n\n==July 19, 1959 (Sunday)==\n*At a meeting in [[Saniquellie]], [[Liberia]], Presidents [[William Tubman]] of Liberia and [[Sekou Toure]] of [[Ghana]], and Prime Minister [[Kwame Nkrumah]] of [[Ghana]], came to an agreement that led to the founding, in 1963, of the [[Organisation of African Unity]] (OAU).<ref>[[Guy Arnold]], ''A Guide To African Political & Economic Development'' (Taylor & Francis, 2001), p5</ref>\n\n==July 20, 1959 (Monday)==\n[[File:William Leahy cropped.jpg|100px|left|thumb|Admiral Leahy]]\n*Soviet Premier [[Nikita Khrushchev]] called off a tour of [[Sweden]], [[Norway]] and [[Denmark]]. The Scandinavian visit had been slated to start on August 15 with a visit to [[Stockholm]], but was criticized by newspapers in all three countries.<ref>\"Khrushchev Cancels Trip to Scandinavia\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 20, 1959, p1</ref>\n*'''Died:''' Fleet Admiral [[William D. Leahy]], 84, highest ranking American naval officer during World War&nbsp;II\n\n==July 21, 1959 (Tuesday)==\n*The [[Boston Red Sox]] became the last Major League Baseball team to integrate, twelve years after Jackie Robinson had broken the color line. In the eighth inning of a game at Chicago, [[Pumpsie Green]] entered the lineup as a pinch runner, then played the ninth inning as a shortstop in a 2\u20131 win over the White Sox.<ref>Howard Bryant, ''Shut Out: A Story of Race and Baseball in Boston'' (Routledge, 2002), p53</ref> Green was called up from the Minneapolis Millers club after Bobby Avila was traded to the Braves.<ref>\"Bobby Avila Sold As Pumpsie Green Joins Boston Club\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 22, 1959, p52</ref>\n*Two milestones in the erosion of [[censorship]] happened on opposite sides of the Atlantic Ocean.  In the United States, federal judge [[Frederick van Pelt Bryan]] enjoined the U.S. Postmaster General from stopping the delivery of the novel ''[[Lady Chatterley's Lover]]''.,<ref>\"Miller, Henry\", ''Encyclopedia of Erotic Literature'' (CRC Press, 2006), p898</ref> while in Britain, the [[Obscene Publications Act 1959]] was passed, marking what [[John Sutherland (author)|John Sutherland]] would describe as \"the great liberation for printed literature\".<ref>Anthony Aldgate, ''Censorship and the Permissive Society: British Cinema and Theatre, 1955\u20131965'' (Oxford University Press, 1995), p4</ref>\n\n==July 22, 1959 (Wednesday)==\n*The Japan\u2013[[Paraguay]] Immigration Agreement was signed, providing for 85,000 Japanese citizens to immigrate to Paraguay over a 30-year period, settling on farmland purchased by Japan's government in Chavez, Fram, Alton Parana and Iguacu. In consideration for the agreement, Japan made a {{Nowrap|$3.8&nbsp;million}} loan so that the Paraguayan Navy could purchase seven war ships. The plan failed, with less than 7,754 Japanese moving to Paraguay.<ref>Toake Endoh, ''Exporting Japan: Politics of Emigration to Latin America'' (University of Illinois Press, 2009), p54</ref>\n\n==July 23, 1959 (Thursday)==\n[[File:Brig. Gen. James M. Stewart.jpg|100px|left|thumb|General Stewart]]\n[[File:Barry Goldwater photo1962.jpg|100px|right|thumb|General Goldwater]]\n*Actor [[Jimmy Stewart]] and U.S. Senator [[Barry Goldwater]] both won promotion to the rank of brigadier general. In addition to their civilian jobs, both were colonels in the U.S. Air Force reserves. The promotions were approved by voice vote in the Senate.<ref>\"Jimmy Stewart Wins Brig. General's Star\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 23, 1959, p3</ref>\n*The September\u2013October issue of the DC Comic [[Showcase (comics)|''Showcase'']], No. 22 in the series, went on sale, and introduced [[Hal Jordan]] as the [[Silver Age of Comic Books|\"Silver Age\"]] [[Green Lantern]].<ref>[http://www.dcindexes.com/database/comic-details.php?comicid=24310 \"Mike's Amazing World of DC Comics\"]</ref>\n\n==July 24, 1959 (Friday)==\n*The [[Kitchen Debate]] took place between Soviet Premier [[Nikita Khrushchev]] and American Vice-President [[Richard Nixon]], at [[Moscow]]'s [[Sokolniki Park]], where the [[American National Exhibition]] was being held. At a display of a model kitchen, Khrushchev and Nixon argued, through interpreters, over the merits of communism and capitalism. Both recounted the incident years later, in ''[[Six Crises]]'' by Nixon, and in ''Khrushchev Remembers''. Time Magazine would later describe the first public discussion between the Soviet and American officials as \"what may be remembered as peacetime diplomacy's most amazing 24 hours\".<ref>\"Better to See Once\", [http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,825793-1,00.html ''Time'' Magazine, August 3, 1959]</ref>\n*'''Died:''' King [[Mutara III of Rwanda|Mutara&nbsp;III]] Rudahigwa, ruler of the Tutsi people in the Belgian colony of [[Rwanda]], collapsed and died after being given a penicillin injection by a Belgian physician in Bujumbura. The death was believed by other doctors to be from anaphylactic shock from a penicillin allergy,<ref>G\u00e9rard Prunier, ''The Rwanda Crisis: History of a Genocide'' (Columbia University Press, 1997), pp54\u201355</ref> although other histories refer to the death as an assassination.<ref>Thomas Streissguth, ''Rwanda in Pictures'' (Twenty-First Century Books, 2007), p67</ref> In the violence that followed, 20,000 Tutsi were killed and 150,000 fled the country over the next seven years.<ref>Johan Pottier, ''Re-imagining Rwanda: Conflict, Survival and Disinformation in the Late Twentieth Century'' (Cambridge University Press, 2002), p125</ref>\n\n==July 25, 1959 (Saturday)==\n*On the 50th anniversary of the first airplane flight across the English Channel (by Louis Bleriot), the first hovercraft trip across the Channel took place, as the SR N1 made the journey on a cushion of air.<ref>Liang Yun and Alan Bliault, ''Theory and Design of Air Cushion Craft'' (Butterworth-Heinemann, 2000), p7</ref>\n*The videotapes of the [[Kitchen Debate]] were broadcast on American television, after a delay occasioned by the Soviet government's request to have 20 minutes of the Nixon-Khrushchev exchange shown in both nations simultaneously. Because the Soviet television equipment would not accommodate American videorecording, the tape was not broadcast there.<ref>\"U.S. Thwarts Russ Censor Try As Nixon, Khrushchev Toast\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 26, 1959, p1</ref>\n\n==July 26, 1959 (Sunday)==\n*Eight days after his \"resignation\", [[Fidel Castro]] rallied half a&nbsp;million peasants and announced that he would return as Prime Minister.  President Urrutia fled Cuba, disguised as a milkman, and was replaced by [[Osvaldo Dorticos Torrado]], while Castro built a cult of personality and a dictatorship.<ref>Fran Rees, ''Fidel Castro, Leader of Communist Cuba'' (Compass Point Books, 2006), pp63\u201364</ref>\n*'''Born:'''  \n**[[Kevin Spacey]], American actor and director, Oscar winner 1995 and 1999, in [[South Orange, New Jersey]] \n**[[Rick Bragg]], American journalist and author, in [[Piedmont, Alabama]]\n\n==July 27, 1959 (Monday)==\n*A proposed third major league for baseball\u2014the [[Continental League]]\u2014was announced at New York's Biltmore Hotel. Like the [[National League]] and the [[American League]], the CL would have eight teams. Backed by [[William Shea]] and [[Branch Rickey]], the league announced the first five teams in\u2014New York, Houston, Toronto, Denver, and Minneapolis-St. Paul.<ref>Lee Lowenfish, ''Branch Rickey: Baseball's Ferocious Gentleman'' (University of Nebraska Press, 2007), p553</ref> New York Mayor Robert F. Wagner had declared it \"Continental League Baseball Day\". The CL planned to play a 154-game schedule starting in 1961.<ref>\"Third Major Loop Becomes Reality\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 27, 1959, p35</ref>\n*Admiral [[Hyman Rickover]] inspected the first nuclear powered Soviet ship, the icebreaker ''Lenin''.<ref>Arnold Kramish, ''Atomic Energy in the Soviet Union'' (Stanford University Press, 1960), p160</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Hugh Green (American football)|Hugh Green]], college and NFL linebacker; in [[Natchez, Mississippi]]\n\n==July 28, 1959 (Tuesday)==\n*Lt. Col. William H. Rankin bailed out of his crippled F-8 fighter after it stalled at 47,000 feet. After a two-minute freefall, his parachute opened automatically at 10,000 feet, but it took him another 38 minutes to reach the ground. Rankin descended into a thunderstorm and was buffeted up and down by the winds until landing near [[Ahoskie, North Carolina]]. He told his story to the Associated Press from his hospital bed more than a week later.<ref>\"Tossed Like Yo-You By Storm-- Tells of Bailing Out 9 Mi. Above Earth\", ''Press-Telegram'' (Long Beach, CA), August 7, 1959, pB-10</ref>\n*Voters in [[Hawaii]] elected their first state governor ([[William F. Quinn]]), their first Congressman ([[Daniel K. Inouye]]), and their first United States Senators, [[Hiram L. Fong]] and [[Oren E. Long]].\n\n==July 29, 1959 (Wednesday)==\n*After passing both houses of Parliament, the Legitimacy Act of 1959 received royal assent in Britain, giving equal rights to children born out of wedlock.<ref>Stephen Michael Cretney, ''Family Law in the Twentieth Century: A History'' (Oxford University Press, 2003), pp552\u201354</ref>\n*Australia entered the \"[[Jet Age]]\", when [[Qantas]] became the first airline outside the United States to inaugurate [[Boeing 707]] services, flying from Sydney, Australia, to San Francisco.<ref>John Gunn, ''High Corridors: Qantas, 1954\u20131970'' (University of Queensland Press, 1988), p155</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Sanjay Dutt]], award-winning Bollywood actor and politician, in [[Bombay]] (now [[Mumbai]])\n\n==July 30, 1959 (Thursday)==\n*The [[United Nations Medal]] was established for service, and is awarded for at least six months service with UN forces. The medal can be awarded to American servicemen as of 1964.<ref>Keith E. Bonn, ''Army Officer's Guide'' (Stackpole Books, 2005), p561</ref>\n*[[Robert Noyce]] of the [[Fairchild Semiconductor]] company filed a patent application for his invention of an [[integrated circuit]] that could be mass-produced.  On April 25, 1961, he would receive U.S. Patent 2,981,877 and, along with [[Jack Kilby]] who had applied for a patent for the original IC five months earlier, would receive the [[Nobel Prize in Physics]] in 2000.  <ref>Arjun N. Saxena, ''Invention of Integrated Circuits: Untold Important Facts'' (World Scientific, 2009) pp72-74</ref> \n*'''Died:''' \n**[[Mar\u00eda Natividad Venegas de la Torre]], 91, Mexican nun who was canonized as a Roman Catholic saint in 2000\n**[[Cho Bong-am]], who had been South Korea's Minister of Agriculture in 1948, and had run for President in 1956, was executed for \"treason against the state\".<ref>Andrew C. Nahm and James E. Hoare, ''Historical Dictionary of the Republic of Korea'' (Scarecrow Press, 2004), p21</ref>\n\n==July 31, 1959 (Friday)==\n*[[Euzkadi Ta Askatasuna]] (ETA), the Basque separatist organization, was founded in Spain. In its first 40 years, ETA's paramilitary attacks killed more than 800 people and wounded thousands.<ref>Wayne Anderson, ''The ETA: Spain's Basque Terrorists'' (Rosen Publishing Group, 2003), p18</ref>\n*Article 356 of the Constitution of India was invoked, providing for [[President's Rule]] of an Indian state, was invoked to depose the Communist government of the State of Kerala.<ref>Rabindra Kumar Sethy, ''Political Crisis and President's Rule in an Indian State'' (APH Publishing, 2003), p72</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Events by month links}}\n\n[[Category:1959|*1959-07]]\n[[Category:July|1959]]\n[[Category:Months in the 1950s|*1959-07]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Month of 1959}}\n{{Events by month|1959}}\n{{calendar|year=1959|month=July}}\n[[File:Oldupai gorge.jpg|350px|thumb|left|July 17, 1959: ''Homo habilis'' remains unearthed after 1,750,000 years in Olduvai Gorge]]\n[[File:Homo habilis.JPG|200px|right|thumb|Homo habilis]]\n[[File:Kitchen debate.jpg|350px|thumb|left|July 24, 1959: Nixon and Khrushchev debate in kitchen exhibit]]\n[[File:1959 Decree 1.jpg|200px|thumb|right|July 5, 1959: Sukarno decrees \"Guided Democracy\", creates totalitarian state in Indonesia]]\n\nThe following events occurred in '''July 1959''':\n\n==July 1, 1959 (Wednesday)==\n* A new standard for the [[yard]] and for the inch was adopted by the United States and Britain. The yard was formally defined as 0.9144 meters, and, as 1/36 of a yard, the inch was {{Nowrap|0.0254 m}} or 2.54 centimeters.<ref>Brian Lasater, ''The Dream of the West, Pt II'' (Lulu.com, 2008), p 256</ref>\n* \"World Refugee Year\" began for the United Nations, running until June 30, 1960. At that time, the UN estimated that 15,000,000 people were [[refugees]], and campaigned for private contributions and increased government spending.<ref>Merle Curti, ''American Philanthropy Abroad'' (Transaction Publishers, 1988), pp 571\u201372</ref>\n* At 12:01&nbsp;a.m., the consumption of opium in [[Thailand]] became illegal, and all approved opium dens were closed. When 12:01 arrived, [[Field Marshal]] [[Sarit Thanarat]] sent the military on a nationwide crackdown on the opium trade.<ref>Thak Chaloemtiarana, ''Thailand: The Politics of Despotic Paternalism'' (SEAP Publications, 2007), p 126</ref>\n* [[Heinrich L\u00fcbke]] was elected the second [[President of Germany|President of West Germany]], succeeding [[Theodor Heuss]]. L\u00fcbke had 517 of the 1038 electoral votes, 3 shy of a majority, while Carlo Schmid had 385 and Max Becker 104 on the first ballot in the electoral college. L\u00fcbke won on the second round.<ref>\"Germans Elect Adenauer's Man President\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 1, 1959, p 1</ref>\n\n==July 2, 1959 (Thursday)==\n*The [[Lushan Conference]] opened, with members of the [[Politburo of the Communist Party of China|Politburo]] and the [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of China]] discussing the failure of the [[Great Leap Forward]], the economic program instituted by [[Mao Zedong]]. When members of the committee drafted a letter to the Chairman, a [[purge]] followed against so-called \"right-wing deviation.\"<ref>Zhengyuan Fu, ''Autocratic Tradition and Chinese Politics'' (Cambridge University Press, 1993), pp300\u2013303</ref>\n*[[Crown Prince]] Albert (later [[Albert&nbsp;II of Belgium]]) married Princess [[Paola Ruffo di Calabria]]. Albert succeeded his brother [[Baudouin of Belgium]] as [[Monarchy of Belgium|King of Belgium]] in 1993.<ref>Paul F. State, ''Historical Dictionary of Brussels'' (Scarecrow Press, 2004), p7</ref>\n*A fire at [[the Pentagon]] destroyed {{Nowrap|$30&nbsp;million}} worth of computers in the Air  Force Statistical Center, forced the evacuation of 30,000 employees, and sent 25 firemen for medical treatment.<ref>\"Secrets Burn, Fire Empties Pentagon\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 2, 1959, p1</ref>\n\n==July 3, 1959 (Friday)==\n*For the first time, a [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] champion came from South America, as [[Alex Olmedo]] of [[Peru]] won the men's singles title, beating Australia's [[Rod Laver]] 6\u20131, 6\u20133 and 6\u20134.<ref>\"Olmedo Blasts Aussie Laver For Wimbledon Title\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 3, 1959, p31</ref> The next day, [[Maria Bueno]] of [[Brazil]] completed the South American sweep and ended a 21-year streak of U.S. titles, defeating American [[Darlene Hard]], 6\u20134, 6\u20133, to win the women's singles.<ref>\"U.S. Net Reign At Wimbledon Ends\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 4, 1959, p11</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Julie Burchill]], British journalist and novelist; in [[Frenchay]]\n\n==July 4, 1959 (Saturday)==\n*The [[Cayman Islands]] became a [[Crown colony]] of the [[British Empire]].<ref>\"Cayman Islands\", ''Encyclopedia of the United Nations and International Agreements'' (Taylor & Francis, 2003) pp284\u20135</ref>\n*The [[Cumberland Gap National Historical Park]] was dedicated.<ref>\"Yesterday's Trails\", ''Popular Science'' (April 1988), p44F</ref>\n*The 49th star was added to the American flag on the first [[Independence Day (United States)|Fourth of July]] following Alaska's admission to the Union. [[United States Secretary of the Interior|Secretary of the Interior]] [[Fred Seaton]] raised the banner (seven stars in seven staggered rows) at 12:01 a.m over [[Fort McHenry]] in Baltimore, where [[Francis Scott Key]] wrote about the Star Spangled Banner.<ref>\"49th Star-By Dawn's Early Light\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 4, 1959, p1</ref>\n\n==July 5, 1959 (Sunday)==\n*[[President Sukarno's 1959 Decree|President Sukarno]] of [[Indonesia]] dissolved the [[Konstituante]] parliament and introduced a totalitarian system, which he called \"[[Guided Democracy]]\" (Demokrasi Terpimpin), with the assistance of General [[Abdul Haris Nasution]].<ref>Bob S. Hadiwinata, ''The Politics of NGOs in Indonesia: Developing Democracy and Managing a Movement'' (Routledge, 2003), p51</ref>\n*[[David Ben-Gurion]] resigned as [[Prime Minister of Israel]] and new elections were called for the [[Knesset]]. Ben-Gurion's Israel Workers' Party won a majority of seats in the November election.<ref>Avraham Avi-ha\u00ef, ''Ben-Gurion: State-Builder'' (Transaction Publishers, 1974), p207</ref>\n*German jurisdiction over [[Saarland]], and its one&nbsp;million residents, became effective at {{Nowrap|12:01 am}} after a period of transition that had begun on January 1, 1957. France had administered the region since the end of World War&nbsp;II, and Saarlanders were given five days to exchange 117 francs for each deutschmark.<ref>\"Saarland Returns To Germany Today \", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 5, 1959, p2</ref>\n\n==July 6, 1959 (Monday)==\n*A [[C-124 Globemaster]] cargo plane, carrying nuclear weapons, crashed on takeoff from [[Barksdale Air Force Base]] in Louisiana. The crew of seven survived, and safety devices functioned properly, but one weapon was destroyed in the fire that followed.<ref>Michael H. Maggelet and James C. Oskins, ''Broken Arrow \u2013 The Declassified History of U.S. Nuclear Weapons Accidents'' (Lulu.com, 2008), pp123\u2013127</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Richard Dacoury]], French National Team basketball player\n\n==July 7, 1959 (Tuesday)==\n*[[Venus]] passed between Earth and the star [[Regulus]] at 1428 GMT, providing astronomers an opportunity to learn more about the second planet. Because the starlight dimmed measurably as it passed through the Venusian atmosphere during the [[occultation]], the density of that atmosphere could be calculated more precisely. The next conjunction of Venus and Regulus will take place on October 1, 2044.<ref>Patrick Moore, ''The Data Book of Astronomy'' (CRC Press, 2000), pp88\u201389</ref>\n*[[Bulgaria]], [[Romania]] and the [[Soviet Union]] signed the \"Convention Concerning Fishing in the Black Sea\" at [[Varna]], Bulgaria's [[Black Sea]] resort.<ref>P. C. Sinha K'Cherry, ''International Encyclopaedia of Environmental Laws'' (Anmol Publications, 1996) pp2357\u201361</ref>\n*The [[National League]] All-Stars defeated the [[American League]] All-Stars 5-4 at [[Pittsburgh]]'s [[Forbes Field]] in the [[1959 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (first game)|first of two Major League Baseball All-Star games]].  Because of an offseason vote by the MLB owners, an unprecedented second All-Star game would be played on [[August 1959|August 3]].<ref>[http://www.baseball-almanac.com/asgbox/yr1959as.shtml|Baseball-Almanac.com]</ref>\n\n==July 8, 1959 (Wednesday)==\n*[[United States Army]] [[Major (United States)|Major]] [[Dale R. Buis]] and [[Master Sergeant]] [[Chester M. Ovnand]] formerly listed as the first two of 57,939 Americans to die in the [[Vietnam War]], killed by a [[Viet Cong]] attack on the divisional headquarters at [[Bi\u00ean H\u00f2a]]. They were two of the 700 American [[Military Assistance Advisory Group|military advisors]] sent to [[South Vietnam]], and had been watching a movie with six other advisors when the attack began. Four were wounded.<ref>James E. Westheider, ''The Vietnam War'' (Greenwood Publishing Group, 2007), pp9\u201310; \"Red Terrorists Kill 2 Yanks In Viet Nam\", ''San Mateo Times'', July 9, 1959, p1</ref> Buis's name is the first on the [[Vietnam Veterans Memorial]]. Richard Vandegeer, one of 18 Americans killed on May 15, 1975, in the [[Mayaguez incident|''Mayaguez'' incident]], is the last.<ref>Rick Atkinson, ''The Long Gray Line: The American Journey of West Point's Class of 1966'' (Macmillan, 1999), p477</ref>\n*An explosion on a [[tour boat]] in [[Haderslev]], [[Denmark]], killed 44 people.<ref>\"Excursion Boat Blast And Fire Fatal to 44\", ''The Post-Standard'' (Syracuse), July 9, 1959, p1</ref>\n\n==July 9, 1959 (Thursday)==\n*After a 16-month break, the United States secretly resumed U-2 spy plane flights over the Soviet Union. Pilot Marty Knutson flew into Soviet airspace to photograph the missile site at [[Tyuratam]].<ref>Curtis Peebles, ''Twilight Warriors: Covert Air Operations Against the USSR'' (Naval Institute Press, 2005), pp150\u2013151</ref> Ironically, the same day marked the signing of an exchange agreement between the [[United States National Academy of Sciences]] and the [[Academy of Sciences of the U.S.S.R.]]<ref>''Annual Report, National Academy of Sciences'' (G.P.O. 1959), pp82\u201383</ref>\n*[[Al Sharpton]] preached his first sermon, at the age of four, at the Washington Temple Church of God in Christ in the Bedford-Stuyvesant section of Brooklyn.<ref>Michael Klein, ''The Man Behind the Sound Bite'' (Castillo International, 1991)</ref>\n*'''Born:''' \n**[[Jim Kerr]], Scottish rock singer ([[Simple Minds]]), in [[Toryglen]] \n**[[Kevin Nash]], American professional wrestler, WCW and WWF, in [[Trenton, Michigan]] \n**[[Clive Stafford Smith]], British civil liberties attorney, in [[Cambridge]]\n\n==July 10, 1959 (Friday)==\n*''[[The Hate That Hate Produced]]'', a TV documentary by [[Mike Wallace]] and [[Louis Lomax]], was first broadcast. Intended as an [[expos\u00e9 (journalism)|expos\u00e9]] of the [[African American Muslims|Black Muslim]] movement, the show instead gave national celebrity to [[Malcolm X]] and [[Warith Deen Mohammed|Wallace Muhammad]]. Prior to the program, the Black Muslim sect had 30,000 members, and within a few weeks the number had doubled.<ref>By Douglas T. Miller and Marion Nowak,\n''The Fifties: The Way We Really Were'' (Doubleday, 1977), p. 209.</ref>\n*A memorial for [[Frank Foley]] (1884\u20131958) was dedicated in [[Harel, Israel]], in the form of a forest planted in the desert. As a [[passport control officer]] at Britain's embassy in Nazi Germany, Foley flouted strict rules in order to help as many as 10,000 German Jews to leave the country.<ref>Mordecai Paldiel, ''Diplomat Heroes of the Holocaust'' (KTAV Publishing House, Inc., 2007), p. 16.</ref>\n\n==July 11, 1959 (Saturday)==\n*The Japanese government implemented a policy of publishing documents with a combination of 881 approved [[kanji]] symbols and the [[katakana]] syllabary.<ref>John Young and Kimiko Nakajima-Okano, ''Learn Japanese: New College Text'' Volume&nbsp;II (University of Hawaii Press, 1984), p320</ref>\n*The crew of a Pan American flight from Honolulu to San Francisco encountered a UFO at 21,000 feet over the Pacific, and the sighting was confirmed by pilots on two other airlines. Captain George Wilson told reporters \"There was an extremely bright light surrounded by small lights\" and that the object traveled at \"inconceivable\" speed, and added \"I'm a believer now.\"<ref>\"5 Pilots Sight Mysterious Flying Object\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 11, 1959, p1; \"Believer Now In Saucers, Says Witness\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 12, 1959, p1</ref>\n*'''Born:'''  \n**[[Richie Sambora]], guitarist in [[Bon Jovi]], in [[Perth Amboy, New Jersey]] \n**[[Suzanne Vega]], American singer-songwriter, in [[Santa Monica, California]]\n*'''Died:''' [[Charlie Parker (cricketer)|Charlie Parker]], 76, English cricketer\n\n==July 12, 1959 (Sunday)==\n*More than 100 people were killed during a 15-hour-long rebellion in the [[Honduras|Honduran]] capital of [[Tegucigalpa]]. Members of the National Police seized the town of [[Comayagua]] and captured several locations in the capital, but failed to get control of the residence of [[President of Honduras]] [[Ramon Villeda Morales]].<ref>\"100 Killed, Rebellion Put Down in Honduras Capital\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 13, 1959, p1</ref>\n\n==July 13, 1959 (Monday)==\n*The worst nuclear accident in American history happened at the [[Santa Susana Field Laboratory]] in southern [[California]]. The [[Sodium Reactor Experiment]], which used liquid sodium to cool the uranium fuel rods and the nuclear reactor, experienced a sudden rise in temperature and radiation. Technicians managed to shut down the reactor, and after a two-hour inspection, the reactor was restarted. On July 26, a second inspection determined that 13 of the 43 fuel rods had melted. For two weeks, radioactive by-products had been released into the surrounding area.<ref>Teresa Patterson, \"Overcooking With Atoms\", from ''It Looked Good On Paper'' (HarperCollins, 2009), pp46\u201350</ref>\n*The planet [[Neptune]] reached its [[aphelion]], the point in its 165-year orbit furthest from the Sun. The planet was at its closest on August 28, 1876, and will be again on September 5, 2042.<ref>Patrick Moore, ''The Data Book of Astronomy'' (CRC Press, 2000), p204</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Richard Leman]], British field hockey player and Olympic medalist, in [[East Grinstead]]\n\n==July 14, 1959 (Tuesday)==\n[[File:General Peng Dehuai.jpg|100px|left|thumb|Ex-Defense Minister Peng]]\n*Marshal [[Peng Dehuai]], China's Minister of Defense, handed Chairman Mao Zedong a letter summarizing problems with the Great Leap Forward. Mao was furious, and two days later printed copies of the letter to distribute to the Luzhang Conference participants. Peng was fired and soon became the focus of the \"Anti-Right Deviation Movement\".<ref>Zhengyuan Fu, Autocratic Tradition and Chinese Politics, p391</ref>\n*In [[Kirkuk]], [[Iraq]], a rally to celebrate the first anniversary of the 1958 revolution degenerated into a three-day-long massacre of ethnic Turks by the Kurds. At least 30 people were killed, and over 100 injured. The event was last referred to as the [[Iraqi Turkmens#Kirkuk massacre of 1959|Kirkuk Massacre]].<ref>Phebe Marr, ''The Modern History of Iraq'' (Westview Press, 2004), p34</ref> On the same day, Iraq became the first Arab nation to appoint a woman to a ministerial post, with Dr. Naziha ad-Dulaimi becoming Minister of Rural Affairs.<ref>[[Gabriel Baer]], ''Population and Society in the Arab East'' (Routledge, 2003), p57</ref>\n*The first nuclear warship, the [[USS Long Beach (CGN-9)|USS ''Long Beach'']], was launched from [[Quincy, Massachusetts]].<ref>Andrew D. Lambert, ''Warship'' (Naval Institute Press, 2004), p25</ref>\n*The [[French Community]], France's version of the British Commonwealth of Nations, was organized in Paris.<ref>Robert Aldrich, ''Greater France: A History of French Overseas Expansion'' (Macmillan, 1996), p303</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Susana Mart\u00ednez]], American politician and Governor of New Mexico since 2011; in [[El Paso, Texas]]\n\n==July 15, 1959 (Wednesday)==\n*More than 500,000 steelworkers walked off the job as the [[United Steelworkers of America]] called the largest strike in American history. Only after intervention by the President and the Supreme Court did the strike end, 116 days later, on November 6.<ref>Jack Metzgar, ''Striking Steel: Solidarity Remembered'' (Temple University Press, 2000), p58</ref>\n*'''Died:''' [[Ernest Bloch]], 78, classical music composer\n\n==July 16, 1959 (Thursday)==\n*Seconds after liftoff, a [[Juno II]] rocket, and the satellite it was carrying, were destroyed by ground control when the rocket veered off course toward central Florida.<ref>\"Juno Rocket Blown Up As It Veers on Takeoff\", ''The Post-Standard'' (Syracuse), July 17, 1959, p1</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Gary Anderson (placekicker)|Gary Anderson]], NFL kicker, in [[Parys]], [[South Africa]]\n\n==July 17, 1959 (Friday)==\n[[File:Mary Leakey.jpg|100px|right|thumb|Mary Leakey]]\n[[File:Billie Holiday 0001 original.jpg|100px|left|thumb|Billie Holiday]]\n*Anthropologist [[Mary Leakey]] unearthed a skull fragment, commonly referred to as ''[[Zinjanthropus]]'', that would lead to a rethinking of the origins of human beings. Discovered at the [[Olduvai Gorge]] in [[Tanzania]], where [[Louis Leakey]] had found prehistoric tools 28 years earlier. Zinjanthropus (now Australopithecus boisei) is not considered a direct human ancestor, but another Olduvai discovery from 1960, the mandible with teeth of \"OH 5\" (Olduvai Hominid 5), the toolmaking ''Homo habilis'', some {{Nowrap|1.75&nbsp;million}} years old, is believed to be.<ref>Matt Cartmill and Fred H. Smith, ''The Human Lineage'' (John Wiley and Sons, 2009), pp162\u201364; Ute Gacs, et al., ''Women Anthropologists: Selected Biographies'' (University of Illinois Press, 1989), p226; \"600,000 Year Old Human Skull Discovered\", ''Oakland Tribune'', August 28, 1960, p1</ref>\n*An early experiment was done by New York TV station [[WPIX]], after a hit by Jim McAnany of the White Sox ended a no-hitter by the Yankees' Ralph Terry. Since the game was being videotaped, broadcaster [[Mel Allen]] asked director Terry Murphy to play a tape of McAnany's hit over the air for a soon-thereafter replay, if not an instant replay.<ref>Stephen Borelli, ''How about That!: The Life of Mel Allen'' (Sports Publishing LLC, 2005), p185</ref>\n*Alfred Hitchcock's ''[[North by Northwest]]'', with Cary Grant, premiered.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0053125/releaseinfo imdb.com]</ref>\n*'''Died:''' Singer [[Billie Holiday]] died at {{Nowrap|3:20 a.m.}} at New York's Metropolitan Hospital, where she had been admitted on May 31 for heart failure. Thousands of mourners turned out for her wake and her funeral.<ref>Bud Kliment, ''Billie Holiday'' (Holloway House Publishing, 1990), pp148\u2013151</ref>\n\n==July 18, 1959 (Saturday)==\n[[File:Manuel Urrutia Lle\u00f3.JPG|100px|right|thumb|Ex-President Urrutia]]\n*[[Osvaldo Dorticos Torrado]] was sworn in as [[President of Cuba]] shortly after midnight, hours after [[Fidel Castro]] went on television to denounce President [[Manuel Urrutia]]. On July 17, Castro had announced his resignation as Prime Minister and his plans to address the nation at {{Nowrap|7:00 p.m.}} Urrutia, who had disagreed with Castro's confiscation of private farmland, resigned three hours into Castro's speech and made plans to flee the country.<ref>\"Castro Changes Presidents in Coup\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 18, 1959, p1</ref>\n\n==July 19, 1959 (Sunday)==\n*At a meeting in [[Saniquellie]], [[Liberia]], Presidents [[William Tubman]] of Liberia and [[Sekou Toure]] of [[Ghana]], and Prime Minister [[Kwame Nkrumah]] of [[Ghana]], came to an agreement that led to the founding, in 1963, of the [[Organisation of African Unity]] (OAU).<ref>[[Guy Arnold]], ''A Guide To African Political & Economic Development'' (Taylor & Francis, 2001), p5</ref>\n\n==July 20, 1959 (Monday)==\n[[File:William Leahy cropped.jpg|100px|left|thumb|Admiral Leahy]]\n*Soviet Premier [[Nikita Khrushchev]] called off a tour of [[Sweden]], [[Norway]] and [[Denmark]]. The Scandinavian visit had been slated to start on August 15 with a visit to [[Stockholm]], but was criticized by newspapers in all three countries.<ref>\"Khrushchev Cancels Trip to Scandinavia\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 20, 1959, p1</ref>\n*'''Died:''' Fleet Admiral [[William D. Leahy]], 84, highest ranking American naval officer during World War&nbsp;II\n\n==July 21, 1959 (Tuesday)==\n*The [[Boston Red Sox]] became the last Major League Baseball team to integrate, twelve years after Jackie Robinson had broken the color line. In the eighth inning of a game at Chicago, [[Pumpsie Green]] entered the lineup as a pinch runner, then played the ninth inning as a shortstop in a 2\u20131 win over the White Sox.<ref>Howard Bryant, ''Shut Out: A Story of Race and Baseball in Boston'' (Routledge, 2002), p53</ref> Green was called up from the Minneapolis Millers club after Bobby Avila was traded to the Braves.<ref>\"Bobby Avila Sold As Pumpsie Green Joins Boston Club\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 22, 1959, p52</ref>\n*Two milestones in the erosion of [[censorship]] happened on opposite sides of the Atlantic Ocean.  In the United States, federal judge [[Frederick van Pelt Bryan]] enjoined the U.S. Postmaster General from stopping the delivery of the novel ''[[Lady Chatterley's Lover]]''.,<ref>\"Miller, Henry\", ''Encyclopedia of Erotic Literature'' (CRC Press, 2006), p898</ref> while in Britain, the [[Obscene Publications Act 1959]] was passed, marking what [[John Sutherland (author)|John Sutherland]] would describe as \"the great liberation for printed literature\".<ref>Anthony Aldgate, ''Censorship and the Permissive Society: British Cinema and Theatre, 1955\u20131965'' (Oxford University Press, 1995), p4</ref>\n\n==July 22, 1959 (Wednesday)==\n*The Japan\u2013[[Paraguay]] Immigration Agreement was signed, providing for 85,000 Japanese citizens to immigrate to Paraguay over a 30-year period, settling on farmland purchased by Japan's government in Chavez, Fram, Alton Parana and Iguacu. In consideration for the agreement, Japan made a {{Nowrap|$3.8&nbsp;million}} loan so that the Paraguayan Navy could purchase seven war ships. The plan failed, with less than 7,754 Japanese moving to Paraguay.<ref>Toake Endoh, ''Exporting Japan: Politics of Emigration to Latin America'' (University of Illinois Press, 2009), p54</ref>\n\n==July 23, 1959 (Thursday)==\n[[File:Brig. Gen. James M. Stewart.jpg|100px|left|thumb|General Stewart]]\n[[File:Barry Goldwater photo1962.jpg|100px|right|thumb|General Goldwater]]\n*Actor [[Jimmy Stewart]] and U.S. Senator [[Barry Goldwater]] both won promotion to the rank of brigadier general. In addition to their civilian jobs, both were colonels in the U.S. Air Force reserves. The promotions were approved by voice vote in the Senate.<ref>\"Jimmy Stewart Wins Brig. General's Star\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 23, 1959, p3</ref>\n*The September\u2013October issue of the DC Comic [[Showcase (comics)|''Showcase'']], No. 22 in the series, went on sale, and introduced [[Hal Jordan]] as the [[Silver Age of Comic Books|\"Silver Age\"]] [[Green Lantern]].<ref>[http://www.dcindexes.com/database/comic-details.php?comicid=24310 \"Mike's Amazing World of DC Comics\"]</ref>\n\n==July 24, 1959 (Friday)==\n*The [[Kitchen Debate]] took place between Soviet Premier [[Nikita Khrushchev]] and American Vice-President [[Richard Nixon]], at [[Moscow]]'s [[Sokolniki Park]], where the [[American National Exhibition]] was being held. At a display of a model kitchen, Khrushchev and Nixon argued, through interpreters, over the merits of communism and capitalism. Both recounted the incident years later, in ''[[Six Crises]]'' by Nixon, and in ''Khrushchev Remembers''. Time Magazine would later describe the first public discussion between the Soviet and American officials as \"what may be remembered as peacetime diplomacy's most amazing 24 hours\".<ref>\"Better to See Once\", [http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,825793-1,00.html ''Time'' Magazine, August 3, 1959]</ref>\n*'''Died:''' King [[Mutara III of Rwanda|Mutara&nbsp;III]] Rudahigwa, ruler of the Tutsi people in the Belgian colony of [[Rwanda]], collapsed and died after being given a penicillin injection by a Belgian physician in Bujumbura. The death was believed by other doctors to be from anaphylactic shock from a penicillin allergy,<ref>G\u00e9rard Prunier, ''The Rwanda Crisis: History of a Genocide'' (Columbia University Press, 1997), pp54\u201355</ref> although other histories refer to the death as an assassination.<ref>Thomas Streissguth, ''Rwanda in Pictures'' (Twenty-First Century Books, 2007), p67</ref> In the violence that followed, 20,000 Tutsi were killed and 150,000 fled the country over the next seven years.<ref>Johan Pottier, ''Re-imagining Rwanda: Conflict, Survival and Disinformation in the Late Twentieth Century'' (Cambridge University Press, 2002), p125</ref>\n\n==July 25, 1959 (Saturday)==\n*On the 50th anniversary of the first airplane flight across the English Channel (by Louis Bleriot), the first hovercraft trip across the Channel took place, as the SR N1 made the journey on a cushion of air.<ref>Liang Yun and Alan Bliault, ''Theory and Design of Air Cushion Craft'' (Butterworth-Heinemann, 2000), p7</ref>\n*The videotapes of the [[Kitchen Debate]] were broadcast on American television, after a delay occasioned by the Soviet government's request to have 20 minutes of the Nixon-Khrushchev exchange shown in both nations simultaneously. Because the Soviet television equipment would not accommodate American videorecording, the tape was not broadcast there.<ref>\"U.S. Thwarts Russ Censor Try As Nixon, Khrushchev Toast\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 26, 1959, p1</ref>\n\n==July 26, 1959 (Sunday)==\n*Eight days after his \"resignation\", [[Fidel Castro]] rallied half a&nbsp;million peasants and announced that he would return as Prime Minister.  President Urrutia fled Cuba, disguised as a milkman, and was replaced by [[Osvaldo Dorticos Torrado]], while Castro built a cult of personality and a dictatorship.<ref>Fran Rees, ''Fidel Castro, Leader of Communist Cuba'' (Compass Point Books, 2006), pp63\u201364</ref>\n*'''Born:'''  \n**[[Kevin Spacey]], American actor and director, Oscar winner 1995 and 1999, in [[South Orange, New Jersey]] \n**[[Rick Bragg]], American journalist and author, in [[Piedmont, Alabama]]\n\n==July 27, 1959 (Monday)==\n*A proposed third major league for baseball\u2014the [[Continental League]]\u2014was announced at New York's Biltmore Hotel. Like the [[National League]] and the [[American League]], the CL would have eight teams. Backed by [[William Shea]] and [[Branch Rickey]], the league announced the first five teams in\u2014New York, Houston, Toronto, Denver, and Minneapolis-St. Paul.<ref>Lee Lowenfish, ''Branch Rickey: Baseball's Ferocious Gentleman'' (University of Nebraska Press, 2007), p553</ref> New York Mayor Robert F. Wagner had declared it \"Continental League Baseball Day\". The CL planned to play a 154-game schedule starting in 1961.<ref>\"Third Major Loop Becomes Reality\", ''Oakland Tribune'', July 27, 1959, p35</ref>\n*Admiral [[Hyman Rickover]] inspected the first nuclear powered Soviet ship, the icebreaker ''Lenin''.<ref>Arnold Kramish, ''Atomic Energy in the Soviet Union'' (Stanford University Press, 1960), p160</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Hugh Green (American football)|Hugh Green]], college and NFL linebacker; in [[Natchez, Mississippi]]\n\n==July 28, 1959 (Tuesday)==\n*Lt. Col. William H. Rankin bailed out of his crippled F-8 fighter after it stalled at 47,000 feet. After a two-minute freefall, his parachute opened automatically at 10,000 feet, but it took him another 38 minutes to reach the ground. Rankin descended into a thunderstorm and was buffeted up and down by the winds until landing near [[Ahoskie, North Carolina]]. He told his story to the Associated Press from his hospital bed more than a week later.<ref>\"Tossed Like Yo-You By Storm-- Tells of Bailing Out 9 Mi. Above Earth\", ''Press-Telegram'' (Long Beach, CA), August 7, 1959, pB-10</ref>\n*Voters in [[Hawaii]] elected their first state governor ([[William F. Quinn]]), their first Congressman ([[Daniel K. Inouye]]), and their first United States Senators, [[Hiram L. Fong]] and [[Oren E. Long]].\n\n==July 29, 1959 (Wednesday)==\n*After passing both houses of Parliament, the Legitimacy Act of 1959 received royal assent in Britain, giving equal rights to children born out of wedlock.<ref>Stephen Michael Cretney, ''Family Law in the Twentieth Century: A History'' (Oxford University Press, 2003), pp552\u201354</ref>\n*Australia entered the \"[[Jet Age]]\", when [[Qantas]] became the first airline outside the United States to inaugurate [[Boeing 707]] services, flying from Sydney, Australia, to San Francisco.<ref>John Gunn, ''High Corridors: Qantas, 1954\u20131970'' (University of Queensland Press, 1988), p155</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Sanjay Dutt]], award-winning Bollywood actor and politician, in [[Bombay]] (now [[Mumbai]])\n\n==July 30, 1959 (Thursday)==\n*The [[United Nations Medal]] was established for service, and is awarded for at least six months service with UN forces. The medal can be awarded to American servicemen as of 1964.<ref>Keith E. Bonn, ''Army Officer's Guide'' (Stackpole Books, 2005), p561</ref>\n*[[Robert Noyce]] of the [[Fairchild Semiconductor]] company filed a patent application for his invention of an [[integrated circuit]] that could be mass-produced.  On April 25, 1961, he would receive U.S. Patent 2,981,877 and, along with [[Jack Kilby]] who had applied for a patent for the original IC five months earlier, would receive the [[Nobel Prize in Physics]] in 2000.  <ref>Arjun N. Saxena, ''Invention of Integrated Circuits: Untold Important Facts'' (World Scientific, 2009) pp72-74</ref> \n*'''Died:''' \n**[[Mar\u00eda Natividad Venegas de la Torre]], 91, Mexican nun who was canonized as a Roman Catholic saint in 2000\n**[[Cho Bong-am]], who had been South Korea's Minister of Agriculture in 1948, and had run for President in 1956, was executed for \"treason against the state\".<ref>Andrew C. Nahm and James E. Hoare, ''Historical Dictionary of the Republic of Korea'' (Scarecrow Press, 2004), p21</ref>\n\n==July 31, 1959 (Friday)==\n*[[Euzkadi Ta Askatasuna]] (ETA), the Basque separatist organization, was founded in Spain. In its first 40 years, ETA's paramilitary attacks killed more than 800 people and wounded thousands.<ref>Wayne Anderson, ''The ETA: Spain's Basque Terrorists'' (Rosen Publishing Group, 2003), p18</ref>\n*Article 356 of the Constitution of India was invoked, providing for [[President's Rule]] of an Indian state, was invoked to depose the Communist government of the State of Kerala.<ref>Rabindra Kumar Sethy, ''Political Crisis and President's Rule in an Indian State'' (APH Publishing, 2003), p72</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Events by month links}}\n\n[[Category:1959|*1959-07]]\n[[Category:July|1959]]\n[[Category:Months in the 1950s|*1959-07]]\n", "name_user": "Alekol", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eJuly 15, 1959 (Wednesday)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/July_1959"}
{"title_page": "Alexandros Konstantidis", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name= \u0391\u03bb\u03b5\u03be \u039a\u03c9\u03bd\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03bd\u03af\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2\n| image =\n| fullname = Alexandros Konstantidis\n| height =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1988|11|03}}\n| birth_place = [[Dortmund]], [[West Germany]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber =\n| position = [[Midfielder (association football)|Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = 2000\u20132004 \n| youthyears2 = 2004\u20132007\n| youthclubs1 = [[Borussia Dortmund]] \n| youthclubs2 = [[Panathinaikos FC|Panathinaikos]]\n| years1 = 2007\u20132008 | clubs1 = [[Panathinaikos FC|Panathinaikos]]| caps1 = 1  | goals1 = 0 \n| years2 = 2007\u20132008 | clubs2 = \u2192 [[Koropi F.C.]] (loan)          | caps2 = 21 | goals2 = 0  \n| years3 = 2008\u20132009 | clubs3 = [[Apollon Smyrni F.C.]]           | caps3 = 19 | goals3 = 1 \n| years4 = 2009\u20132010 | clubs4 = [[Panserraikos]]                  | caps4 =    | goals4 =  \n| years5 = 2010\u20132011 | clubs5 = [[Ag. Dimitrios F.C.]]            | caps5 =    | goals5 =  \n| years6 = 2011\u20132012 | clubs6 = [[Iraklis Thessaloniki F.C.]]     | caps6 =    | goals6 =\n\n| nationalyears1 = 2008\u20132009\n| nationalteam1 = [[Greece national under-21 football team|Greece Under 21]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 11  \n| nationalgoals1 = 2 \n| pcupdate =\n| ntupdate =\n}}\n'''Alexandros Konstantidis''' (born 3 November 1988) is a [[Greece|Greek]] footballer currently playing for [[Panserraikos]].\n\n==Career==\nKonstantidis began his career with [[Panathinaikos FC|Panathinaikos]] and played in season 2007/2008 on loan for [[Koropi F.C.]]. He turned back in July 2008 to [[Panathinaikos FC]] and played for the team until June 2008,<ref>[http://katowice.gazeta.pl/katowice/1,35027,7256120,To_jest_talent__Kibice_niebieskich_az_wstawali_z_miejsc.html To jest talent! Kibice niebieskich a\u017c wstawali z miejsc]</ref> before signed in August for [[Apollon Smyrni F.C.]]. After one year with [[Apollon Smyrni F.C.]] was in summer 2009 released and signed after a difficult trial with [[Ruch Chorzow]],<ref>[http://www.pilkarskidziennik.pl/polska/ekstraklasa/18740-konstantinidis-chce-zostac-w-ruchu.html Konstantinidis chce zosta\u0107 w Ruchu]</ref> for [[Panserraikos]] who scored his first goal for his new team on 15 November 2009.<ref>[http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/intligen/intwettbewerbe/division-a-GR/2009-10/9/986493/livematch_fc-rhodos_panserraikos.html FC Rhodos - Panserraikos 2:3, B Ethniki, Saison 2009/10]</ref>\n\n==International career==\nKonstantinidis is former member of the [[Greece national under-21 football team]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sportslaski.pl/Grek-przeszedl-badania-i-odlecial,sport-slaski,13685,info.html |title=Grek przeszed\u0142 badania i odlecia\u0142 - Wiadomo\u015bci - sport \u015bl\u0105ski |access-date=26 January 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100120051659/http://www.sportslaski.pl/Grek-przeszedl-badania-i-odlecial,sport-slaski,13685,info.html |archive-date=20 January 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{soccerway}}\n* [http://www.ogol.com.br/jogador/alexandros_konstantinidis/atual/ficha/0/default/39110 Konstantinidis :: Alexandros Konstantinidis :: ogol.com.br]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [http://www.onsports.gr/onstats/?url=/soccer/player/main.php&sport-select=soccer&player-select=8793 Onsports.gr Profile]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130818071528/http://myplayer.gr/index.php?option=com_myplayer_players&view=player&player=1864 Myplayer.gr Profile]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Konstantidis, Alexandros}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Greek footballers]]\n[[Category:Panathinaikos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Superleague Greece players]]\n[[Category:Borussia Dortmund players]]\n[[Category:German people of Greek descent]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name= \u0391\u03bb\u03b5\u03be \u039a\u03c9\u03bd\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03bd\u03af\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2\n| image =\n| fullname = Alexandros Konstantidis\n| height =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1988|11|03}}\n| birth_place = [[Dortmund]], [[West Germany]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber =\n| position = [[Midfielder (association football)|Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = 2000\u20132004 \n| youthyears2 = 2004\u20132007\n| youthclubs1 = [[Borussia Dortmund]] \n| youthclubs2 = [[Panathinaikos FC|Panathinaikos]]\n| years1 = 2007\u20132008 | clubs1 = [[Panathinaikos FC|Panathinaikos]]| caps1 = 1  | goals1 = 0 \n| years2 = 2007\u20132008 | clubs2 = \u2192 [[Koropi F.C.]] (loan)          | caps2 = 21 | goals2 = 0  \n| years3 = 2008\u20132009 | clubs3 = [[Apollon Smyrni F.C.]]           | caps3 = 19 | goals3 = 1 \n| years4 = 2009\u20132010 | clubs4 = [[Panserraikos]]                  | caps4 =    | goals4 =  \n| years5 = 2010\u20132011 | clubs5 = [[Ag. Dimitrios F.C.]]            | caps5 =    | goals5 =  \n| years6 = 2011\u20132012 | clubs6 = [[Iraklis Thessaloniki F.C.]]     | caps6 =    | goals6 =\n\n| nationalyears1 = 2008\u20132009\n| nationalteam1 = [[Greece national under-21 football team|Greece Under 21]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 11  \n| nationalgoals1 = 2 \n| pcupdate =\n| ntupdate =\n}}\n'''Alexandros Konstantidis''' (born 3 November 1988) is a [[Greece|Greek]] footballer currently playing for [[Panserraikos]].\n\n==Career==\nKonstantidis began his career with [[Panathinaikos FC|Panathinaikos]] and played in season 2007/2008 on loan for [[Koropi F.C.]]. He turned back in July 2008 to [[Panathinaikos FC]] and played for the team until June 2008,<ref>[http://katowice.gazeta.pl/katowice/1,35027,7256120,To_jest_talent__Kibice_niebieskich_az_wstawali_z_miejsc.html To jest talent! Kibice niebieskich a\u017c wstawali z miejsc]</ref> before sig