y:Superleague Greece players]]\n[[Category:Borussia Dortmund players]]\n[[Category:German people of Greek descent]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n", "name_user": "Pelmeen10", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexandros_Konstantidis"}
{"title_page": "MS Zaandam", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=MS Zaandam.JPG\n|Ship caption=''Zaandam'' in [[Glacier Bay]], [[Alaska]]\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship name=''Zaandam''\n|Ship owner=[[Carnival Corporation & plc]]\n|Ship operator=[[Holland America Line]]\n|Ship registry={{flagicon|Netherlands}} [[Rotterdam]]<ref name=\"csr\">{{csr|register=LR|id=9156527|shipname=Zaandam|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n|Ship route=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=*[[Fincantieri]] Cantieri Navali Italiana SpA, [[Marghera]], [[Italy]]\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=6036\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=26 June 1998<ref name=\"csr\" />\n|Ship launched=29 April 1999\n|Ship completed=6 April 2000<ref name=\"csr\" />\n|Ship christened=May 2000\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship maiden voyage=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship identification=* [[Call sign#Ships and boats|Call sign]] PDAN\n* {{IMO Number|9156527}}\n* [[Maritime Mobile Service Identity|MMSI no:]] 246442000\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=Quarantined\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=[[Holland America Line#Rotterdam class (R class)|''Rotterdam''-class]] [[cruise ship]]\n|Ship tonnage=* {{GT|61,396}}<ref name=csr />\n* {{NetT|31457}}<ref name=csr />\n* {{DWT|6150}}<ref name=csr />\n|Ship length={{cvt|237|m|ft}}<ref name=\"csr\" />\n|Ship beam={{cvt|32.28|m|ft}}<ref name=\"csr\" />\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draught={{cvt|8.1|m|ft}}<ref name=\"csr\" />\n|Ship decks=10 decks\n|Ship power     = 42,000{{nbsp}}kW<ref name=\"csr\" />\n|Ship propulsion= * [[Diesel-electric]]\n*2{{nbsp}}\u00d7{{nbsp}}[[Variable-pitch propeller]]s<ref name=\"RINA\">{{csr|register=RINA|id=9156527|shipname=Zaandam|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n|Ship speed     = {{convert|23|kn|lk=in}}\n|Ship capacity  = 1,432 passengers\n|Ship crew      = 615\n|Ship notes     =\n}}\n|}\n\n'''MS ''Zaandam''''' is a [[cruise ship]] owned and operated by [[Holland America Line]], named for the city of [[Zaandam]], [[Netherlands]] near [[Amsterdam]]. It was built by [[Fincantieri]] in [[Marghera]], Italy and delivered in 2000. ''Zaandam'' is part of the [[Holland America Line#Rotterdam class (R class)|''Rotterdam'' class]] and a [[sister ship]] to {{MS|Volendam||2}}, {{MS|Rotterdam||2}}, and {{MS|Amsterdam||2}}.\n\n==Design and description==\n[[File:Passenger ship Zaandam in drydock.jpg|thumb|left|''Zaandam'' in dry dock]]\nThe ship has a [[gross tonnage]] (GT) of 61,396, a [[net tonnage]] (NT) of 31,224 and measures {{DWT|7321|disp=long}}. The ship is {{convert|780|ft|m|order=flip|1}} long with a [[Beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|106|ft|5|in|m|order=flip|1}} and a [[Draft (hull)|draught]] of {{convert|27|ft|1|in|m|order=flip|1}}.{{sfn|Holland America}}{{sfn|Port State Information Exchange}}{{efn|Holland America has the beam at {{convert|105|ft|8|in|m|order=flip|1}},{{sfn|Holland America}} while Equasis has the deadweight tonnage at the original 6,150.{{sfn|Equasis}}}} As built the vessel had a GT of 60,906 and DWT 6,150. As built ''Zaandam'' was {{convert|237|m|ftin}} [[Length overall|long overall]] and {{convert|202.8|m|ftin}} [[Length between perpendiculars|between perpendiculars]] with a beam of {{convert|32.3|m|ftin}}.{{sfn|Miramar Ship Index}}\n\nThe vessel is powered by a [[diesel-electric]] system turning two [[propeller]] shafts creating {{convert|37500|kW|lk=on}}.{{sfn|Ward|2019|p=1631}} This gives ''Zaandam'' a maximum speed of {{convert|23|kn|lk=in}}.{{sfn|Holland America}} The vessel can accommodate 1,432 passengers and has 607 crew.{{sfn|Holland America}}{{sfn|Ward|2019|p=1631}}{{efn|Ward has the crew numbering 650.{{sfn|Ward|2019|p=1631}}}} The 716 cabins range in size from in size from {{convert|10.5|-|104.6|m2|abbr=on}}, of which 197 have a balcony. ''Zaandam'' has a musical theme and is decorated with artifacts and memorabilia from different musical genres. Items such as a [[Baroque]]-style [[dutch people|Dutch]] [[pipe organ]] and guitars signed by the [[Rolling Stones]], [[Carlos Santana]] and [[Queen (band)|Queen]] can be seen.{{sfn|Ward|2019|p=1631}} One of the centre stairways also has a saxophone signed by former [[United States President]] [[Bill Clinton]] on the mouthpiece.{{sfn|Ward|2019|p=1631}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Zaandam Ship Details |url=http://www.cruiseabout.com.au/cruiselines/Holland_America_Line/ships/Zaandam.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ixPxVgIW?url=http://www.cruiseabout.com.au/cruiselines/Holland_America_Line/ships/Zaandam.html |work=Cruiseabout |accessdate=11 August 2009 |archivedate=11 August 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref>  \n\n==Construction and career==\nThe cruise ship was constructed by [[Fincantieri]] Cantieri Navali Italiana SpA at [[Marghera]], Italy with the [[yard number]] 6036 and the [[keel]] was [[Keel laying|laid down]] on 26 June 1998. The vessel was [[Ceremonial ship launching|launched]] on 29 April 1999 and completed on 6 April 2000.{{sfn|Miramar Ship Index}} ''Zaandam'' was christened by [[Mary-Kate Olsen|Mary-Kate]] and [[Ashley Olsen]] in May 2000.{{sfn|Holland America}} The ship is [[Ship registration|registered]] in the Netherlands and owned and operated by the [[Holland America Line]].{{sfn|Equasis}}\n\n''Zaandam'' currently sails through Canada and [[New England]] during the summer and during the winter sails Mexico and [[Hawaii]]. In December and January, ''Zaandam'' cruises the Antarctic and South America.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollandamerica.com/en_US/cruise-destinations/south-america-antarctica.html|title=South America & Antarctica Cruises & Vacations |website=hollandamerica.com |language=en-US|access-date=25 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 June 2018, the  U.S. [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] reported that 73 people became ill on ''Zaandam'' due to an outbreak of [[norovirus]]. The ship was on a voyage from [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]] to [[Alaska]] at the time.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.king5.com/article/news/local/73-sickened-on-cruise-ship-that-left-seattle-for-alaska/281-567129143 |title=73 sickened on cruise ship that left Seattle for Alaska |work=King5.com |agency=Associated Press |date=24 June 2018 |access-date=25 June 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Coronavirus pandemic===\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships#Zaandam}}\nOn 7 March 2020 ''Zaandam'' departed [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]], sailing for [[San Antonio, Chile]].{{sfn|Harris|2020}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/27/stranded-at-sea-cruise-ships-around-the-world-are-adrift-as-ports-turn-them-away |title='Stranded at sea': cruise ships around the world are adrift as ports turn them away |work=The Guardian |last=McCormick |first=Erin |date=27 March 2020 |access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> It became stranded off the coast of Chile after being denied entry to ports since 14 March. Of the 1,829 people (1,243 passengers, 586 crew) aboard, 13 passengers and 100+ crew members had fallen ill with \"flu-like symptoms.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/cruise-ship-holland-america-covid-19-canadians-1.5506674 |title='Get us the hell off': Canadians on board stranded cruise ship with 42 sick passengers, crew |last=Harris |first=Sophia |work=CBC News |date=23 March 2020 |access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> As of 24 March, the vessel was sailing for [[Port Everglades, Florida]] hoping to dock on 30 March. The total of sick persons aboard had risen to 77  as of 24 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/business/tourism-cruises/article241457871.html |title=A cruise ship with 77 sick on board hopes to dock in Port Everglades on March 30 |work=Miami Herald |last=Dolven |first=Taylor |date=24 March 2020  |access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> Four passengers died while waiting for permission to transit the [[Panama Canal]] with the number of sick aboard climbing to 148. Holland America dispatched [[sister ship]] {{MS|Rotterdam||2}} to aid the ship by bringing supplies, additional medical staff, and [[COVID-19]] tests, and also with the intention of transferring healthy passengers onto ''Rotterdam''.{{sfn|Harris|2020}} \n\nOn 27 March, ''Zaandam'' was denied transit through the Panama Canal due to the number of sick people on board.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.plenglish.com/index.php?o=rn&id=53903&SEO=zaandam-cruise-ship-denied-crossing-panama-canal-due-to-quarantine |title=Zaandam cruise ship denied crossing Panama Canal due to quarantine |work=Prensa Latina |date=27 March 2020 |access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> On 28 March 2020, however, both ''Zaandam'' and the accompanying vessel ''Rotterdam'' were cleared by the Panama Department of Health to transit through the Panama Canal towards their destination in Florida.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2020/03/28/covid-19-holland-america-splitting-up-its-healthy-sick-passengers/2933381001/ |title=Coronavirus: Holland America's Zaandam, Rotterdam get permission to transit Panama Canal |last=Hines |first=Morgan |work=USA Today |date=28 March 2020 |access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>   ''Rotterdam'' had followed ''Zaandam'' through the Panama Canal on its way to Port Everglades, in [[Fort Lauderdale]], Florida. An unstated number of passengers from ''Zaandam'' were transferred to the second vessel on 28 March 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2020/03/28/covid-19-holland-america-splitting-up-its-healthy-sick-passengers/2933381001/ |title=Coronavirus: Holland America's Zaandam, Rotterdam get OK to transit Panama Canal for Florida |date=28 March 2020 |work=USA Today |last=Hines |first=Morgan |access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/30/us/zaandam-cruise-ship-sick-passengers/index.html |title=A cruise ship headed to Florida has reported more sick people on board after 4 die and 2 test positive for Covid-19 |date=30 March 2020 |work=CNN |last=Silverman |first=Hollie |access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-52072703?intlink_from_url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world/latin_america&link_location=live-reporting-story |title=Coronavirus: Cruise ship off Panama coast transfers passengers |work=BBC |date=29 March 2020 |access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> At that time, the crew of ''Zaandam'' included four physicians and four nurses while ''Rotterdam''{{'}}s roster included two physicians and four nurses.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2020/03/28/passengers-on-cruise-ship-in-panama-transferred-to-new-vessel.html |title=Passengers on cruise ship in Panama transferred to new vessel |last=Winsa |first=Patty |date=28 March 2020 |work=Toronto Star|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nBy 31 March 2020, the number reported as being \"ill\" had increased to 193.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/covid-19-zaandam-cruise-ship-ill-stranded-1.5515811 |title=More COVID-19 cases on stranded cruise ship with 4 dead. Cruise line pleads for help |date=31 March 2020 |work=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> By 31 March, ''Rotterdam'' had taken almost 1,400 people from ''Zaandam''; none had flu-like symptoms, 450 passengers and 602 crew members on its sister ship.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/national-international/ships-with-people-from-ill-fated-cruise-beg-florida-to-dock/2352797/ |title=Florida Docking Plan in the Works for Ill-Fated Cruise Ships |date=31 March 2020 |work=NBC New York |last=Gomez |first=Adriana Gomez |last2=Kennedy |first2=Kelli |last-author-amp=y |agency=Associated Press |access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 30 March 2020, Holland America had not received permission to dock either vessel at Fort Lauderdale as planned. According to an [[Associated Press]] report, the city's mayor, Dean Trantalis, \"said he didn't want the ship to dock near his city, at least without extensive precautions.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wfla.com/community/health/coronavirus/authority-stranded-ships-begin-transiting-panama-canal/ |title=Authority: Stranded ships begin transiting Panama Canal |date=30 March 2020 |work=WFLA News Channel 8 |agency=Associated Press |access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=nealdolven>{{cite web |url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/coronavirus/article241605286.html |title=Fort Lauderdale mayor not ready to accept the coronavirus-hit Zaandam at Port Everglades |date=30 March 2020 |work=Miami Herald |last=Neal |first=David J. |last2=Dolven |first2=Taylor |last-author-amp=y |access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> The governor of Florida was also hesitant to accept ''Zaandam'' at Fort Lauderdale because the state already had so much to deal with during the pandemic; as of 31 March 2020, a decision had not yet been made. The president of Holland America made a public plea for acceptance of the ship and expressed concern that various ports in several countries had been reluctant to provide provisions and medical supplies.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/covid-19-zaandam-cruise-ship-ill-stranded-1.5515811 |title=More COVID-19 cases on stranded cruise ship with 4 dead. Cruise line pleads for help |date=31 March 2020 |work=CBC News |access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> During the governor's press conference on 30 March, he said that the best solution might be to send medical assistance to the ship.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/health-pmn/cruise-ship-with-coronavirus-outbreak-sails-to-uncertain-florida-welcome |title=Cruise ship with coronavirus outbreak sails to uncertain Florida welcome |date=31 March 2020 |work=National Post |access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> On 1 April, the governor relented by saying that citizens of Florida could disembark when the ship arrived off the state. 190 passengers and crew reported \"flu-like\" symptoms and eight tested positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/04/01/us/holland-america-zaandam-cruise-ship-florida/index.html |title=Florida governor: We'll take state residents only from Zaandam cruise ship |last=Sanchez |first=Ray |last2=Flores |first2=Rosa |last3=Weisfeldt |first3=Sara |last-author-amp=y |work=CNN |date=1 April 2020 |access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nPresident [[Donald Trump]] said on 1 April 2020 that \"we have to help the people\" [on the ships] and that discussions were underway about Canada and the United Kingdom \"arranging flights to retrieve their citizens from the ship\". News reports on 2 April stated that the ships would be allowed to dock at Port Everglades that afternoon. Nine passengers were to be taken to local hospitals but 45 others who are ill would not be disembarking. The cruise line was making arrangements for passengers from other countries to leave via chartered aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/cruise-ship-sick-passengers-sister-ship-will-be-allowed-dock-n1174796 |title=Cruise ship with sick passengers and sister ship will be allowed to dock in Florida |last=Burke |first=Minyvonne |work=NBC News |date=2 April 2020 |access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Citations==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{csr|register=E|id=9156527|shipname=Zaandam|accessdate=27 March 2020 |ref={{sfnref|Equasis}}}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://www.bradenton.com/news/coronavirus/article241559956.html |last=Harris |first=Alex |title=Four passengers died on Zaandam cruise ship with 148 people sick with flu-like symptoms |work=Bradenton Herald |date=27 March 2020 |access-date=27 March 2020 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |title= Fast Fact Sheet \u2013 MS Zaandam |url=http://book.hollandamerica.com/pdfs/media/factsheets/FastFacts_Zaandam.pdf |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5ixQXnazc?url=http://book.hollandamerica.com/pdfs/media/factsheets/FastFacts_Zaandam.pdf |archive-date=11 August 2009 |publisher=[[Holland America]] |access-date=27 March 2020  |url-status=dead |ref={{sfnref|Holland America}}}}\n* {{csr|register=MSI|id=9156527|shipname=Zaandam|accessdate=27 March 2020|ref={{sfnref|Miramar Ship Index}}}}\n* {{csr|register=PSIX|id=4746|shipname=Zaandam|accessdate=27 March 2020 |ref={{sfnref|Port State Information Exchange}}}}\n* {{cite book |last=Ward |first=Douglas |year=2019 |title=Berlitz Complete Guide to Cruising & Cruise Ships 2020 |edition=28th |publisher=Berlitz |location=Singapore |isbn=978-1-78573-250-8 |ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|IMO 9156527}}\n* {{official website|http://hollandamerica.com/cruiseships/Zaandam}}\n* [http://www.sailwx.info/shiptrack/shipposition.phtml?call=PDAN Ship Position]\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.vesseltracker.com/en/Ships/Zaandam-9156527.html |title= Zaandam (IMO: 9156527) |work=vesseltracker.com}}\n\n{{List of ships built by Fincantieri}}\n{{Holland America Ships}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zaandam}}\n[[Category:1999 ships]]\n[[Category:Cruise ships]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 2009]]\n[[Category:Ships of the Holland America Line]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Venice]]\n[[Category:Ships built by Fincantieri]]\n[[Category:Ships involved in the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=MS Zaandam.JPG\n|Ship caption=''Zaandam'' in [[Glacier Bay]], [[Alaska]]\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship name=''Zaandam''\n|Ship owner=[[Carnival Corporation & plc]]\n|Ship operator=[[Holland America Line]]\n|Ship registry={{flagicon|Netherlands}} [[Rotterdam]]<ref name=\"csr\">{{csr|register=LR|id=9156527|shipname=Zaandam|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n|Ship route=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=*[[Fincantieri]] Cantieri Navali Italiana SpA, [[Marghera]], [[Italy]]\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=6036\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=26 June 1998<ref name=\"csr\" />\n|Ship launched=29 April 1999\n|Ship completed=6 April 2000<ref name=\"csr\" />\n|Ship christened=May 2000\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship maiden voyage=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship identification=* [[Call sign#Ships and boats|Call sign]] PDAN\n* {{IMO Number|9156527}}\n* [[Maritime Mobile Service Identity|MMSI no:]] 246442000\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=Quarantined\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=[[Holland America Line#Rotterdam class (R class)|''Rotterdam''-class]] [[cruise ship]]\n|Ship tonnage=* {{GT|61,396}}<ref name=csr />\n* {{NetT|31457}}<ref name=csr />\n* {{DWT|6150}}<ref name=csr />\n|Ship length={{cvt|237|m|ft}}<ref name=\"csr\" />\n|Ship beam={{cvt|32.28|m|ft}}<ref name=\"csr\" />\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draught={{cvt|8.1|m|ft}}<ref name=\"csr\" />\n|Ship decks=10 decks\n|Ship power     = 42,000{{nbsp}}kW<ref name=\"csr\" />\n|Ship propulsion= * [[Diesel-electric]]\n*2{{nbsp}}\u00d7{{nbsp}}[[Variable-pitch propeller]]s<ref name=\"RINA\">{{csr|register=RINA|id=9156527|shipname=Zaandam|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n|Ship speed     = {{convert|23|kn|lk=in}}\n|Ship capacity  = 1,432 passengers\n|Ship crew      = 615\n|Ship notes     =\n}}\n|}\n\n'''MS ''Zaandam''''' is a [[cruise ship]] owned and operated by [[Holland America Line]], named for the city of [[Zaandam]], [[Netherlands]] near [[Amsterdam]]. It was built by [[Fincantieri]] in [[Marghera]], Italy and delivered in 2000. ''Zaandam'' is part of the [[Holland America Line#Rotterdam class (R class)|''Rotterdam'' class]] and a [[sister ship]] to {{MS|Volendam||2}}, {{MS|Rotterdam||2}}, and {{MS|Amsterdam||2}}.\n\n==Design and description==\n[[File:Passenger ship Zaandam in drydock.jpg|thumb|left|''Zaandam'' in dry dock]]\nThe ship has a [[gross tonnage]] (GT) of 61,396, a [[net tonnage]] (NT) of 31,224 and measures {{DWT|7321|disp=long}}. The ship is {{convert|780|ft|m|order=flip|1}} long with a [[Beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|106|ft|5|in|m|order=flip|1}} and a [[Draft (hull)|draught]] of {{convert|27|ft|1|in|m|order=flip|1}}.{{sfn|Holland America}}{{sfn|Port State Information Exchange}}{{efn|Holland America has the beam at {{convert|105|ft|8|in|m|order=flip|1}},{{sfn|Holland America}} while Equasis has the deadweight tonnage at the original 6,150.{{sfn|Equasis}}}} As built the vessel had a GT of 60,906 and DWT 6,150. As built ''Zaandam'' was {{convert|237|m|ftin}} [[Length overall|long overall]] and {{convert|202.8|m|ftin}} [[Length between perpendiculars|between perpendiculars]] with a beam of {{convert|32.3|m|ftin}}.{{sfn|Miramar Ship Index}}\n\nThe vessel is powered by a [[diesel-electric]] system turning two [[propeller]] shafts creating {{convert|37500|kW|lk=on}}.{{sfn|Ward|2019|p=1631}} This gives ''Zaandam'' a maximum speed of {{convert|23|kn|lk=in}}.{{sfn|Holland America}} The vessel can accommodate 1,432 passengers and has 607 crew.{{sfn|Holland America}}{{sfn|Ward|2019|p=1631}}{{efn|Ward has the crew numbering 650.{{sfn|Ward|2019|p=1631}}}} The 716 cabins range in size from in size from {{convert|10.5|-|104.6|m2|abbr=on}}, of which 197 have a balcony. ''Zaandam'' has a musical theme and is decorated with artifacts and memorabilia from different musical genres. Items such as a [[Baroque]]-style [[dutch people|Dutch]] [[pipe organ]] and guitars signed by the [[Rolling Stones]], [[Carlos Santana]] and [[Queen (band)|Queen]] can be seen.{{sfn|Ward|2019|p=1631}} One of the centre stairways also has a saxophone signed by former [[United States President]] [[Bill Clinton]] on the mouthpiece.{{sfn|Ward|2019|p=1631}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Zaandam Ship Details |url=http://www.cruiseabout.com.au/cruiselines/Holland_America_Line/ships/Zaandam.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ixPxVgIW?url=http://www.cruiseabout.com.au/cruiselines/Holland_America_Line/ships/Zaandam.html |work=Cruiseabout |accessdate=11 August 2009 |archivedate=11 August 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref>  \n\n==Construction and career==\nThe cruise ship was constructed by [[Fincantieri]] Cantieri Navali Italiana SpA at [[Marghera]], Italy with the [[yard number]] 6036 and the [[keel]] was [[Keel laying|laid down]] on 26 June 1998. The vessel was [[Ceremonial ship launching|launched]] on 29 April 1999 and completed on 6 April 2000.{{sfn|Miramar Ship Index}} ''Zaandam'' was christened by [[Mary-Kate Olsen|Mary-Kate]] and [[Ashley Olsen]] in May 2000.{{sfn|Holland America}} The ship is [[Ship registration|registered]] in the Netherlands and owned and operated by the [[Holland America Line]].{{sfn|Equasis}}\n\n''Zaandam'' currently sails through Canada and [[New England]] during the summer and during the winter sails Mexico and [[Hawaii]]. In December and January, ''Zaandam'' cruises the Antarctic and South America.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollandamerica.com/en_US/cruise-destinations/south-america-antarctica.html|title=South America & Antarctica Cruises & Vacations |website=hollandamerica.com |language=en-US|access-date=25 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 June 2018, the  U.S. [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] reported that 73 people became ill on ''Zaandam'' due to an outbreak of [[norovirus]]. The ship was on a voyage from [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]] to [[Alaska]] at the time.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.king5.com/article/news/local/73-sickened-on-cruise-ship-that-left-seattle-for-alaska/281-567129143 |title=73 sickened on cruise ship that left Seattle for Alaska |work=King5.com |agency=Associated Press |date=24 June 2018 |access-date=25 June 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Coronavirus pandemic===\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships#Zaandam}}\nOn 7 March 2020 ''Zaandam'' departed [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]], sailing for [[San Antonio, Chile]].{{sfn|Harris|2020}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/27/stranded-at-sea-cruise-ships-around-the-world-are-adrift-as-ports-turn-them-away |title='Stranded at sea': cruise ships around the world are adrift as ports turn them away |work=The Guardian |last=McCormick |first=Erin |date=27 March 2020 |access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> It became stranded off the coast of Chile after being denied entry to ports since 14 March. Of the 1,829 people (1,243 passengers, 586 crew) aboard, 13 passengers and 100+ crew members had fallen ill with \"flu-like symptoms.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/cruise-ship-holland-america-covid-19-canadians-1.5506674 |title='Get us the hell off': Canadians on board stranded cruise ship with 42 sick passengers, crew |last=Harris |first=Sophia |work=CBC News |date=23 March 2020 |access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> As of 24 March, the vessel was sailing for [[Port Everglades, Florida]] hoping to dock on 30 March. The total of sick persons aboard had risen to 77  as of 24 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/business/tourism-cruises/article241457871.html |title=A cruise ship with 77 sick on board hopes to dock in Port Everglades on March 30 |work=Miami Herald |last=Dolven |first=Taylor |date=24 March 2020  |access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> Four passengers died while waiting for permission to transit the [[Panama Canal]] with the number of sick aboard climbing to 148. Holland America dispatched [[sister ship]] {{MS|Rotterdam||2}} to aid the ship by bringing supplies, additional medical staff, and [[COVID-19]] tests, and also with the intention of transferring healthy passengers onto ''Rotterdam''.{{sfn|Harris|2020}} \n\nOn 27 March, ''Zaandam'' was denied transit through the Panama Canal due to the number of sick people on board.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.plenglish.com/index.php?o=rn&id=53903&SEO=zaandam-cruise-ship-denied-crossing-panama-canal-due-to-quarantine |title=Zaandam cruise ship denied crossing Panama Canal due to quarantine |work=Prensa Latina |date=27 March 2020 |access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> On 28 March 2020, however, both ''Zaandam'' and the accompanying vessel ''Rotterdam'' were cleared by the Panama Department of Health to transit through the Panama Canal towards their destination in Florida.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2020/03/28/covid-19-holland-america-splitting-up-its-healthy-sick-passengers/2933381001/ |title=Coronavirus: Holland America's Zaandam, Rotterdam get permission to transit Panama Canal |last=Hines |first=Morgan |work=USA Today |date=28 March 2020 |access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>   ''Rotterdam'' had followed ''Zaandam'' through the Panama Canal on its way to Port Everglades, in [[Fort Lauderdale]], Florida. An unstated number of passengers from ''Zaandam'' were transferred to the second vessel on 28 March 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2020/03/28/covid-19-holland-america-splitting-up-its-healthy-sick-passengers/2933381001/ |title=Coronavirus: Holland America's Zaandam, Rotterdam get OK to transit Panama Canal for Florida |date=28 March 2020 |work=USA Today |last=Hines |first=Morgan |access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/30/us/zaandam-cruise-ship-sick-passengers/index.html |title=A cruise ship headed to Florida has reported more sick people on board after 4 die and 2 test positive for Covid-19 |date=30 March 2020 |work=CNN |last=Silverman |first=Hollie |access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-52072703?intlink_from_url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world/latin_america&link_location=live-reporting-story |title=Coronavirus: Cruise ship off Panama coast transfers passengers |work=BBC |date=29 March 2020 |access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> At that time, the crew of ''Zaandam'' included four physicians and four nurses while ''Rotterdam''{{'}}s roster included two physicians and four nurses.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2020/03/28/passengers-on-cruise-ship-in-panama-transferred-to-new-vessel.html |title=Passengers on cruise ship in Panama transferred to new vessel |last=Winsa |first=Patty |date=28 March 2020 |work=Toronto Star|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nBy 31 March 2020, the number reported as being \"ill\" had increased to 193.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/covid-19-zaandam-cruise-ship-ill-stranded-1.5515811 |title=More COVID-19 cases on stranded cruise ship with 4 dead. Cruise line pleads for help |date=31 March 2020 |work=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> By 31 March, ''Rotterdam'' had taken almost 1,400 people from ''Zaandam''; none had flu-like symptoms, 450 passengers and 602 crew members on its sister ship.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/national-international/ships-with-people-from-ill-fated-cruise-beg-florida-to-dock/2352797/ |title=Florida Docking Plan in the Works for Ill-Fated Cruise Ships |date=31 March 2020 |work=NBC New York |last=Gomez |first=Adriana Gomez |last2=Kennedy |first2=Kelli |last-author-amp=y |agency=Associated Press |access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 30 March 2020, Holland America had not received permission to dock either vessel at Fort Lauderdale as planned. According to an [[Associated Press]] report, the city's mayor, Dean Trantalis, \"said he didn't want the ship to dock near his city, at least without extensive precautions.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wfla.com/community/health/coronavirus/authority-stranded-ships-begin-transiting-panama-canal/ |title=Authority: Stranded ships begin transiting Panama Canal |date=30 March 2020 |work=WFLA News Channel 8 |agency=Associated Press |access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=nealdolven>{{cite web |url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/coronavirus/article241605286.html |title=Fort Lauderdale mayor not ready to accept the coronavirus-hit Zaandam at Port Everglades |date=30 March 2020 |work=Miami Herald |last=Neal |first=David J. |last2=Dolven |first2=Taylor |last-author-amp=y |access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> The governor of Florida was also hesitant to accept ''Zaandam'' at Fort Lauderdale because the state already had so much to deal with during the pandemic; as of 31 March 2020, a decision had not yet been made. The president of Holland America made a public plea for acceptance of the ship and expressed concern that various ports in several countries had been reluctant to provide provisions and medical supplies.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/covid-19-zaandam-cruise-ship-ill-stranded-1.5515811 |title=More COVID-19 cases on stranded cruise ship with 4 dead. Cruise line pleads for help |date=31 March 2020 |work=CBC News |access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> During the governor's press conference on 30 March, he said that the best solution might be to send medical assistance to the ship.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/health-pmn/cruise-ship-with-coronavirus-outbreak-sails-to-uncertain-florida-welcome |title=Cruise ship with coronavirus outbreak sails to uncertain Florida welcome |date=31 March 2020 |work=National Post |access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> On 1 April, the governor relented by saying that citizens of Florida could disembark when the ship arrived off the state. 190 passengers and crew reported \"flu-like\" symptoms and eight tested positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/04/01/us/holland-america-zaandam-cruise-ship-florida/index.html |title=Florida governor: We'll take state residents only from Zaandam cruise ship |last=Sanchez |first=Ray |last2=Flores |first2=Rosa |last3=Weisfeldt |first3=Sara |last-author-amp=y |work=CNN |date=1 April 2020 |access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nPresident Donald Trump said on 1 April 2020 that \"we have to help the people\" [on the ships] and that discussions were underway about Canada and the United Kingdom \"arranging flights to retrieve their citizens from the ship\". News reports on 2 April stated that the ships would be allowed to dock at Port Everglades that afternoon. Nine passengers were to be taken to local hospitals but 45 others who are ill would not be disembarking. The cruise line was making arrangements for passengers from other countries to leave via chartered aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/cruise-ship-sick-passengers-sister-ship-will-be-allowed-dock-n1174796 |title=Cruise ship with sick passengers and sister ship will be allowed to dock in Florida |last=Burke |first=Minyvonne |work=NBC News |date=2 April 2020 |access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Citations==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{csr|register=E|id=9156527|shipname=Zaandam|accessdate=27 March 2020 |ref={{sfnref|Equasis}}}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://www.bradenton.com/news/coronavirus/article241559956.html |last=Harris |first=Alex |title=Four passengers died on Zaandam cruise ship with 148 people sick with flu-like symptoms |work=Bradenton Herald |date=27 March 2020 |access-date=27 March 2020 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |title= Fast Fact Sheet \u2013 MS Zaandam |url=http://book.hollandamerica.com/pdfs/media/factsheets/FastFacts_Zaandam.pdf |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5ixQXnazc?url=http://book.hollandamerica.com/pdfs/media/factsheets/FastFacts_Zaandam.pdf |archive-date=11 August 2009 |publisher=[[Holland America]] |access-date=27 March 2020  |url-status=dead |ref={{sfnref|Holland America}}}}\n* {{csr|register=MSI|id=9156527|shipname=Zaandam|accessdate=27 March 2020|ref={{sfnref|Miramar Ship Index}}}}\n* {{csr|register=PSIX|id=4746|shipname=Zaandam|accessdate=27 March 2020 |ref={{sfnref|Port State Information Exchange}}}}\n* {{cite book |last=Ward |first=Douglas |year=2019 |title=Berlitz Complete Guide to Cruising & Cruise Ships 2020 |edition=28th |publisher=Berlitz |location=Singapore |isbn=978-1-78573-250-8 |ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|IMO 9156527}}\n* {{official website|http://hollandamerica.com/cruiseships/Zaandam}}\n* [http://www.sailwx.info/shiptrack/shipposition.phtml?call=PDAN Ship Position]\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.vesseltracker.com/en/Ships/Zaandam-9156527.html |title= Zaandam (IMO: 9156527) |work=vesseltracker.com}}\n\n{{List of ships built by Fincantieri}}\n{{Holland America Ships}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zaandam}}\n[[Category:1999 ships]]\n[[Category:Cruise ships]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 2009]]\n[[Category:Ships of the Holland America Line]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Venice]]\n[[Category:Ships built by Fincantieri]]\n[[Category:Ships involved in the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "Llammakey", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCoronavirus pandemic:added link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MS_Zaandam"}
{"title_page": "Anthony Fauci", "text_new": "{{pp-protect|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American immunologist}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name = Anthony Fauci\n|honorific-suffix = [[Doctor of Medicine|MD]]\n|image = Anthony S. Fauci, M.D., NIAID Director (26759498706).jpg\n|caption =Fauci in 2007\n|office = Director of the [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]]\n|president = [[Ronald Reagan]]<br>[[George H.W. Bush]]<br>[[Bill Clinton]]<br>[[George W. Bush]]<br>[[Barack Obama]]<br>[[Donald Trump]]\n|term_start = November 2, 1984\n|term_end = \n|predecessor = [[Richard M. Krause]]\n|successor = \n|birth_name = Anthony Stephen Fauci\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1940|12|24}}\n|birth_place = [[New York City]], U.S.\n|death_date = \n|death_place = \n|education = [[College of the Holy Cross]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br>[[Cornell University]] ([[Doctor of Medicine|MD]])\n|spouse = {{marriage|[[Christine Grady]]|1985}}\n|children = 3\n|awards = [[Maxwell Finland Award]] (1989)<br/>[[Ernst Jung Prize]] (1995)<br/>[[Lasker Award]] (2007)<br/>[[Presidential Medal of Freedom|Medal of Freedom]] (2008)<br/>[[Robert Koch Prize]] (Gold, 2013)\n|module = {{infobox scientist\n|embed = yes\n|fields = [[Immunology]]\n|workplaces = [[National Institutes of Health]], [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]]}}\n}}\n'''Anthony Stephen Fauci''' ({{IPAc-en|pron|\u02c8|f|a\u028a|t\u0283|i|}}; born December 24, 1940) is an American physician and [[Immunology|immunologist]] who has served as the director of the [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]] (NIAID) since 1984. Since January 2020, he has been one of the lead members of the [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] addressing the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|in the United States]].\n\nAs a physician with the [[National Institutes of Health]] (NIH) of the United States, he has served public health in various capacities for over fifty years. He has made contributions to [[HIV/AIDS research]] and other immunodeficiencies, both as a scientist and as the head of the NIAID at the NIH. ''The New York Times'' called Fauci \"the nation's leading expert on infectious diseases\".<ref name=Grady>Grady, Denise, [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/08/health/fauci-coronavirus.html?searchResultPosition=1 \"Not His First Epidemic: Dr. Anthony Fauci Sticks to the Facts\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', March 8, 11, 2020.</ref>\n\n==Background and education==\n[[File:VOA Interview Dr. Anthony S. Fauci.webm|thumb|left|alt=Gray haired man wearing a tie and a medium blue oxford button down shirt, seated in front of framed press clippings and awards, interviewed by medium-length blond-haired female interviewer about age 60, wearing a gray suit and yellow blouse| [[Greta Van Susteren]] interviewed Fauci in 2018 (38:18 minutes)]]\nFauci was born December 24, 1940, in [[Brooklyn]], New York, to Stephen A. Fauci and Eugenia A. Fauci, owners of a pharmacy, where his father worked as the [[pharmacist]], his mother and sister worked the register, and Fauci delivered prescriptions.<ref name=MedalBio/> The pharmacy was located in the [[Dyker Heights]] section of Brooklyn.\n\nFauci's paternal grandparents, Antonino Fauci and Calogera Guardino, were from [[Sciacca]], Italy. His maternal grandmother, Raffaella Trematerra, from [[Naples]], Italy, was a seamstress.  His maternal grandfather, Giovanni Abys, was born in Switzerland and was an artist, noted for landscape and portrait painting, magazine illustrations (Italy) as well graphic design for commercial labels, including olive oil cans. His great-grandparents emigrated to the US in the late 19th century. Fauci grew up [[Catholic]].<ref name=MedalBio>{{cite journal|last1=Gallin|first1=John I.|title=Introduction of Anthony S. Fauci, MD|journal=Journal of Clinical Investigation|date=1 October 2007|volume=117|issue=10|pages=3131\u20133135|pmid=17909634|pmc=1994641|doi=10.1172/jci33692}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Fauci89: Transcription of oral history interview |url=http://history.nih.gov/NIHInOwnWords/assets/media/pdf/Fauci89.pdf |publisher=NIH |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409183210/https://history.nih.gov/NIHInOwnWords/assets/media/pdf/Fauci89.pdf |archivedate=April 9, 2016 |date=March 7, 1989}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://history.nih.gov/nihinownwords/docs/fauci2_01.html|title=In Their Own Words|website=history.nih.gov}}</ref>\n\nFauci attended [[Regis High School (New York City)|Regis High School]] in [[New York City]] where he graduated in 1958. He then enrolled at the [[College of the Holy Cross]] where he received a [[Bachelor of Science|BS]] in [[classics]] in 1962. Fauci then went on to attend [[Weill Cornell Medical College of Cornell University|Cornell University Medical College]] where he graduated first in his class with an [[Doctor of Medicine|MD]] in 1966.<ref name=MedalBio/> He then completed an internship and [[Residency (medicine)|residency]] at The [[New York Hospital-Cornell Medical Center]].<ref name=\"NIAID\">{{cite web|title=Biography Anthony S. Fauci, M.D. NIAID Director|url=http://www3.niaid.nih.gov/about/directors/biography/|publisher=NIAID|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071030171118/http://www3.niaid.nih.gov/about/directors/biography/|archivedate=October 30, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Dr Anthony Fauci-America's Man on Infectious Diseases-VoA.webm|thumb|left|alt=Gray haired man in wearing a suit and seated on a chair in a lab, mixed with shots of female coworkers working with laboratory equipment|Fauci discusses his work in 2020 (4 minutes)]]\nIn 1968, Fauci joined the National Institutes of Health as a clinical associate in the Laboratory of Clinical Investigation (LCI) at the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases.<ref name=\"pr1984\"/> In 1974, he became Head of the Clinical Physiology Section, LCI, and in 1980 was appointed Chief of the Laboratory of Immunoregulation. In 1984, he became Director of NIAID, a position which he was still holding in 2020.<ref name = Grady/> In that role he has the responsibility for an extensive research portfolio of basic and applied research on infectious and immune-mediated illnesses.<ref name=\"pr1984\">{{cite web |title=Dr. Anthony Fauci Named New NIAID Director |url=https://history.nih.gov/nihinownwords/assets/media/pdf/press/1984/PR_NIAID_1984_11_02.pdf |website=HHS News |accessdate=13 March 2020 |format=Press release |date=2 November 1984}}</ref> He has turned down several offers to lead his agency's parent, the NIH, and has been at the forefront of US efforts to contend with viral diseases like HIV, [[SARS]], the [[2009 swine flu pandemic]], [[MERS]], [[Ebola]] and the new coronavirus, [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Grady |first1=Denise |title=Not His First Epidemic: Dr. Anthony Fauci Sticks to the Facts |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/08/health/fauci-coronavirus.html |work=The New York Times |publisher=New York Times Company |date=8 March 2020 |location=New York}}</ref>\n\nHe played a significant role in the early 2000s in creating the [[President's Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief]]<ref>{{cite journal|last=Varmus|first=Harold|title=Making PEPFAR|journal=Science & Diplomacy|date=1 December 2013 |volume=2|issue=4|url=http://www.sciencediplomacy.org/article/2013/making-pepfar}}</ref> and in driving development of [[biodefense]] drugs and vaccines following the [[September 11 attacks|9/11 terrorist attacks]].<ref>Bernard Wysocki Jr for The Wall Street Journal. December 6, 2005 [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB113383825463714813 Agency Chief Spurs Bioterror Research \u2013 And Controversy]</ref>\n\n===Medical achievements===\n[[File:President Clinton meets with Dr. Anthony Fauci (14358494424).jpg|thumb|right|President [[Bill Clinton]] visits the NIH in 1995 and hears about the latest advances in HIV/AIDS research from Fauci]]\nFauci has made important scientific observations that contributed to the understanding of regulation of the human immune response, and is recognized for delineating the mechanisms whereby [[Immunosuppression|immunosuppressive]] agents adapt to that response. He developed therapies for formerly fatal diseases such as [[polyarteritis nodosa]], [[granulomatosis with polyangiitis]], and [[lymphomatoid granulomatosis]]. In a 1985 [[Stanford University]] Arthritis Center Survey of the American Rheumatism Association, membership ranked Fauci's work on the treatment of polyarteritis nodosa and granulomatosis with polyangiitis as one of the most important advances in patient management in [[rheumatology]] over the previous 20 years.<ref name=\"Holy Cross\">Holy Cross Magazine [http://www.holycross.edu/departments/publicaffairs/hcm/summer02/features/fauci_sidebar.html Anthony S. Fauci, M.D., \u201962] Retrieved on May 30, 2007</ref><ref name=\"AACC Lectureship Award 1998\">{{cite web |title=1998 AACC Lectureship Award |url=https://www.aacc.org/Community/Awards/Hall-of-Fame/Bios/A-to-K/Anthony-Fauci.aspx |publisher=American Association for Clinical Chemistry |accessdate=30 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180102191524/https://www.aacc.org/Community/Awards/Hall-of-Fame/Bios/A-to-K/Anthony-Fauci.aspx|archivedate=2 January 2018}}</ref>\n[[File:President Obama greets Dr Anthony Fauci 9203044910 l (14352845344).jpg|thumb|President [[Barack Obama]] greets Fauci in June 2014]]\nFauci has contributed to the understanding of how [[HIV]] destroys the body's defenses leading to the progression to [[AIDS]]. He has outlined the mechanisms of induction of HIV expression by endogenous [[cytokine]]s.<ref name=\"AACC Lectureship Award 1998\" /> Fauci has worked to develop strategies for the therapy and immune reconstitution of patients with the disease, as well as for a [[vaccine]] to prevent HIV infection. His current research is concentrated on identifying the nature of the immunopathogenic mechanisms of HIV infection and the scope of the body's immune responses to HIV.\n\nIn 2003, the [[Institute for Scientific Information]] stated that from 1983 to 2002, \"Fauci was the 13th most-cited scientist among the 2.5 to 3 million authors in all disciplines throughout the world who published articles in scientific journals\".<ref name=\"NIAID\"/>\n\n=== Ebola Congressional hearing ===\n{{See also|Ebola virus cases in the United States}}\n\nOn October 16, 2014, in a United States Congressional hearing regarding the [[Ebola virus]] crisis, Fauci, who, as the director of the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases (NIAID) had been discussing the importance of screening for weeks,<ref>[https://www.usnews.com/news/politics/articles/2014/10/06/more-ebola-screening-possible-for-united-states Officials eyeing additional screening for Ebola in US, vow to protect citizens from disease]. Associated Press. 6 October 2014.  Retrieved 16 October 2014.</ref> testified that NIAID was still some distance away from producing sufficient quantities of cures or vaccines for widespread trials.<ref name=\"Guardian Ebola Hearing\">Roberts, Dan. [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/16/ebola-congress-hearing-cdc-director &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; News World news  Ebola  CDC director warns Ebola like 'forest fire' as Congress readies for hearing] \u2013 Ebola crisis live updates. ''The Guardian''. Retrieved 16 October 2014.</ref> Specifically, Fauci said \"While NIAID is an active participant in the global effort to address the public health emergency occurring in west Africa, it is important to recognize that we are still in the early stages of understanding how infection with the Ebola virus can be treated and prevented.\" <ref name=\"Guardian Ebola Hearing\" />\n\nFauci also remarked in the hearing: \"As we continue to expedite research while enforcing high safety and efficacy standards, the implementation of the public health measures already known to contain prior Ebola virus outbreaks and the implementation of treatment strategies such as fluid and electrolyte replacement are essential to preventing additional infections, treating those already infected, protecting healthcare providers, and ultimately bringing this epidemic to an end.\"<ref name=\"Guardian Ebola Hearing\"/>\n\n===COVID-19 task force===\n[[File:White House Press Briefing (49483222101).jpg|thumb|Fauci speaks to the [[White House]] press corps on [[COVID-19]] in March 2020]]\nFauci is a member of the [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] established in late January 2020, under [[President Trump]], to deal with the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=WhatWeKnow>{{cite news |url= https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/02/27/coronavirus-what-we-know-mike-pence-and-task-force/4891905002/ |work= USA Today |accessdate= March 15, 2020 |title= What we know about the White House coronavirus task force now that Mike Pence is in charge |author= Santucci, Jeanine |date= February 27, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"scimag-22mar2020\">{{cite news |last1=Cohen |first1=Jon |title='I'm going to keep pushing.' Anthony Fauci tries to make the White House listen to facts of the pandemic |url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/03/i-m-going-keep-pushing-anthony-fauci-tries-make-white-house-listen-facts-pandemic |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=[[Science Magazine]] |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> He said that the final [[case fatality rate]] of those who are infected will likely be closer to 1% than the 2% initially estimated by the [[World Health Organization]], which is ten times the 0.1% reported rate for seasonal flu.<ref>Higgins-Dunn, Noah; Lovelace, Berkely, Jr., [https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/11/top-federal-health-official-says-coronavirus-outbreak-is-going-to-get-worse-in-the-us.html \"Top US health official says the coronavirus is 10 times 'more lethal' than the seasonal flu\"], ''[[CNBC]]'', March 11, 2020.</ref><ref>McCormack, John, [https://www.nationalreview.com/corner/coronavirus-vs-the-flu-the-difference-between-a-1-and-0-1-fatality-rate-is-huge/ \"Coronavirus vs. the Flu: The Difference Between a 1% and 0.1% Fatality Rate Is Huge\"], ''[[National Review]]'', March 14, 2020.</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Haberman |first1=Maggie |title=Trump Has Given Unusual Leeway to Fauci, but Aides Say He's Losing His Patience |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/23/us/politics/coronavirus-trump-fauci.html?campaign_id=9&emc=edit_NN_p_20200324&instance_id=17020&nl=morning-briefing&regi_id=104839084&section=topNews&segment_id=22704&te=1&user_id=c001b63136aba3268ed514b0835032af |website=The New York Times |accessdate=24 March 2020 |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nFauci has been a \"de facto\" public health spokesperson for the office of the President during the pandemic<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/5-reasons-gov-cuomo-and-dr-fauci-are-americas-de-facto-leaders-during-the-coronavirus-pandemic-2020-03-30|title=5 reasons Gov. Cuomo and Dr. Fauci are America's de facto leaders during the coronavirus pandemic|last=Smith|first=Virginia K.|website=MarketWatch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> and strong advocate of ongoing social distancing efforts in the United States. He argued for the extension of the initial 15-day self-isolation guidelines, issued by the executive office, to at least until the end of April 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://time.com/5812439/trump-coronavirus-measures-fauci/|title=President Trump's Advisors 'Argued Strongly' Against Easing Coronavirus Measures Too Early, Anthony Fauci Says|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> Due to his blunt assessment of the gravity of the pandemic in the United States, Fauci was criticized by a small group of the President's supporters and had even received an increase in death threats that resulted in the need of security detail for his protection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/media/490763-fauci-dismisses-death-threats-its-my-job|title=Fauci dismisses death threats: 'It's my job'|last=Budryk|first=Zack|date=2020-04-02|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/01/politics/anthony-fauci-security-detail/index.html|title=Nation's top coronavirus expert Dr. Anthony Fauci forced to beef up security as death threats increase|last=CNN|first=Kate Bennett and Evan Perez|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n==Memberships==\nFauci is a member of the [[United States National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Sciences]], the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]], the [[National Academy of Medicine]], the [[American Philosophical Society]], and the [[Royal Danish Academy of Sciences and Letters]], as well as other numerous professional societies including the [[American Society for Clinical Investigation]], the [[Infectious Diseases Society of America]], and the [[American Association of Immunologists]]. He serves on the editorial boards of many scientific journals; as an editor of ''[[Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine]]''; and as author, coauthor, or editor of more than 1,000 scientific publications, including several textbooks.<ref name=\"Cited\">Highly Cited [http://hcr3.isiknowledge.com/author.cgi?id=366&cb=7149 Biography] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929120428/http://hcr3.isiknowledge.com/author.cgi?id=366&cb=7149 |date=September 29, 2007 }} Retrieved May 30, 2007</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFauci married [[Christine Grady]], a nurse with the NIH, in 1985, after meeting while treating a patient. Grady is chief of the Department of Bioethics at the [[National Institutes of Health Clinical Center]]. The couple has three adult daughters: Jennifer, Megan, and Alison.<ref name=\"Heavy31320\">{{cite news |last1=Laviola |first1=Erin |title=Christine Grady, Anthony Fauci's Wife: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know |url=https://heavy.com/news/2020/03/christine-grady-anthony-fauci-wife/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Heavy.com |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Merchandise ==\nOn March 31, 2020, [[CNN]] published an article on its website about how because of Fauci's increased visibility due to his role in the federal government response to the COVID-19 pandemic, some businesses have put Fauci's face on objects available for purchase by the public, including but not limited to cupcakes, doughnuts, and prayer candles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/31/us/dr-fauci-cupcakes-doughnuts-socks-trnd/index.html|title=From cupcakes to candles, you can now find Dr. Anthony Fauci's face on everything|first=Alaa |last=Elassar|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n[[File:Ben Carson and Anthony Fauci.jpg|right|thumb|[[Ben Carson]] and Anthony Fauci (right) being announced as recipients of the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] at the [[White House]] on June 19, 2008.]]\n* 1979: [[Arthur S. Flemming Award]]<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2020-04-02|title=Press Release Archive: Twelve Outstanding Public Servants Representing the Best and Brightest in Federal Government to be Honored at 53rd Annual Arthur S. Flemming Awards Presented by GW June 11|url=https://www2.gwu.edu/~media/pressreleases/06-06-02-FlemmingAdvisory.htm|website=www2.gwu.edu}}</ref>\n* 1995: [[Ernst Jung Prize]] (shared with Samuel A. Wells, Jr.)<ref>{{cite web|title=All Laureates \u2013 English|url=http://www.jung-stiftung.de/en/die-jung-stiftung-1/ernst-jung-preis-fuer-medizin/alle-preistraeger|publisher=Jung Foundation for Science and Research|accessdate=4 November 2016}}</ref>\n* 1996: Honorary Doctor of Science, [[Colgate University]], for pioneering observations of human immune response and pursuit of an AIDS vaccine<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www4.colgate.edu/scene/july1996/honorary-degrees.html | title=Honoris causa|website=Colgate University}}</ref>\n* 1999: Honorary Doctor of Public Service Degree, [[Shippensburg University of Pennsylvania]]\n* 2002: [[Albany Medical Center Prize]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Lawrence K. Altman |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/03/28/us/aids-researcher-fauci-wins-prize.html |title=AIDS Researcher Fauci Wins Prize  |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2002-03-28 |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* 2003: [[American Academy of Achievement]]'s Golden Plate Award <ref name = AAA>{{cite web|title= Anthony S. Fauci, M.D. Biography and Interview |website=achievement.org|publisher=[[American Academy of Achievement]]|url=https://www.achievement.org/achiever/anthony-s-fauci-m-d/#interview}}</ref>\n* 2005: [[National Medal of Science]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nsf.gov/od/nms/recip_details.jsp?recip_id=5300000000430 |title=The President's National Medal of Science: Recipient Details  |publisher=[[National Science Foundation]] |date=2007-07-27 |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* 2005: [[American Association of Immunologists Lifetime Achievement Award]]<ref name=\"Winners\">{{cite web | title=Past Recipients | website=The American Association of Immunologists | url=https://www.aai.org/Awards/Career-Awards/AAI-Lifetime-Achievement-Award/Past-Recipients.aspx | access-date=19 September 2018}}</ref>\n* 2007: [[Mary Woodard Lasker Public Service Award]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Altman|first1=Lawrence K.|title=4 Winners of Lasker Medical Prize|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/16/health/16lasker.html?ref=us|work=The New York Times|date=16 September 2007}}</ref>\n* 2008: [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]]<ref name = AAA/>\n* 2013: [[Robert Koch Gold Medal]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.robert-koch-stiftung.de/index.php?article_id=81&clang=1|title=Robert Koch Stiftung - Anthony S. Fauci|website=www.robert-koch-stiftung.de}}</ref>\n* 2013: [[Prince Mahidol Award]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.princemahidolaward.org/people/dr-anthony-fauci/|title=Dr. Anthony Fauci|date=November 21, 2013|website=Prince Mahidol Award Foundation}}</ref>\n* 2016: [[John Dirks Canada Gairdner Global Health Award]]<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(16)30050-2/abstract|title=NIAID director wins Canada Gairdner Global Health Award|first=Brian|last=Owens|date=March 26, 2016|journal=The Lancet|volume=387|issue=10025|pages=1261|via=www.thelancet.com|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(16)30050-2|pmid=27017308}}</ref>\n\nFauci has been a visiting professor at many medical centers, and has received 30 honorary doctorate degrees from universities in the United States and abroad.<ref name=\"Cited\"/>\n\n==Selected publications==\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 769625 | volume=84 | issue=3 | title=Glucocorticosteroid therapy: mechanisms of action and clinical considerations | date=March 1976 |vauthors=Fauci AS, Dale DC, Balow JE | journal=Ann. Intern. Med. | pages=304\u201315 | doi=10.7326/0003-4819-84-3-304}}\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 31121 | volume=89 | issue=5 Pt 1 | title=The spectrum of vasculitis: clinical, pathologic, immunologic and therapeutic considerations | date=November 1978 |vauthors=Fauci AS, Haynes B, Katz P | journal=Ann. Intern. Med. | pages=660\u201376 | doi = 10.7326/0003-4819-89-5-660}}\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 6336643 | volume=98 | issue=1 | title=Wegener's granulomatosis: prospective clinical and therapeutic experience with 85 patients for 21 years | date=January 1983 |vauthors=Fauci AS, Haynes BF, Katz P, Wolff SM | journal=Ann. Intern. Med. | pages=76\u201385 | doi=10.7326/0003-4819-98-1-76}}\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 6318629 | volume=100 | issue=1 | title=NIH conference. Acquired immunodeficiency syndrome: epidemiologic, clinical, immunologic, and therapeutic considerations | date=January 1984 |author1=Fauci AS |author2=Macher AM |author3=Longo DL  |display-authors=etal| journal=Ann. Intern. Med. | pages=92\u2013106 | doi=10.7326/0003-4819-100-1-92}}\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 3277274 | volume=239 | issue=4840 | title=The human immunodeficiency virus: infectivity and mechanisms of pathogenesis | date=February 1988 | author=Fauci AS | journal=Science | pages=617\u201322 | doi=10.1126/science.3277274| bibcode=1988Sci...239..617F }}\n* {{cite journal |vauthors=Pantaleo G, Graziosi C, Fauci AS | date = Feb 1993 | title = New concepts in the immunopathogenesis of human immunodeficiency virus infection | journal = N Engl J Med | volume = 328 | issue = 5| pages = 327\u201335 | doi = 10.1056/NEJM199302043280508 | pmid = 8093551 }}\n* {{cite journal |vauthors=Fauci AS | date = 12 December 1996 | title = Host Factors and the Pathogenesis of HIV-induced Disease | journal = Nature | volume = 384 | issue = 6609| pages = 529\u2013534 | doi = 10.1038/384529a0 | pmid = 8955267 | bibcode = 1996Natur.384..529F | url = https://zenodo.org/record/1233194 }}\n* {{cite journal |vauthors=Morens DM, Folkers GK, Fauci AS | date = Jul 2004 | title = The challenge of emerging and re-emerging infectious diseases | journal = Nature | volume = 430 | issue = 6996| pages = 242\u201349 | doi = 10.1038/nature02759 | pmid = 15241422 | pmc = 7094993 | bibcode = 2004Natur.430..242M }}\n* {{cite journal |vauthors=Johnston MI, Fauci AS | date = Aug 2008 | title = An HIV vaccine \u2013 challenges and prospects | journal = N Engl J Med | volume = 359 | issue = 9| pages = 888\u201390 | doi = 10.1056/NEJMp0806162 | pmid = 18753644 }}\n* Fauci AS, Braunwald E, Kasper DL, Hauser SL, Longo DL, Jameson JL, Loscalzo J, eds. [http://www.accessmedicine.com/resourceTOC.aspx?resourceID=4 Harrison's principles of internal medicine, 17th ed.] New York: McGraw-Hill Medical, 2008. {{ISBN|978-0-07-159991-7}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline}}\n{{Scholia|author}}\n*Nicholas, Peter, [https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2020/03/anthony-fauci-covid-19-trump-and-staying-healthy/608554/ \"Anthony Fauci\u2019s Plan to Stay Honest\"], ''[[The Atlantic]]'', 22 March 2020.  Interview with Fauci.\n*{{C-SPAN}}\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/?term= Publications] listed on [[PubMed]]\n\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Biography}}\n\n{{Winners of the National Medal of Science|biological}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fauci, Anthony F.}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:American immunologists]]\n[[Category:American medical researchers]]\n[[Category:American people of Campanian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Sicilian descent]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:American scientists of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:College of the Holy Cross alumni]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS researchers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States National Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:National Institutes of Health people]]\n[[Category:National Medal of Science laureates]]\n[[Category:Presidential Medal of Freedom recipients]]\n[[Category:Regis High School (New York City) alumni]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Weill Cornell Medical College alumni]]\n[[Category:White House Coronavirus Task Force]]\n[[Category:American people of Swiss-Italian descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protect|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American immunologist}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name = Anthony Fauci\n|honorific-suffix = [[Doctor of Medicine|MD]]\n|image = Anthony S. Fauci, M.D., NIAID Director (26759498706).jpg\n|caption =Fauci in 2007\n|office = Director of the [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]]\n|president = [[Ronald Reagan]]<br>[[George H.W. Bush]]<br>[[Bill Clinton]]<br>[[George W. Bush]]<br>[[Barack Obama]]<br>[[Donald Trump]]\n|term_start = November 2, 1984\n|term_end = \n|predecessor = [[Richard M. Krause]]\n|successor = \n|birth_name = Anthony Stephen Fauci\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1940|12|24}}\n|birth_place = [[New York City]], U.S.\n|death_date = \n|death_place = \n|education = [[College of the Holy Cross]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br>[[Cornell University]] ([[Doctor of Medicine|MD]])\n|spouse = {{marriage|[[Christine Grady]]|1985}}\n|children = 3\n|awards = [[Maxwell Finland Award]] (1989)<br/>[[Ernst Jung Prize]] (1995)<br/>[[Lasker Award]] (2007)<br/>[[Presidential Medal of Freedom|Medal of Freedom]] (2008)<br/>[[Robert Koch Prize]] (Gold, 2013)\n|module = {{infobox scientist\n|embed = yes\n|fields = [[Immunology]]\n|workplaces = [[National Institutes of Health]], [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]]}}\n}}\n'''Anthony Stephen Fauci''' ({{IPAc-en|pron|\u02c8|f|a\u028a|t\u0283|i|}}; born December 24, 1940) is an American physician and [[Immunology|immunologist]] who has served as the director of the [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]] (NIAID) since 1984. Since January 2020, he has been one of the lead members of the [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] addressing the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|in the United States]].\n\nAs a physician with the [[National Institutes of Health]] (NIH) of the United States, he has served public health in various capacities for over fifty years. He has made contributions to [[HIV/AIDS research]] and other immunodeficiencies, both as a scientist and as the head of the NIAID at the NIH. ''The New York Times'' called Fauci \"the nation's leading expert on infectious diseases\".<ref name=Grady>Grady, Denise, [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/08/health/fauci-coronavirus.html?searchResultPosition=1 \"Not His First Epidemic: Dr. Anthony Fauci Sticks to the Facts\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', March 8, 11, 2020.</ref>\n\n==Background and education==\n[[File:VOA Interview Dr. Anthony S. Fauci.webm|thumb|left|alt=Gray haired man wearing a tie and a medium blue oxford button down shirt, seated in front of framed press clippings and awards, interviewed by medium-length blond-haired female interviewer about age 60, wearing a gray suit and yellow blouse| [[Greta Van Susteren]] interviewed Fauci in 2018 (38:18 minutes)]]\nFauci was born December 24, 1940, in [[Brooklyn]], New York, to Stephen A. Fauci and Eugenia A. Fauci, owners of a pharmacy, where his father worked as the [[pharmacist]], his mother and sister worked the register, and Fauci delivered prescriptions.<ref name=MedalBio/> The pharmacy was located in the [[Dyker Heights]] section of Brooklyn.\n\nFauci's paternal grandparents, Antonino Fauci and Calogera Guardino, were from [[Sciacca]], Italy. His maternal grandmother, Raffaella Trematerra, from [[Naples]], Italy, was a seamstress.  His maternal grandfather, Giovanni Abys, was born in Switzerland and was an artist, noted for landscape and portrait painting, magazine illustrations (Italy) as well graphic design for commercial labels, including olive oil cans. His great-grandparents emigrated to the US in the late 19th century. Fauci grew up [[Catholic]].<ref name=MedalBio>{{cite journal|last1=Gallin|first1=John I.|title=Introduction of Anthony S. Fauci, MD|journal=Journal of Clinical Investigation|date=1 October 2007|volume=117|issue=10|pages=3131\u20133135|pmid=17909634|pmc=1994641|doi=10.1172/jci33692}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Fauci89: Transcription of oral history interview |url=http://history.nih.gov/NIHInOwnWords/assets/media/pdf/Fauci89.pdf |publisher=NIH |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409183210/https://history.nih.gov/NIHInOwnWords/assets/media/pdf/Fauci89.pdf |archivedate=April 9, 2016 |date=March 7, 1989}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://history.nih.gov/nihinownwords/docs/fauci2_01.html|title=In Their Own Words|website=history.nih.gov}}</ref>\n\nFauci attended [[Regis High School (New York City)|Regis High School]] in [[New York City]] where he graduated in 1958. He then enrolled at the [[College of the Holy Cross]] where he received a [[Bachelor of Science|BS]] in [[classics]] in 1962. Fauci then went on to attend [[Weill Cornell Medical College of Cornell University|Cornell University Medical College]] where he graduated first in his class with an [[Doctor of Medicine|MD]] in 1966.<ref name=MedalBio/> He then completed an internship and [[Residency (medicine)|residency]] at The [[New York Hospital-Cornell Medical Center]].<ref name=\"NIAID\">{{cite web|title=Biography Anthony S. Fauci, M.D. NIAID Director|url=http://www3.niaid.nih.gov/about/directors/biography/|publisher=NIAID|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071030171118/http://www3.niaid.nih.gov/about/directors/biography/|archivedate=October 30, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Dr Anthony Fauci-America's Man on Infectious Diseases-VoA.webm|thumb|left|alt=Gray haired man in wearing a suit and seated on a chair in a lab, mixed with shots of female coworkers working with laboratory equipment|Fauci discusses his work in 2020 (4 minutes)]]\nIn 1968, Fauci joined the National Institutes of Health as a clinical associate in the Laboratory of Clinical Investigation (LCI) at the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases.<ref name=\"pr1984\"/> In 1974, he became Head of the Clinical Physiology Section, LCI, and in 1980 was appointed Chief of the Laboratory of Immunoregulation. In 1984, he became Director of NIAID, a position which he was still holding in 2020.<ref name = Grady/> In that role he has the responsibility for an extensive research portfolio of basic and applied research on infectious and immune-mediated illnesses.<ref name=\"pr1984\">{{cite web |title=Dr. Anthony Fauci Named New NIAID Director |url=https://history.nih.gov/nihinownwords/assets/media/pdf/press/1984/PR_NIAID_1984_11_02.pdf |website=HHS News |accessdate=13 March 2020 |format=Press release |date=2 November 1984}}</ref> He has turned down several offers to lead his agency's parent, the NIH, and has been at the forefront of US efforts to contend with viral diseases like HIV, [[SARS]], the [[2009 swine flu pandemic]], [[MERS]], [[Ebola]] and the new coronavirus, [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Grady |first1=Denise |title=Not His First Epidemic: Dr. Anthony Fauci Sticks to the Facts |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/08/health/fauci-coronavirus.html |work=The New York Times |publisher=New York Times Company |date=8 March 2020 |location=New York}}</ref>\n\nHe played a significant role in the early 2000s in creating the [[President's Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief]]<ref>{{cite journal|last=Varmus|first=Harold|title=Making PEPFAR|journal=Science & Diplomacy|date=1 December 2013 |volume=2|issue=4|url=http://www.sciencediplomacy.org/article/2013/making-pepfar}}</ref> and in driving development of [[biodefense]] drugs and vaccines following the [[September 11 attacks|9/11 terrorist attacks]].<ref>Bernard Wysocki Jr for The Wall Street Journal. December 6, 2005 [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB113383825463714813 Agency Chief Spurs Bioterror Research \u2013 And Controversy]</ref>\n\n===Medical achievements===\n[[File:President Clinton meets with Dr. Anthony Fauci (14358494424).jpg|thumb|right|President [[Bill Clinton]] visits the NIH in 1995 and hears about the latest advances in HIV/AIDS research from Fauci]]\nFauci has made important scientific observations that contributed to the understanding of regulation of the human immune response, and is recognized for delineating the mechanisms whereby [[Immunosuppression|immunosuppressive]] agents adapt to that response. He developed therapies for formerly fatal diseases such as [[polyarteritis nodosa]], [[granulomatosis with polyangiitis]], and [[lymphomatoid granulomatosis]]. In a 1985 [[Stanford University]] Arthritis Center Survey of the American Rheumatism Association, membership ranked Fauci's work on the treatment of polyarteritis nodosa and granulomatosis with polyangiitis as one of the most important advances in patient management in [[rheumatology]] over the previous 20 years.<ref name=\"Holy Cross\">Holy Cross Magazine [http://www.holycross.edu/departments/publicaffairs/hcm/summer02/features/fauci_sidebar.html Anthony S. Fauci, M.D., \u201962] Retrieved on May 30, 2007</ref><ref name=\"AACC Lectureship Award 1998\">{{cite web |title=1998 AACC Lectureship Award |url=https://www.aacc.org/Community/Awards/Hall-of-Fame/Bios/A-to-K/Anthony-Fauci.aspx |publisher=American Association for Clinical Chemistry |accessdate=30 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180102191524/https://www.aacc.org/Community/Awards/Hall-of-Fame/Bios/A-to-K/Anthony-Fauci.aspx|archivedate=2 January 2018}}</ref>\n[[File:President Obama greets Dr Anthony Fauci 9203044910 l (14352845344).jpg|thumb|President [[Barack Obama]] greets Fauci in June 2014]]\nFauci has contributed to the understanding of how [[HIV]] destroys the body's defenses leading to the progression to [[AIDS]]. He has outlined the mechanisms of induction of HIV expression by endogenous [[cytokine]]s.<ref name=\"AACC Lectureship Award 1998\" /> Fauci has worked to develop strategies for the therapy and immune reconstitution of patients with the disease, as well as for a [[vaccine]] to prevent HIV infection. His current research is concentrated on identifying the nature of the immunopathogenic mechanisms of HIV infection and the scope of the body's immune responses to HIV.\n\nIn 2003, the [[Institute for Scientific Information]] stated that from 1983 to 2002, \"Fauci was the 13th most-cited scientist among the 2.5 to 3 million authors in all disciplines throughout the world who published articles in scientific journals\".<ref name=\"NIAID\"/>\n\n=== Ebola Congressional hearing ===\n{{See also|Ebola virus cases in the United States}}\n\nOn October 16, 2014, in a United States Congressional hearing regarding the [[Ebola virus]] crisis, Fauci, who, as the director of the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases (NIAID) had been discussing the importance of screening for weeks,<ref>[https://www.usnews.com/news/politics/articles/2014/10/06/more-ebola-screening-possible-for-united-states Officials eyeing additional screening for Ebola in US, vow to protect citizens from disease]. Associated Press. 6 October 2014.  Retrieved 16 October 2014.</ref> testified that NIAID was still some distance away from producing sufficient quantities of cures or vaccines for widespread trials.<ref name=\"Guardian Ebola Hearing\">Roberts, Dan. [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/16/ebola-congress-hearing-cdc-director &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; News World news  Ebola  CDC director warns Ebola like 'forest fire' as Congress readies for hearing] \u2013 Ebola crisis live updates. ''The Guardian''. Retrieved 16 October 2014.</ref> Specifically, Fauci said \"While NIAID is an active participant in the global effort to address the public health emergency occurring in west Africa, it is important to recognize that we are still in the early stages of understanding how infection with the Ebola virus can be treated and prevented.\" <ref name=\"Guardian Ebola Hearing\" />\n\nFauci also remarked in the hearing: \"As we continue to expedite research while enforcing high safety and efficacy standards, the implementation of the public health measures already known to contain prior Ebola virus outbreaks and the implementation of treatment strategies such as fluid and electrolyte replacement are essential to preventing additional infections, treating those already infected, protecting healthcare providers, and ultimately bringing this epidemic to an end.\"<ref name=\"Guardian Ebola Hearing\"/>\n\n===COVID-19 task force===\n[[File:White House Press Briefing (49483222101).jpg|thumb|Fauci speaks to the [[White House]] press corps on [[COVID-19]] in March 2020]]\nFauci is a member of the [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] established in late January 2020, under [[President Trump]], to deal with the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=WhatWeKnow>{{cite news |url= https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/02/27/coronavirus-what-we-know-mike-pence-and-task-force/4891905002/ |work= USA Today |accessdate= March 15, 2020 |title= What we know about the White House coronavirus task force now that Mike Pence is in charge |author= Santucci, Jeanine |date= February 27, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"scimag-22mar2020\">{{cite news |last1=Cohen |first1=Jon |title='I'm going to keep pushing.' Anthony Fauci tries to make the White House listen to facts of the pandemic |url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/03/i-m-going-keep-pushing-anthony-fauci-tries-make-white-house-listen-facts-pandemic |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=[[Science Magazine]] |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> He said that the final [[case fatality rate]] of those who are infected will likely be closer to 1% than the 2% initially estimated by the [[World Health Organization]], which is ten times the 0.1% reported rate for seasonal flu.<ref>Higgins-Dunn, Noah; Lovelace, Berkely, Jr., [https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/11/top-federal-health-official-says-coronavirus-outbreak-is-going-to-get-worse-in-the-us.html \"Top US health official says the coronavirus is 10 times 'more lethal' than the seasonal flu\"], ''[[CNBC]]'', March 11, 2020.</ref><ref>McCormack, John, [https://www.nationalreview.com/corner/coronavirus-vs-the-flu-the-difference-between-a-1-and-0-1-fatality-rate-is-huge/ \"Coronavirus vs. the Flu: The Difference Between a 1% and 0.1% Fatality Rate Is Huge\"], ''[[National Review]]'', March 14, 2020.</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Haberman |first1=Maggie |title=Trump Has Given Unusual Leeway to Fauci, but Aides Say He's Losing His Patience |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/23/us/politics/coronavirus-trump-fauci.html?campaign_id=9&emc=edit_NN_p_20200324&instance_id=17020&nl=morning-briefing&regi_id=104839084&section=topNews&segment_id=22704&te=1&user_id=c001b63136aba3268ed514b0835032af |website=The New York Times |accessdate=24 March 2020 |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nFauci has been a \"de facto\" public health spokesperson for the office of the President during the pandemic<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/5-reasons-gov-cuomo-and-dr-fauci-are-americas-de-facto-leaders-during-the-coronavirus-pandemic-2020-03-30|title=5 reasons Gov. Cuomo and Dr. Fauci are America's de facto leaders during the coronavirus pandemic|last=Smith|first=Virginia K.|website=MarketWatch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> and strong advocate of ongoing social distancing efforts in the United States. He argued for the extension of the initial 15-day self-isolation guidelines, issued by the executive office, to at least until the end of April 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://time.com/5812439/trump-coronavirus-measures-fauci/|title=President Trump's Advisors 'Argued Strongly' Against Easing Coronavirus Measures Too Early, Anthony Fauci Says|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> Due to his blunt assessment of the gravity of the pandemic in the United States, Fauci was criticized by a small group of the President's supporters and had even received an increase in death threats that resulted in the need of security detail for his protection.\n\n==Memberships==\nFauci is a member of the [[United States National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Sciences]], the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]], the [[National Academy of Medicine]], the [[American Philosophical Society]], and the [[Royal Danish Academy of Sciences and Letters]], as well as other numerous professional societies including the [[American Society for Clinical Investigation]], the [[Infectious Diseases Society of America]], and the [[American Association of Immunologists]]. He serves on the editorial boards of many scientific journals; as an editor of ''[[Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine]]''; and as author, coauthor, or editor of more than 1,000 scientific publications, including several textbooks.<ref name=\"Cited\">Highly Cited [http://hcr3.isiknowledge.com/author.cgi?id=366&cb=7149 Biography] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929120428/http://hcr3.isiknowledge.com/author.cgi?id=366&cb=7149 |date=September 29, 2007 }} Retrieved May 30, 2007</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFauci married [[Christine Grady]], a nurse with the NIH, in 1985, after meeting while treating a patient. Grady is chief of the Department of Bioethics at the [[National Institutes of Health Clinical Center]]. The couple has three adult daughters: Jennifer, Megan, and Alison.<ref name=\"Heavy31320\">{{cite news |last1=Laviola |first1=Erin |title=Christine Grady, Anthony Fauci's Wife: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know |url=https://heavy.com/news/2020/03/christine-grady-anthony-fauci-wife/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Heavy.com |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Merchandise ==\nOn March 31, 2020, [[CNN]] published an article on its website about how because of Fauci's increased visibility due to his role in the federal government response to the COVID-19 pandemic, some businesses have put Fauci's face on objects available for purchase by the public, including but not limited to cupcakes, doughnuts, and prayer candles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/31/us/dr-fauci-cupcakes-doughnuts-socks-trnd/index.html|title=From cupcakes to candles, you can now find Dr. Anthony Fauci's face on everything|first=Alaa |last=Elassar|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n[[File:Ben Carson and Anthony Fauci.jpg|right|thumb|[[Ben Carson]] and Anthony Fauci (right) being announced as recipients of the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] at the [[White House]] on June 19, 2008.]]\n* 1979: [[Arthur S. Flemming Award]]<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2020-04-02|title=Press Release Archive: Twelve Outstanding Public Servants Representing the Best and Brightest in Federal Government to be Honored at 53rd Annual Arthur S. Flemming Awards Presented by GW June 11|url=https://www2.gwu.edu/~media/pressreleases/06-06-02-FlemmingAdvisory.htm|website=www2.gwu.edu}}</ref>\n* 1995: [[Ernst Jung Prize]] (shared with Samuel A. Wells, Jr.)<ref>{{cite web|title=All Laureates \u2013 English|url=http://www.jung-stiftung.de/en/die-jung-stiftung-1/ernst-jung-preis-fuer-medizin/alle-preistraeger|publisher=Jung Foundation for Science and Research|accessdate=4 November 2016}}</ref>\n* 1996: Honorary Doctor of Science, [[Colgate University]], for pioneering observations of human immune response and pursuit of an AIDS vaccine<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www4.colgate.edu/scene/july1996/honorary-degrees.html | title=Honoris causa|website=Colgate University}}</ref>\n* 1999: Honorary Doctor of Public Service Degree, [[Shippensburg University of Pennsylvania]]\n* 2002: [[Albany Medical Center Prize]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Lawrence K. Altman |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/03/28/us/aids-researcher-fauci-wins-prize.html |title=AIDS Researcher Fauci Wins Prize  |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2002-03-28 |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* 2003: [[American Academy of Achievement]]'s Golden Plate Award <ref name = AAA>{{cite web|title= Anthony S. Fauci, M.D. Biography and Interview |website=achievement.org|publisher=[[American Academy of Achievement]]|url=https://www.achievement.org/achiever/anthony-s-fauci-m-d/#interview}}</ref>\n* 2005: [[National Medal of Science]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nsf.gov/od/nms/recip_details.jsp?recip_id=5300000000430 |title=The President's National Medal of Science: Recipient Details  |publisher=[[National Science Foundation]] |date=2007-07-27 |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n* 2005: [[American Association of Immunologists Lifetime Achievement Award]]<ref name=\"Winners\">{{cite web | title=Past Recipients | website=The American Association of Immunologists | url=https://www.aai.org/Awards/Career-Awards/AAI-Lifetime-Achievement-Award/Past-Recipients.aspx | access-date=19 September 2018}}</ref>\n* 2007: [[Mary Woodard Lasker Public Service Award]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Altman|first1=Lawrence K.|title=4 Winners of Lasker Medical Prize|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/16/health/16lasker.html?ref=us|work=The New York Times|date=16 September 2007}}</ref>\n* 2008: [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]]<ref name = AAA/>\n* 2013: [[Robert Koch Gold Medal]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.robert-koch-stiftung.de/index.php?article_id=81&clang=1|title=Robert Koch Stiftung - Anthony S. Fauci|website=www.robert-koch-stiftung.de}}</ref>\n* 2013: [[Prince Mahidol Award]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.princemahidolaward.org/people/dr-anthony-fauci/|title=Dr. Anthony Fauci|date=November 21, 2013|website=Prince Mahidol Award Foundation}}</ref>\n* 2016: [[John Dirks Canada Gairdner Global Health Award]]<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(16)30050-2/abstract|title=NIAID director wins Canada Gairdner Global Health Award|first=Brian|last=Owens|date=March 26, 2016|journal=The Lancet|volume=387|issue=10025|pages=1261|via=www.thelancet.com|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(16)30050-2|pmid=27017308}}</ref>\n\nFauci has been a visiting professor at many medical centers, and has received 30 honorary doctorate degrees from universities in the United States and abroad.<ref name=\"Cited\"/>\n\n==Selected publications==\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 769625 | volume=84 | issue=3 | title=Glucocorticosteroid therapy: mechanisms of action and clinical considerations | date=March 1976 |vauthors=Fauci AS, Dale DC, Balow JE | journal=Ann. Intern. Med. | pages=304\u201315 | doi=10.7326/0003-4819-84-3-304}}\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 31121 | volume=89 | issue=5 Pt 1 | title=The spectrum of vasculitis: clinical, pathologic, immunologic and therapeutic considerations | date=November 1978 |vauthors=Fauci AS, Haynes B, Katz P | journal=Ann. Intern. Med. | pages=660\u201376 | doi = 10.7326/0003-4819-89-5-660}}\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 6336643 | volume=98 | issue=1 | title=Wegener's granulomatosis: prospective clinical and therapeutic experience with 85 patients for 21 years | date=January 1983 |vauthors=Fauci AS, Haynes BF, Katz P, Wolff SM | journal=Ann. Intern. Med. | pages=76\u201385 | doi=10.7326/0003-4819-98-1-76}}\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 6318629 | volume=100 | issue=1 | title=NIH conference. Acquired immunodeficiency syndrome: epidemiologic, clinical, immunologic, and therapeutic considerations | date=January 1984 |author1=Fauci AS |author2=Macher AM |author3=Longo DL  |display-authors=etal| journal=Ann. Intern. Med. | pages=92\u2013106 | doi=10.7326/0003-4819-100-1-92}}\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 3277274 | volume=239 | issue=4840 | title=The human immunodeficiency virus: infectivity and mechanisms of pathogenesis | date=February 1988 | author=Fauci AS | journal=Science | pages=617\u201322 | doi=10.1126/science.3277274| bibcode=1988Sci...239..617F }}\n* {{cite journal |vauthors=Pantaleo G, Graziosi C, Fauci AS | date = Feb 1993 | title = New concepts in the immunopathogenesis of human immunodeficiency virus infection | journal = N Engl J Med | volume = 328 | issue = 5| pages = 327\u201335 | doi = 10.1056/NEJM199302043280508 | pmid = 8093551 }}\n* {{cite journal |vauthors=Fauci AS | date = 12 December 1996 | title = Host Factors and the Pathogenesis of HIV-induced Disease | journal = Nature | volume = 384 | issue = 6609| pages = 529\u2013534 | doi = 10.1038/384529a0 | pmid = 8955267 | bibcode = 1996Natur.384..529F | url = https://zenodo.org/record/1233194 }}\n* {{cite journal |vauthors=Morens DM, Folkers GK, Fauci AS | date = Jul 2004 | title = The challenge of emerging and re-emerging infectious diseases | journal = Nature | volume = 430 | issue = 6996| pages = 242\u201349 | doi = 10.1038/nature02759 | pmid = 15241422 | pmc = 7094993 | bibcode = 2004Natur.430..242M }}\n* {{cite journal |vauthors=Johnston MI, Fauci AS | date = Aug 2008 | title = An HIV vaccine \u2013 challenges and prospects | journal = N Engl J Med | volume = 359 | issue = 9| pages = 888\u201390 | doi = 10.1056/NEJMp0806162 | pmid = 18753644 }}\n* Fauci AS, Braunwald E, Kasper DL, Hauser SL, Longo DL, Jameson JL, Loscalzo J, eds. [http://www.accessmedicine.com/resourceTOC.aspx?resourceID=4 Harrison's principles of internal medicine, 17th ed.] New York: McGraw-Hill Medical, 2008. {{ISBN|978-0-07-159991-7}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline}}\n{{Scholia|author}}\n*Nicholas, Peter, [https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2020/03/anthony-fauci-covid-19-trump-and-staying-healthy/608554/ \"Anthony Fauci\u2019s Plan to Stay Honest\"], ''[[The Atlantic]]'', 22 March 2020.  Interview with Fauci.\n*{{C-SPAN}}\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/?term= Publications] listed on [[PubMed]]\n\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Biography}}\n\n{{Winners of the National Medal of Science|biological}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fauci, Anthony F.}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:American immunologists]]\n[[Category:American medical researchers]]\n[[Category:American people of Campanian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Sicilian descent]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:American scientists of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:College of the Holy Cross alumni]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS researchers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States National Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:National Institutes of Health people]]\n[[Category:National Medal of Science laureates]]\n[[Category:Presidential Medal of Freedom recipients]]\n[[Category:Regis High School (New York City) alumni]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Weill Cornell Medical College alumni]]\n[[Category:White House Coronavirus Task Force]]\n[[Category:American people of Swiss-Italian descent]]\n", "name_user": "PenulisHantu", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCOVID-19 task force:citations", "url_page": "//en.wiki